{"title_page": "Danny Calegari", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Danny Calegari\n|image             = Danny Calegari.jpg\n|image_size       = \n|caption           = Danny Calegari\n|birth_date        = \n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = \n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Mathematics]]\n|work_institutions = [[University of Chicago]]\n|alma_mater        = [[University of California, Berkeley]]{{br}}[[University of Melbourne]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Andrew Casson]]{{br}}[[William Thurston]]\n|thesis_title      = Foliations and the Geometry of Three-Manifolds\n| thesis_url       =\n| thesis_year      = 2000\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = \n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = \n|footnotes         = Brother of [[Frank Calegari]] \n|signature         =\n}}\n'''Danny Matthew Cornelius Calegari'''  is a mathematician who is currently a professor of mathematics at the [[University of Chicago]]. His research interests include [[geometry]], [[dynamical systems]], [[low-dimensional topology]], and [[geometric group theory]].\n\n==Education and career==\nIn 1994, Calegari received a B.A. in Mathematics from the [[University of Melbourne]] with honors. He received his Ph.D. in 2000 from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] under the joint supervision of [[Andrew Casson]] and [[William Thurston]]; his dissertation concerned [[foliation]]s of three-dimensional [[manifold]]s.<ref>{{mathgenealogy|id=46274|name=\nDanny Matthew Cornelius Calegari}}.</ref>\n\nFrom 2000\u20132002 he was Benjamin Peirce Assistant Professor at [[Harvard University]], after which he joined the [[California Institute of Technology]] faculty; he became Merkin Professor in 2007. He was a University Professor of Pure Mathematics at the [[University of Cambridge]] in 2011\u20132012, and has been a Professor of Mathematics at the University of Chicago since 2012.<ref name=\"cv\">[http://math.uchicago.edu/~dannyc/vita/vita.pdf Calegari's curriculum vitae] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530224919/http://math.uchicago.edu/~dannyc/vita/vita.pdf |date=30 May 2013 }}.</ref> \n\nCalegari is also an author of short fiction, published in ''[[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]]'', ''Southerly'', and ''[[Overland (literary journal)|Overland]]''. His story ''A Green Light'' was a winner of a 1992 [[The Age Short Story Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://math.uchicago.edu/~dannyc/ |title=Danny Calegari |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nCalegari was one of the recipients of the 2009 [[Clay Research Award]] for his solution to the [[Marden tameness conjecture|Marden Tameness Conjecture]] and the [[Ahlfors measure conjecture|Ahlfors Measure Conjecture]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Research Awards {{!}} Clay Mathematics Institute|url = http://www.claymath.org/research|website = www.claymath.org|accessdate = 2015-10-29}}</ref> In 2012, he became a [[Fellow of the American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 2012-11-10.</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*{{cite book | title=Foliations and the geometry of 3-manifolds | series=Oxford Mathematical Monographs | publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] | place=Oxford | year= 2007 | pages=xiv+363 pp. | isbn=978-0-19-857008-0 | mr=2327361}}\n*{{cite book |  title=scl (stable commutator length) | series=MSJ Memoirs | volume=20 | publisher=Mathematical Society of Japan | location= Tokyo | year=2009 | pages= xii+209 pp | isbn=978-4-931469-53-2 | mr=2527432}}\n*{{cite journal | title=<math>\\mathbb R</math>-covered foliations of hyperbolic 3-manifolds | journal=[[Geometry & Topology]] | volume=3 | year=1999 | pages= 137\u2013153 | mr=1695533  | arxiv=math/9808064 | doi=10.2140/gt.1999.3.137}} \n*{{cite journal | last=Calegari | first=Danny | last2=Dunfield | first2=Nathan | title=Laminations and groups of homeomorphisms of the circle | journal=[[Inventiones Mathematicae]] | volume=152 | year=2003 | number= 1 | pages= 149\u2013204 | mr=1965363 | arxiv=math/0203192 | doi=10.1007/s00222-002-0271-6| bibcode=2003InMat.152..149D }}\n*{{cite journal | title=Promoting essential laminations | journal=Inventiones Mathematicae | volume=166 | year=2006 | number=3 | pages= 583\u2013643 | mr=2257392 | arxiv=math/0210148 | doi=10.1007/s00222-006-0004-3| bibcode=2006InMat.166..583C }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Calegari | first=Danny | last2=Gabai|first2=David|authorlink2=David Gabai | title=Shrinkwrapping and the taming of hyperbolic 3-manifolds | journal=[[Journal of the American Mathematical Society]] | volume=19 | year=2006 | number=2 | pages=385\u2013446 | mr=2188131 | arxiv=math/0407161 | doi=10.1090/S0894-0347-05-00513-8}}\n*\"Universal circles for quasigeodesic flows\". ''Geometry & Topology'' '''10''' (2006), 2271-2298.\n*{{cite journal | title=What is stable commutator length? | journal=[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] | volume=55 | year=2008 | number=9 | pages=1100\u20131101 | mr=2451345 | url=http://www.ams.org/notices/200809/tx080901100p.pdf}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMathematician [[Frank Calegari]] is Danny Calegari's brother.<ref name=\"friends\">{{cite web|url=https://math.uchicago.edu/~fcale/friends.html |title=Family, Collaborators, Students |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Google Scholar id | Z9MXmuYAAAAJ }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calegari, Danny M. C.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Australian mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Topologists]]\n[[Category:University of Melbourne alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:California Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Institute for Advanced Study visiting scholars]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Clay Research Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Mathematical Society]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n\n\n{{Australia-scientist-stub}}\n{{mathematician-stub}}\n{{US-mathematician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Danny Calegari\n|image             = Danny Calegari.jpg\n|image_size       = \n|caption           = Danny Calegari\n|birth_date        = \n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = \n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Mathematics]]\n|work_institutions = [[University of Chicago]]\n|alma_mater        = [[University of California, Berkeley]]{{br}}[[University of Melbourne]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Andrew Casson]]{{br}}[[William Thurston]]\n|thesis_title      = Foliations and the Geometry of Three-Manifolds\n| thesis_url       =\n| thesis_year      = 2000\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = \n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = \n|footnotes         = Brother of [[Frank Calegari]] \n|signature         =\n}}\n'''Danny Matthew Cornelius Calegari'''  is a mathematician who is currently a professor of mathematics at the [[University of Chicago]]. His research interests include [[geometry]], [[dynamical systems]], [[low-dimensional topology]], and [[geometric group theory]].\n\n==Education and career==\nIn 1994, Calegari received a B.A. in Mathematics from the [[University of Melbourne]] with honors. He received his Ph.D. in 2000 from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] under the joint supervision of [[Andrew Casson]] and [[William Thurston]]; his dissertation concerned [[foliation]]s of three-dimensional [[manifold]]s.<ref>{{mathgenealogy|id=46274|name=\nDanny Matthew Cornelius Calegari}}.</ref>\n\nFrom 2000\u20132002 he was Benjamin Peirce Assistant Professor at [[Harvard University]], after which he joined the [[California Institute of Technology]] faculty; he became Merkin Professor in 2007. He was a University Professor of Pure Mathematics at the [[University of Cambridge]] in 2011\u20132012, and has been a Professor of Mathematics at the University of Chicago since 2012.<ref name=\"cv\">[http://math.uchicago.edu/~dannyc/vita/vita.pdf Calegari's curriculum vitae] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530224919/http://math.uchicago.edu/~dannyc/vita/vita.pdf |date=30 May 2013 }}.</ref> \n\nCalegari is also an author of short fiction, published in ''[[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]]'', ''Southerly'', and ''[[Overland (literary journal)|Overland]]''. His story ''A Green Light'' was a winner of a 1992 [[The Age Short Story Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://math.uchicago.edu/~dannyc/ |title=Danny Calegari |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nCalegari was one of the recipients of the 2009 [[Clay Research Award]] for his solution to the [[Marden tameness conjecture|Marden Tameness Conjecture]] and the [[Ahlfors measure conjecture|Ahlfors Measure Conjecture]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Research Awards {{!}} Clay Mathematics Institute|url = http://www.claymath.org/research|website = www.claymath.org|accessdate = 2015-10-29}}</ref> In 2012, he became a [[Fellow of the American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 2012-11-10.</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*{{cite book | title=Foliations and the geometry of 3-manifolds | series=Oxford Mathematical Monographs | publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] | place=Oxford | year= 2007 | pages=xiv+363 pp. | isbn=978-0-19-857008-0 | mr=2327361}}\n*{{cite book |  title=scl (stable commutator length) | series=MSJ Memoirs | volume=20 | publisher=Mathematical Society of Japan | location= Tokyo | year=2009 | pages= xii+209 pp | isbn=978-4-931469-53-2 | mr=2527432}}\n*{{cite journal | title=<math>\\mathbb R</math>-covered foliations of hyperbolic 3-manifolds | journal=[[Geometry & Topology]] | volume=3 | year=1999 | pages= 137\u2013153 | mr=1695533  | arxiv=math/9808064 | doi=10.2140/gt.1999.3.137}} \n*{{cite journal | last=Calegari | first=Danny | last2=Dunfield | first2=Nathan | title=Laminations and groups of homeomorphisms of the circle | journal=[[Inventiones Mathematicae]] | volume=152 | year=2003 | number= 1 | pages= 149\u2013204 | mr=1965363 | arxiv=math/0203192 | doi=10.1007/s00222-002-0271-6| bibcode=2003InMat.152..149D }}\n*{{cite journal | title=Promoting essential laminations | journal=Inventiones Mathematicae | volume=166 | year=2006 | number=3 | pages= 583\u2013643 | mr=2257392 | arxiv=math/0210148 | doi=10.1007/s00222-006-0004-3| bibcode=2006InMat.166..583C }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Calegari | first=Danny | last2=Gabai|first2=David|authorlink2=David Gabai | title=Shrinkwrapping and the taming of hyperbolic 3-manifolds | journal=[[Journal of the American Mathematical Society]] | volume=19 | year=2006 | number=2 | pages=385\u2013446 | mr=2188131 | arxiv=math/0407161}}\n*\"Universal circles for quasigeodesic flows\". ''Geometry & Topology'' '''10''' (2006), 2271-2298.\n*{{cite journal | title=What is stable commutator length? | journal=[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] | volume=55 | year=2008 | number=9 | pages=1100\u20131101 | mr=2451345 | url=http://www.ams.org/notices/200809/tx080901100p.pdf}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMathematician [[Frank Calegari]] is Danny Calegari's brother.<ref name=\"friends\">{{cite web|url=https://math.uchicago.edu/~fcale/friends.html |title=Family, Collaborators, Students |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Google Scholar id | Z9MXmuYAAAAJ }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calegari, Danny M. C.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Americ