f the series was that the home team took all 7 game in a series.<ref name=\"Washington Wizards 1963-Present\"/> <br> (2) '''[[Washington Bullets]]''' vs. (3) [[Buffalo Braves]]: ''Bullets win series 4\u20133''\n*'''Game 1''' @ Washington: '''Buffalo 113''', Washington 102\n*'''Game 2''' @ Buffalo: '''Washington 120''', Buffalo 106\n*'''Game 3''' @ Washington: '''Washington 111''', Buffalo 96\n*'''Game 4''' @ Buffalo: '''Buffalo 108''', Washington 102\n*'''Game 5''' @ Washington: '''Washington 97''', Buffalo 93\n*'''Game 6''' @ Buffalo: '''Buffalo 102''', Washington 96\n*'''Game 7''' @ Washington: '''Washington 115''', Buffalo 96\n\n===East Conference Finals===\n(1) [[Boston Celtics]] vs. (2) '''[[Washington Bullets]]''': ''Bullets win series 4\u20132''\n*'''Game 1''' @ Boston: '''Washington 100''', Boston 95\n*'''Game 2''' @ Washington: '''Washington 117''', Boston 92\n*'''Game 3''' @ Boston: '''Boston 101''', Washington 90\n*'''Game 4''' @ Washington: '''Washington 119''', Boston 108\n*'''Game 5''' @ Boston: '''Boston 103''', Washington 99\n*'''Game 6''' @ Washington: '''Washington 98''', Boston 92\n\n===NBA Finals===\nThe Bullets reached the NBA Finals but found themselves swept in 4 straight by the Golden State Warriors, although the Warriors would only win 2 of the 4 games by 1 point.<ref name=\"Washington Wizards 1963-Present\"/>\n\n{{main article|1975 NBA Finals}}\n(E1) [[Washington Bullets]] vs. (W1) '''[[Golden State Warriors]]''': ''Warriors win series 4\u20130''\n*'''Game 1''' @ Washington: '''Golden State 101''', Washington 95\n*'''Game 2''' @ Golden State: '''Golden State 92''', Washington 91\n*'''Game 3''' @ Golden State: '''Golden State 109''', Washington 101\n*'''Game 4''' @ Washington: '''Golden State 96''', Washington 95\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*[[Elvin Hayes]], [[All-NBA First Team]]\n*[[Phil Chenier]], All-NBA Second Team\n*Elvin Hayes, [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1975.html Bullets on Basketball Reference]\n\n{{1974-75 NBA season by team}}\n{{Washington Wizards seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1974-75 Washington Bullets season}}\n[[Category:1974\u201375 NBA season|Washington]]\n[[Category:Washington Wizards seasons]]\n[[Category:Eastern Conference (NBA) championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1974 in sports in Washington, D.C.|Wash]]\n[[Category:1975 in sports in Washington, D.C.|Wash]]\n", "text_old": "{{NBA_season\n| team = Washington Bullets\n| end_year = 1975\n| DivisionWin = yes\n| ConferenceWin = yes\n| wins = 60\n| losses = 22\n| division = Central\n| division_place = 1\n| conf_place = 2\n| coach = [[K. C. Jones]]\n| arena = [[Capital Centre]]\n| television = [[WDCA]]\n| radio = [[WFED|WTOP]]\n| playoffs = [[1975 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]]<br><small>(Eliminated 0\u20134)</small>\n| bbr_team = WSB\n| prev_name = Capital Bullets\n}}\nThe '''1974\u201375 Washington Bullets''' played in their 14th season and 2nd in the Washington, D.C. area. The franchise changed their name from the Capital Bullets to the Washington Bullets. The franchise captured its 6th division title in 7 years by posting a franchise best record of 60\u201322.<ref name=\"Washington Wizards 1963-Present\">[http://www.sportsecyclopedia.com/nba/dc/wizards.html Washington Wizards (1963\u2013Present)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The Bullets were nearly unbeatable at home posting a record of 36\u20135 at the Capital Centre.<ref name=\"Washington Wizards 1963-Present\"/>  The Bullets won their second Eastern Conference title, but were swept in the [[1975 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]] in four games by the [[Golden State Warriors]].\n\n==Draft picks==\n{{main article|1974 NBA Draft}}\n\n==Roster==\n{{NBA roster header|team=Washington Bullets\n| bg1 = #C9143A | color1 = white\n| bg2 = #0344AD | color2 = white\n}}\n<!-- begin player list -->\n{{player2 | num = 45 | first = Phil | last = Chenier | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 3 | lbs = 180 | college = California}}\n{{player2 | n