State 109''', Washington 101\n*'''Game 4''' @ Washington: '''Golden State 96''', Washington 95\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*[[Elvin Hayes]], [[All-NBA First Team]]\n*[[Phil Chenier]], All-NBA Second Team\n*Elvin Hayes, [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/WSB/1975.html Bullets on Basketball Reference]\n\n{{1974-75 NBA season by team}}\n{{Washington Wizards seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1974-75 Washington Bullets season}}\n[[Category:1974\u201375 NBA season|Washington]]\n[[Category:Washington Wizards seasons]]\n[[Category:Eastern Conference (NBA) championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1974 in sports in Washington, D.C.|Wash]]\n[[Category:1975 in sports in Washington, D.C.|Wash]]\n", "name_user": "Johannbgood", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoster", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1974%E2%80%9375_Washington_Bullets_season"}
{"title_page": "History of the Irish in Holyoke", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Irish people in Holyoke\n| native_name      = ''\u00c9ireannaigh Holyoke''\n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Banquet held by Holyoke Irish Centennial Anniversary Committee 1973.jpg\n| image_caption    = Attendees of a banquet held by the Holyoke Irish Centennial Anniversary Committee, 1973\n| total            = 6,076\n| total_year       = 2010\n| total_source     = <!-- source of total population; may be ''census'' or ''estimate'' -->\n| total_ref        = <!-- references supporting total population -->\n| genealogy        = \n| regions          = <!-- for e.g. a list of regions (countries), especially if regionN etc below not used -->\n\n| region1          = <!-- first region (country)'s name -->\n| pop1             = <!-- population in first region -->\n| ref1             = <!-- <ref>erence/s supporting pop1 data -->\n| region2          = \n| pop2             = \n| ref2             = \n| region3          = \n| pop3             = \n| ref3             = \n<!-- etc, to: -->\n| region33         = \n| pop33            = \n| ref33            = \n\n| languages        = [[American English]],<br>[[Irish language]] <small>(in 19th century, rare)</small>\n| religions        = \n| footnotes        = \n}}\n{{Ethnic Holyoke sidebar}}\n\nFrom the beginning of the city's history as the western bank of [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]], Irish families have resided in and contributed to the development of the civics and culture of [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]]. Among the first appellations given to the city were the handles \"Ireland\", \"Ireland Parish\", or \"Ireland Depot\", after the village was designated the 3rd Parish of [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]] in 1786.<ref name=Holland1855>{{cite book |last=Holland |first=Josiah Gilbert |date=1855 |title=History of Western Massachusetts; the counties of Hampden, Hampshire, Franklin, and Berkshire |url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofwestern02holluoft#page/70/mode/2up |location=Springfield, Mass. |publisher=Samuel Bowles |pages=70 |isbn= |author-link= |quote=On the 7th of July, 1786, the part of West Springfield now embraced in Holyoke was incorporated as the Third Parish of West Springfield, and was called 'Ireland', and 'Ireland Parish', from the fact that several Irish families were the first settlers of the territory, though there is no record of the date of their settlement}}</ref> Initially occupied by a mixture of [[Yankee#Early usage|Yankee English]] and [[Irish Protestant]] families, many of whom belonged to the Baptist community of [[Elmwood, Holyoke, Massachusetts|Elmwood]], from 1840 through 1870 the area saw a large influx of [[Irish Catholic]] workers, immigrants to the United States, initially from the exodus of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]].<ref name=\"constance\">{{cite book | last1=Green | first=Constance McLaughlin|chapter=XII. Social Life|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.59808/2015.59808.Holyoke-Massachusetts-A-Case-History-Of-The-Inkistrial-Revolution-In-America#page/n387/mode/2up/search/1889 |author-link=Constance McLaughlin Green|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.59808/2015.59808.Holyoke-Massachusetts-A-Case-History-Of-The-Inkistrial-Revolution-In-America#page/n11/mode/2up|title=Holyoke, Massachusetts; a case history of the industrial revolution in America | year=1939 | publisher=Yale University Press |location = New Haven |series=Yale Historical Publications|number=XXXIV}}</ref> During that period Irish immigrants and their descendants comprised the largest demographic in Holyoke and built much of the early city's infrastructure, including the dams, canals, and factories.<ref name=\"modern\">{{cite book|last=Zuckerman|first=Molly K|title=Modern Environments and Human Health: Revisiting the Second Epidemiologic Transition|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2014|page=165|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EdYVAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT165&lpg=PT165&dq=prue+french+holyoke#v=onepage&q=&f=false|isbn=9781118504291}}</ref> Facing early hardships from [[Anti-Irish sentiment]], Holyoke's Irish would largely build the early [[Labor unions in the United States|labor movement]] of the city's textile and paper mills, and remained active in the national [[Irish nationalist]] and [[Gaelic revival]] movements of the United States, with the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society being one of 13 signatory organizations creating the Gaelic League of America, an early 20th century American counterpart of [[Conradh na Gaeilge]].<ref name=\"IrishIdentity\">{{cite book|title=Building Irish Identity in America, 1870-1915: The Gaelic Revival|last=Bhroim\u00e9il|first=\u00dana N\u00ed|year=2003|page=51|publisher=Four Courts|location=Dublin|oclc=238503444}}</ref><ref name=\"join\">{{cite magazine|magazine=F\u00e1inne an lae|year=1898|page=27|quote=From the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society which, at the close of its last session, affiliated with the Gaelic League here, comes a very hearty fraternal greeting|title=[\"From the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society\"]}}</ref>\n\nChanges in industry and culture, and successive waves of different immigrant demographics would displace the Irish community to an extent, however the demographic remained an active identity in civic life throughout the 20th century. The Irish community today organizes the largest public event held in Holyoke annually, the [[Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade]], with representatives from surrounding towns and cities, which has gradually become a collective celebration for people of Irish parentage as well as the city's syncretic culture. Today people of Irish ancestry are the second largest demographic in Holyoke and the largest non-Hispanic group, representing about 15% of all residents, and 17% of residents of Hampden County, the second-largest single group by ancestry.<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0600000US2501330840|title=DP02 Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006\u20132010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates for Holyoke, Massachusetts|accessdate=August 11, 2019|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213161216/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0600000US2501330840|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US25013|title=DP02 Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006\u20132010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates for Hampden County, Massachusetts|accessdate=August 11, 2019|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early settlement and Ireland Parish===\n[[File:Ireland, the 3rd Parish of West Springfield, Holyoke (1827).png|right|thumb|One of the earliest maps of Holyoke, as \"Ireland, or 3<sup>d</sup> Parish of Springfield\", often corrupted as \"Ireland Parish\", 1827]]\n\nWhile the earliest settlers of Springfield would largely be of Yankee English stock, the first of the residents of the 3rd Parish of West Springfield were Irish immigrants who began settling in the region before the construction of the dam and industrialization that followed, granting the area the name \"Ireland\" or \"Ireland Parish.\" Colonists had claimed lands by 1655, and early accounts refer to John Riley as the first permanent settler of Holyoke,<ref>{{cite book|quote=[T]he dwellers on the west side are spoken of in old records as 'our neighbors'{{nbsp}}... John Riley went as far away as the southern part of the present Holyoke and may be considered as the first settler of that city.|last=Barrows|first=Charles Henry|title=The History of Springfield in Massachusetts for the Young|publisher=The Connecticut Valley Historical Society|year=1911|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyspringfi00barrgoog/page/n52 88]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyspringfi00barrgoog}}</ref><ref name=\"storyof\">{{cite book | last1=Harper | first=Wyatt E. | title=The Story of Holyoke | year=1973 | publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke | oclc=8060402 |url = https://archive.org/stream/storyofholyoke00harp#page/172/mode/2up}}</ref>{{rp|12}} but though Riley owned 28 acres along \"Riley's Brook\" (Tannery Brook in modern-day [[Ingleside, Holyoke, Massachusetts|Ingleside]]), his daughters Mary and Margaret, and their [[Irish Protestant]] husbands, Joseph Ely and William MacCranny, would first establish their homesteads in 1667.<ref name=\"stone\">{{cite book|title=Stories Carved in Stone: Holyoke, Massachusetts|last=Clark|first=Rusty|year=2006|publisher=Dog Pond Press|location=West Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>{{rp|10}} By the time West Springfield was partitioned in 1707, numerous Irish families had moved to the Parish, and eventually it was chartered as such, the 3rd Parish of West Springfield, on July 7, 1786. Quickly it gained the nickname '''Ireland''', for in those days a number of other families had joined the descendants of the Elys and MacCrannys; these names have also been in the past combined into the better known '''Ireland Parish''' handle.<ref>{{cite book|title=The History of the First Baptist Church of Holyoke, Mass; Together with the Proceedings of the Centennial Services|last=Hungate|first=Jesse A.|location=Holyoke, Mass.|year=1904}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke Celebrates Semi-Centennial; Holyoke's History Had Its Roots in Ireland Parish|page=31|work=Springfield Republican|date=September 2, 1923|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland Depot era===\n[[File:Dam workers construct the first or second Holyoke Dam c1849.jpg|right|thumb|Dam workers pose for a group photo during the construction of the first or second timber dam, c. 1848\u20131849]]\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 230\n   | align = left\n   | footer = The contrast between \"The Patch\" (''top''), and 1840s worker housing in \"The Flats\" (''bottom''); within a generation most Irish laborers would find improved conditions representative of the latter, as \"New City\" and its infrastructure were built from field and forest\n   | image1 = The Patch, Holyoke, circa 1850s.jpg\n   | image2 = HolyokeMA CompanyHousing.jpg}}\n\nThe growth of the Irish community up until this time can be found in birth records of West Springfield, of which Holyoke was its 3rd parish. In 1847 there were 14 births, none of which were of Irish surnames, but by 1848, 19 of 87 were, and by 1849 105 out of 221 West Springfield births were of Irish parentage.<ref name=\"stjeromes\">{{cite book|title=History of St. Jerome's Parish, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Diocese of Springfield; issued in connection with the Observance of its Diamond Jubilee|year=1931|author=P. J. Lucey|publisher=Diocese of Springfield|location=Holyoke, Mass.|oclc=42457185}}</ref>{{rp|24}} Many of the new arrivals came to find work in the construction of the dam and the factories that would be built with it. In the fall of 1848 the Hadley Falls Company put their building lots on the market, and of these lots, many were purchased by recently-arrived Irish. From these arrivals there formed three small villages, the abodes of the [[Hadley Falls Company Housing District|Hadley Falls Company Housing]], otherwise known as the \"North Flats\" at the time, designed by mill engineer John Chase, and built by one Charles MacClellan.<ref>[http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=HLY.36 HLY.36], MACRIS, Massachusetts Historical Commission.</ref> Long lost to history there existed two smaller shanty villages, \"The Patch\", lying where [[Pulaski Park (Holyoke, Massachusetts)|Pulaski Park]] stands today,<ref name=\"storyof\"/>{{rp|41}} and \"The Bush\", a series of dwellings in the fields of [[South Holyoke]].<ref name=\"stjeromes\"/>{{rp|24}} Another early settlement, simply referred to as \"The Field\", would be rechristened \"Ireland Depot\" with the arrival of the railroad in 1845,<ref>{{cite book|title=Immigrant and Native Families: The Impact of Immigration on the Demographic Transformation of Western Massachusetts, 1850 to 1900|last=Golden|first=Hilda H|publisher=University Press of America|location=Lanham, Md.|page=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4yOkZ-cGb60C&pg=PA3|isbn=9780819192875|year=1994}}</ref> today being part of the broader-defined \"The Flats\" or more specifically \"Depot Hill\", which was used for tillage predating the development of the grid and [[Holyoke Canal System|canal system]].<ref>{{cite book |year=1891|editor1-last=Warner |editor1-first=Charles F.  |editor2-last=Johnson |editor2-first=Clifton |title=Picturesque Hampden |script-title= |trans-title= |url=https://archive.org/stream/picturesquehampd00warn#page/n0/mode/2up  |series=Picturesque Massachusetts Series |volume=Part II - West |location=Northampton, Mass. |publisher=Picturesque Publishing Company |pages=1\u2013152|oclc= 70679168 }}</ref>{{rp|7}}\n\nIn contrast with the skilled-labor class and the rowhouses of the Hadley Falls Company in The Flats, the early dwellings of The Patch were primitive, ephemeral, and described as shanties. Construction of these structures was described in Clifton Johnson's ''Hampden County'' as \"a shanty built by putting four upright posts, to which rough boards were nailed{{nbsp}}... a roof of overlapping boards was put on top, places cut for a door and windows{{nbsp}}... Inside the shanty the earth was smoothed{{nbsp}}... and a rude floor of boards put down\".<ref name=\"hampden1936\">{{cite book|title=Hampden County, 1636-1936|editor-last=Johnson|editor-first=Clifton|page=667|chapter-url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=wu.89067299834;view=1up;seq=125|oclc=9479870|volume=II|chapter=Holyoke, the Paper City}}</ref>{{rp|681}} These buildings typically housed a single family, however some were boarding houses for large groups of workers, the largest described as being 40 feet long at its longest wall and housing 30 people. Livestock would often be seen milling freely about between such buildings in areas like The Patch.<ref name=\"hampden1936\"/>{{rp|681}} \n\nTragedy struck in 1849, when the immigrant colonies suffered a severe epidemic of [[cholera]]. Men, women and children would get sick in the evening, and perish by the morning; with no cemetery other than one across the river in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]], the epidemic spread quickly and acutely.<ref name=\"storyof\"/>{{rp|41}} It was reported to have resulted in hundreds of deaths, and the outbreak resulted in the deaths of 10% of the city's early Irish population. Part of a national phenomena, the cause of the outbreak was likely from the unsanitary conditions on ships bringing large groups seeking refuge from the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]].<ref name=\"stjeromes\"/>{{rp|24-25}} Prior to the construction of [[Pulaski Park (Holyoke, Massachusetts)|Prospect Park]] on the site and the construction of a modern sewage system, conditions at The Patch led to outbreaks that would persist for its residents there in the ensuing decades.<ref>{{cite news|title=[\"Holyoke had the cholera...\"]|work=Springfield Republican|page=8|location=Springfield, Mass.|quote=Holyoke had the cholera or something much like it\u2014a disease that has caused several deaths after short illness in some of the factory boarding houses, inhabited mostly by foreigners and very filthy, and at the 'Patch,' an Irish settlement|date=October 6, 1866}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/reasonableusepeo0000cumb|url-access=registration|title=Reasonable Use: The People, the Environment, and the State, New England...|last=Cumbler|first=John T.|page=[https://archive.org/details/reasonableusepeo0000cumb/page/47 47]|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=9780195138139}}</ref>\n\nIn 1850 following a meeting of the Hadley Falls Company, the New City was dubbed Holyoke. Emigration from Ireland to Holyoke would continue well into the 20th century and yet, with some irony it was after the changing of the name \"Ireland Parish\" from the New City to an English surname, that the area changed from more predominantly English Yankee, into a city substantially more Irish in character.<ref name=\"della\">{{cite book|title=Holyoke|last=Della Penna|first=Craig P.|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=1997|location=Charleston, SC|oclc=1035596870}}</ref>{{rp|6}} With the emergence of industry and a new wave of immigration, by 1855 more than a third of residents in Holyoke were of Irish origin.<ref name=\"toil\">{{cite book|title=Commonwealth of Toil|last1=Juravich|last2=Hartford|last3=Green|first1=Tom|first2=William F.|first3=James R.|page=[https://archive.org/details/commonwealthofto00jura/page/63 63]|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|year=1996|url=https://archive.org/details/commonwealthofto00jura|url-access=registration|isbn=1558490469}}</ref>\n\n===Tradesmen and builders===\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | width1 = 149\n   | width2 = 298\n   | align = right\n   | footer = Left to right: John Delaney (1815\u20131887), and \"Delaney's Marble Block\", or Marble Hall, as it appeared on the corner of Dwight and High Street the late 1880s\n   | image1 = John Delaney (1815-1887).jpg\n   | image2 = Delaney's Marble Block.jpg}}\n\nIrish immigration to Holyoke would continue well into the 20th century, however the majority of immigrants to the city would be Irish predominantly in the first decades of the city's existence, from the famine refugees of the 1840s through the later factory worker arrivals of the 1890s.<ref name=\"institutes\">{{cite journal|publisher=National Institutes of Health|doi=10.1017/ssh.2017.26|pmid = 29307945|title=Immigration, Occupation and Inequality in Emergent Nineteenth-Century New England Cities|date=Winter 2017|journal=Social Science History|volume=XLI|issue=4|pages=645\u2013671|pmc=5751957|last1 = Leonard|first1 = Susan Hautaniemi|last2 = Robinson|first2 = Christopher|last3 = Anderton|first3 = Douglas L.}}</ref> By 1900, larger groups of French-Canadians had begun to arrive, however with their early arrival and the separation of French language institutions, the Irish would however come to define Holyoke's identity as founders. They, along a much smaller and separate German demographic, would establish much of the city's early social, political, and labor institutions.<ref name=\"constance\"/>\n\nAlthough many of Holyoke's earliest arrivals would be farmers, these would-be laborers included a number of tradesmen such as carpenters, masons, and blacksmiths, some of the industrial city's workers who would construct its dam, canals, and factories in subsequent decades.<ref name=\"modern\"/><ref>{{cite web|website=Our Plural History, Springfield, MA|title=Irish Immigrants in Holyoke|url=http://ourpluralhistory.stcc.edu/industrial/irish.html|publisher=Springfield Technical Community College|year=2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607134120/http://ourpluralhistory.stcc.edu/industrial/irish.html|archive-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref> This was reflected in a shifting demography: in 1860, three in four skilled construction workers were Yankee Americans; by 1880 fewer than one in five reflected the same demographic, the vast majority being Irish tradesmen who would define the labor community of unions and local politics for virtually the entirety of the city's history.<ref name=\"toil\"/> One of Ireland's notable sculptor's [[Jerome Connor]], was brought to the United States as a boy as his stonemason father, Patrick Connor, was among Holyoke's early tradesmen.\n\nDespite [[anti-Irish sentiment]] in the United States during the 19th century, the Irish were split into two classes, with about 50% working in industry between 1860 and 1900, and 25\u201336% represented in [[professional services]], such as lawyers, architects, bankers, and other occupations, during the same period, exceeding the proportions of the other immigrant demographics and native-born populations in such occupations during that time.<ref name=\"institutes\">{{cite journal|publisher=National Institutes of Health|doi=10.1017/ssh.2017.26|pmid = 29307945|title=Immigration, Occupation and Inequality in Emergent Nineteenth-Century New England Cities|date=Winter 2017|journal=Social Science History|volume=XLI|issue=4|pages=645\u2013671|pmc=5751957|last1 = Leonard|first1 = Susan Hautaniemi|last2 = Robinson|first2 = Christopher|last3 = Anderton|first3 = Douglas L.}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 250\n   | align = left\n   | footer = Top to bottom: Johanna (n\u00e9e Brassil), Daniel O'Connell and Sons, c. 1908; the Holy Cross Church, now Our Lady of the Cross, erected by the Daniel O'Connell's Sons firm in 1926 when they incorporated under that name, one of many projects the firm would complete, including the [[W. E. B. DuBois Library]] at [[UMass Amherst]] and Springfield's [[Monarch Place]]\n   | image1 = Daniel J. O'Connell, Johanna Brassil, and Sons.jpg\n   | image2 = Holy Cross Church, Holyoke, Mass (71668).jpg}}\n[[File:Chief John T. Lynch, Holyoke Fire Dept, hero fireman as Lt in Precious Blood Church fire.jpg|150px|right|thumb|Fire Chief John T. Lynch, a fixture in Holyoke for decades, best remembered for his bravery as a lieutenant in rescuing parishioners in the 1875 [[Precious Blood Church fire]]]]\nAmong the earliest arrivals in Holyoke's workmen and contractors was John Delaney, a stonemason. By the time he would arrive in Holyoke in April of 1849,<ref name=\"marble\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke's Marble Building; Which John Delaney has Built at a Cost of $100,000|date=April 18, 1886|page=3|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Republican}}</ref> Delaney had previously worked on the [[Croton Watershed|Croton Water-works]] supplying the City of New York, [[Fort Warren (Massachusetts)|Fort Warren]] in Boston, and the [[Lowell Power Canal System and Pawtucket Gatehouse|Lowell Canal System]]. In his time in Holyoke he would become known for supervising the construction of the [[Holyoke Canal System]], as well as a number of its mills, and oversaw the construction of [[Holyoke City Hall]]'s foundations.<ref name=\"storyof\"/>{{rp|42}}<ref>{{cite book  |year=1879  |chapter=Holyoke |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofconnect02ever#page/n557/mode/2up |chapter-format=  |title=History of the Connecticut Valley in Massachusetts, with illustrations and biographical sketches of some of its prominent men and pioneers |volume=II |pages=915\u2013938 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Louis H. Everts; Press of J.B. Lippincott and Co |url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofconnect02ever#page/n7/mode/2up |oclc= 866692568 }}</ref> In the latter years of his career, Delaney wished to build \"a worthy monument to leave behind him\", and purchased the old Second Congregational Church that once sat across from City Hall in 1884. By January of 1885, work had begun in razing the old structure and plans had been drawn up by architect [[James A. Clough]] to build a grand building made of [[Proctor, Vermont|Sutherland Falls]] marble from Vermont, from a quarry owned by Vermont Governor [[Redfield Proctor]]'s family, with foundational ashlar facing Dwight Street taken from Delaney's quarry at [[Mount Tom (Massachusetts)|Mount Tom]].<ref name=\"marble\"/> When Proctor would visit Holyoke, Springfield, or one of its surrounding towns thereafter, he would make a point to pass that corner of Dwight and High \"to see how his marble weathered.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Holyoke|last=Dawson|first=Devon|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C8InX3IfhlUC&pg=PA26|year=2004|publisher=Arcadia|location=Charleston, SC|lccn=2003116189|isbn=9780738535265}}</ref> Unfortunately Delaney's monument to Holyoke's tradesmen would succumb to the wrecking ball after 65 years, for by 1950 its tenant the [[W. T. Grant|W. T. Grant Department Store]] sought a more modern building. Demolished in January and February of 1950, a total of 195 trucks hauled the dismantled marble South Hadley, where it was used as ground fill in a new housing development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Going|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=40|date=January 19, 1950}}</ref><ref name=\"della\"/>{{rp|54}} Today the legacy of Delaney and his men remains most visible in the stone facades of the city's canal system.\n\nA prominent figure in Holyoke's printing industry was one Michael J. Doyle.<ref name=\"water\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Water Commissioner Looks Like ex-Alderman M. J. Doyle for the Place\u2014Democratic Aldermen Will Caucus Late This Week\u2014President Kennedy Wanted Again\u2014Dr McIntee's Letter|date=December 25, 1904|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=6|quote=Indications pointed last evening to the election by the Holyoke board of aldermen a week from to-morrow of ex-Alderman Michael J. Doyle of the M. J. Doyle printing company to the water board to succeed Chairman John J. Sullivan}}</ref> Born in [[Ireland]] on September 27, 1872 to Thomas and Mary Doyle (n\u00e9e Murphy), Doyle would arrive in America with his parents in 1880. Educated in [[Holyoke Public Schools]], he would eventually take up an engraving apprenticeship in Springfield, and began a firm under the handle \"M. J. Doyle Printing Company\" in 1893, was elected to the board of aldermen in 1897 and water commission in 1904,<ref name=\"water\"/> running many jobs for the city's annual reports and publications through the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite book  |year=1902  |chapter=The City of Holyoke and the Factors in its History |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/n23/mode/2up |chapter-format= |editor1-last=Copeland |editor1-first=Alfred Minot  |title=\"Our county and its people\" : A history of Hampden County, Massachusetts |volume=III |pages=659 |publisher= The Century Memorial Publishing Company |url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/658/mode/2up |oclc= 5692695963 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Holyoke: The Skinner Family and Wistariahurst|series=Images of America|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Charleston, S.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QI4Dhk5_KBgC&pg=PA61|page=61|quote=M. J. Doyle Printing Company was a printing and negraving company that began in the late 1890s. It was located on Front Street in Holyoke and advertised having a telephone connection for those needing to contact the company|isbn=9780738539447|date=March 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=[\"M. J. Doyle Printing\"] Full-text Search Results - HathiTrust Digital Library|website=HathiTrust|access-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907200139/https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/ls?field1=ocr%3Bq1%3D%22M.%20J.%20Doyle%20Printing%22%3Ba%3Dsrchls%3Blmt%3Dft|archive-date=September 7, 2019|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/ls?field1=ocr;q1=\"M._J._Doyle_Printing\";a=srchls;lmt=ft|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDaniel O'Connell was one of the most influential of the early Irish tradesmen. Born in [[County Kerry]] in 1833, he and his family arrived in Chicopee Falls and subsequently Holyoke in 1847. His first job was as a water boy for the workers of the first, ill-fated dam.<ref name=\"storyof\"/> In 1864 he began serving as superintendent of streets, an early counterpart of the superintendent of the department of public works. Following the election of Mayor William Ruddy in 1879, O'Connell was called into the new mayor's offices and told to put four new men on his payroll, and initially to fire the six he already had under employ.<ref name=\"storyof\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=International Directory of Company Histories|volume=C|year=2009|pages=306\u2013308|publisher=St. James Press|oclc=224417874|editor-last=Grant|editor-first=Tina}}</ref> Even after Ruddy retracted this demand and told O'Connell to simply add the four as a political favor, O'Connell would not abide and resigned, starting an independent contracting business. The next morning [[William Skinner (manufacturer)|William Skinner]] knocked on O'Connell's front door and after discussing the circumstances, hired him to pave the yards of the [[William Skinner and Sons|Skinner and Sons Silk]] mills in the city.<ref name=\"1988oconnell\">{{cite news|title=Water boy job gave start to Holyoke's O'Connell firm|last1=Lauer|first1=Martin J.|last2=Hachadourian|first2=Kris|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=F-87, F-90|date=January 24, 1988}}</ref> The first O'Connell would go on to serve as one of the subcontractors for the granite [[Holyoke Dam]], and would work on a number of other projects including the construction of the New Bedford reservoir. Following his death in 1916, his sons and their descendants would continue his legacy, formally incorporating the company as Daniel O'Connell's Sons in 1926, and going on to work on a number of major projects in the Commonwealth, the broader United States, and as far away as South America.<ref name=\"storyof\"/> Among their notable works are the world's tallest academic library, [[W.E.B. DuBois Library]] at UMass Amherst, Springfield's [[Monarch Place]], [[Interstate 391]], [[Steven Holl]]'s [[Simmons Hall]] for [[MIT]], as well as the [[Frank Gehry]]-designed [[Richard B. Fisher Center for the Performing Arts]] of [[Bard College]].<ref name=\"1988oconnell\"/><ref>{{cite web|publisher=The O'Connell Companies|archive-date=April 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422174636/http://www.oconnells.com/projects/signature-projects/|url=http://www.oconnells.com/projects/signature-projects/|title=Signature Projects}}</ref>\n\n===Second wave, labor, and trade unions===\n[[File:Holyoke, Massachusetts - Paper. American Writing Paper Co. Rag sorting (Irish). - NARA - 518336.jpg|right|thumb|\"Rag girls\" cut up cotton rags used in making [[fine paper|fine writing paper]] in a Holyoke mill of the [[American Writing Paper Company]], c. 1937]]\n\nIn the decades after the [[Irish Potato Famine]] up until the [[Great Depression]], a number of single Irish women would immigrate to the United States, following the footsteps of families and male relatives who had come before. Many would take up work as domestic servants for wealthy families in larger cities, and while some of Holyoke's wealthier mill owners like the [[Wistariahurst|Skinner family]] would have servants in their homes,<ref>{{cite web|title=Skinner Servants|archive-date=July 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729051718/https://wistariahurst.org/skinner-servants/|url=https://wistariahurst.org/skinner-servants/|website=Wistariahurst|year=2013}}</ref> many of Holyoke's would find work in the city's textile factories.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|archive-date=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919025854/https://www.masslive.com/living/2013/03/the_irish_legacy_excerpt_anna_sullivan_of_holyoke.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/living/2013/03/the_irish_legacy_excerpt_anna_sullivan_of_holyoke.html|title='The Irish Legacy' excerpt: Anna Sullivan of Holyoke played dominant role in organizing Weaver's Union|date=March 8, 2013|last=Shannon|first=Catherine B.}}</ref> Holyoke would also have among the first woman police officers in the Commonwealth, Mary McMahon, who was appointed to that role in 1917 and retired after marrying in 1921. Although historian Marcella Kelly would place her as the first woman police officer in the Commonwealth, and her appointment predated Boston's first by several years, early accounts also refer to previous woman officers in Springfield and Northampton at the time of her tenure.<ref>{{cite book|title=Behind Eternity: Holyoke Women Who Made a Difference, 1873-1973|publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke|year=1973|last=Kelly|first=Marcella R.|oclc=38305604|pages=187\u2013188}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=To Have Police Woman; Mary McMahon, a Teacher, Recommended to the Mayor for Appointment|page=12|date=June 28, 1917|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Republican|quote=Police women from Springfield and Northampton were present at the meeting and explained the duties of the position}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922161829/https://archive.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/04/21/90_years_later_bostons_first_policewomen_get_fresh_recognition/|url=https://archive.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/04/21/90_years_later_bostons_first_policewomen_get_fresh_recognition/|archive-date=September 22, 2019|date=April 21, 2011|last=Cramer|first=Maria|work=The Boston Globe|title=They upended barriers\u2014and criminals; 90 years later, city's first policewomen get fresh recognition}}</ref>\n\nMany of the earliest factory worker arrivals saw new tensions between their unions and the arrival of French-Canadian workers, who while some would participate in unionism elsewhere in New England, were largely unorganized in Holyoke and brought in by mill owners to undermine the workers' leverage for better wages and working hours. In the successive generations more ethnic groups would be taken into the fold but much of the city's earliest union movements comprised Irish and German laborers.<ref name=\"toil\"/><ref name=\"masshumanities\">{{cite web|website=MassHumanities|publisher=Massachusetts Foundation for the Humanities|location=Northampton, Mass.|url=http://www.masshumanities.org/ph_fear-of-uniting-labor-movements-in-early-holyoke/|title=Fear of Uniting: Labor Movements in Early Holyoke|last=Lotspeich|first=Charlie|date=November 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022060923/http://masshumanities.org/ph_fear-of-uniting-labor-movements-in-early-holyoke/|archive-date=October 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hartford |first=William F. | title=Working people of Holyoke : class and ethnicity in a Massachusetts mill town, 1850\u20131960|location=New Brunswick, NJ.| publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1990| isbn= 9780813515762|oclc= 21041495}}</ref> Irish identity in the working class community became synonymous with unionism, as unions gradually took on the roles associated with ethnic organizations in public meetings and cultural events. Examples of such trade unions include a local of the [[United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners of America]] which was organized in the city soon after the formation of that trade union in 1881,<ref name=\"toil\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners of America. Springfield District Council Records, 1885-1975|archive-date=July 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701134742/http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums110|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums110|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|website=Special Collections & University Archives, UMass Amherst Libraries}}</ref> and also the Holyoke Irish role in founding the United Brotherhood of Paperworkers. Ultimately representing workers of all backgrounds, it first began as a social club within the city's Irish trade unionists known as the Eagle Lodge, receiving charter as Local{{nbsp}}1 from the [[American Federation of Labor]] in May of 1883. Even as the organization grew, it would remain tied to the community through the 20th century, among other occasions, the city would host the International Brotherhood's president in 1913, and during Holyoke's centennial in 1973, the union, then a member of the AFL-CIO, would be one of the ceremonies sponsors.<ref>{{cite news|title=President Carey Guest of Honor; Holyoke Paper Makers Entertain Prominent Union Officials|date=September 1, 1913|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Union|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Holyoke, Massachusetts Centennial Souvenir Program | year=1973 | publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke | oclc= 49709901 |url = https://archive.org/stream/holyokemassachus00holy#page/n0/mode/2up}}</ref>{{rp|87}} The union would reorganize and merge several times over the subsequent decades, eventually becoming the [[Paper, Allied-Industrial, Chemical and Energy Workers International Union]] in 1999, ultimately folding into [[United Steelworkers]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite journal|volume=XXXIII|issue=3|journal=The Massachusetts Review|location=Amherst, Mass.|last=Jacobson-Hardy|first=Michael|title=Faces, Machines, and Voices: The Fading Landscape of Papermaking in Holyoke, Massachusetts|date=Autumn 1992|pages=361\u2013384|jstor=25090356}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103134830/http://scua.library.umass.edu/umarmot/international-brotherhood-of-paper-makers-eagle-lodge/|archive-date=January 3, 2018|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/umarmot/international-brotherhood-of-paper-makers-eagle-lodge/|title=International Brotherhood of Paper Makers Local 1 (Eagle Lodge : Holyoke, Mass.) Records|publisher=University of Massachusetts|website=Special Collections and University Archives}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/files/docs/publications/bls/bls_0420_1926.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528121916/https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/files/docs/publications/bls/bls_0420_1926.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-05-28|title=Handbook of American Trade-Unions|issue=420|date=October 1926|publisher=US Department of Labor; Government Printing Office (GPO)|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=103\u2013104}}</ref>\n[[File:Anna_Sullivan_(labor_organizer).jpg|left|thumb|Anna Sullivan, who first unionized Holyoke's silk industry]]\nOne of Holyoke's leading figures in organized labor into the twentieth century was Anne B Sullivan (n\u00e9e Burns), whom Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] would describe as the \"first lady of labor\" at a testimonial dinner in 1975.<ref name=\"histjourno\">{{cite journal|journal=Historical Journal of Massachusetts|date=Summer 2008|location=Westfield, Mass.|publisher=Westfield State University|last=Dodge|first=L. Mara|title=Anna B. Sullivan, 1903\u20131983: The Formative Years of a Textile Mill Union Organizer (Holyoke, Massachusetts)|pages=184\u2013225|volume=XXXVI|issue=2}}</ref> Sullivan, born in Holyoke in 1903 to an Irish father and second generation Irish and German mother, began her career in labor joining the Weavers Union in 1932 and, inspired by the [[Textile workers strike (1934)|Textile Workers Strike of 1934]], by she had 1936 had organized workers to join the [[Textile Workers Union of America|Textile Workers Union]] at [[William Skinner and Sons]], the first mill in Western Massachusetts to unionize under the [[Congress of Industrial Organizations|CIO]].<ref>{{cite news|page=20H|date=September 23, 1983|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|title=Anna F. Sullivan; 'first lady of labor'}}</ref><ref name=\"womenmakingchange\">{{cite web|title=Anna Sullivan|website=Women Making Change; Wistariahurst|archive-date=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919015742/https://wistariahurst.org/women-making-change/anna-sullivan/|url=https://wistariahurst.org/women-making-change/anna-sullivan/|year=2017}}</ref> Up until this time, workers were offered no real guarantee of consistent pay or work, with one example being a mill which would lay off its employees for two weeks at the holidays, with no pay at Christmas.<ref name=\"womenmakingchange\"/> Besides the dangers of the loud, heavy machinery used in the mills and common respiratory illnesses from particulate in the air, foremen could fire workers for any reason, and with women workers, as Sullivan recalled, \"if [the foreman] liked the color of your hair today you were alright. If he didn't like it tomorrow, good bye.\" By the end of the 1920s, the urgency of additional work for the same wages as well as a practice of fining workers for flaws made in satins were part of the impetus which led to unionization at Skinner's mills in the next decade.<ref name=\"histjourno\"/> Despite labor being replaced by successive generations of immigrant labor, and the movement of many factories to cheaper operations in the South, part of what Sullivan attributed to the union's leverage was the skill required to be a weaver, especially in silk, which meant months of training with each hire, which didn't even guarantee mastery from each worker's efforts.<ref name=\"histjourno\"/>\n\nSullivan would go on to serve as manager of the Holyoke Joint Board of Textile Workers from 1944 to 1966, and the Berkshire Joint Board in Pittsfield from 1958 until 1966 when deindustrialization severely reduced textile work. Sullivan would also run once for Congress in 1950 on the Democratic ticket, losing to incumbent [[John W. Heselton]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Sullivan Concedes Win For Heselton|page=1|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=November 8, 1950}}</ref> part of her reason for running being to fight rising food costs attributed to shortages from the [[Korean War]]. During her campaign she gathered more than 1000 signatures in a petition to President Truman stating in part that \"we pledge ourselves to support our soldiers, in Korea by refusing to hoard foodstuffs{{nbsp}}... We earnestly petition you to request the Congress to roll back prices to their levels of June 15, 1950, and to request the Anti-Trust Division of the Department of Justice to investigate whether a conspiracy exists to profiteer in food in violation of our laws.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=1000 Holyokers Sign Petitions Asking Truman for Rollback; Mrs Sullivan's Supporters Get Names in 24-Hour Period; Price Curb Backing Is Seen|date=August 5, 1950|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=16|work=Springfield Union}}</ref> Even after entering state government in 1966 as a representative for Springfield's office of the [[Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination]], she remained active member of the Springfield-Chicopee-Westfield Labor Council and on the board of directors of the Springfield Chapter of the [[American Red Cross]]. In a memorial address delivered before Congress Rep. [[Edward P. Boland]] lionized her as a pioneer in Massachusetts labor, a good friend, and described her as a close personal friend of [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref>[[s:Anna F. Sullivan, Pioneer in the Labor Movement and Western Massachusetts' First Lady of Labor - Congressional Record: September 27, 1983|Anna F. Sullivan, Pioneer in the Labor Movement and Western Massachusetts' First Lady of Labor]]. Congressional Record. September 27, 1983. Extensions of Remarks. Page 26005. 98 Cong. Rec. (Bound) - Volume 98, First Session</ref>\n\n===Baseball===\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | width1 = 149\n   | width2 = 146\n   | align = left\n   | footer = [[Mickey Welch]] (''left''), and [[Roger Connor]] (''right''), both [[MLB]] [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] inductees who started early in their careers on the roster of the Holyoke Shamrocks\n   | image1 = Mickey_Welch_baseball_card.jpg\n   | image2 = 1888_N403_Yum_Yum_Tobacco_Roger_Connor,_Redemption_Back_SGC_60_EX_5.png}}\n\nIn the national context, Irish players were a key part of professional baseball in its formative years. Between 1871 and 1920, 23 percent of all baseball players were Irish or Irish-American, with about 58 percent born in American towns outside the largest 14 cities of the United States. In his 2014 book ''The Irish and the Making of American Sport, 1835-1920'', historian Patrick Redmond, would describe Holyoke specifically as \"crucial to baseball's Irish history\", with 19 major league players born in the city, 10 of whom were Irish Americans from during that period.<ref name=\"redmond\">{{cite book|title=The Irish and the Making of American Sport|last=Redmond|first=Patrick R|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|year=2014}}</ref>{{rp|57}} South Holyoke, known as Tigertown in the 1870s, was a frequent venue for baseball and earned its name from the tensions that ran between competing teams, particularly between Holyoke and Springfield, including at least one such game where a squad of police larger than both teams was required to break up a riot that had broken out between the two.<ref>{{cite news|work=Boston Sunday Globe|location=Boston|date=November 14, 1897|page=62|title=Holyoke; Mayor Smith Indorsed [sic] in the Caucuses\u2014 Old Names of Suburban Villages|quote=South Holyoke of today bears little resemblance to the 'Tigertown' of former days. In the days gone by the local baseball men played for blood and showed such tigerish propensities toward rival teams if the game did not go to their liking that perhaps this may have earned the cognomen of 'Tigertown.' A well-known baseball man recalls the feverish excitement which was developed whenever Springfield and Holyoye [sic] met on a ball field. It was invariably a gory battle, so much so that when Springfield came up here to play the local team, a squad of police, larger than the two ball nines, was required to bring the game to a peaceful ending}}</ref>\n\nThough not on any Holyoke professional team, there would be a number of players during this era born in the city, such as [[Tommy Tucker (baseball)|Tommy Tucker]], and [[Tommy Dowd (baseball)|Tommy Dowd]].<ref name=\"redmond\"/>{{rp|57}} However more than being the hometown of such players, for a time the city hosted a number of baseball teams itself. A wealth of largely-Irish baseball clubs were formed in the 19th century and teams named the \"Shamrocks\" abounded, however of the period between 1871 and 1920, only the Holyoke Shamrocks would attain professional status, competing in the [[National Association of Professional Base Ball Players|National Association]] and the [[International League]].<ref name=\"redmond\"/>{{rp|291}} \n\nRecords for Holyoke Shamrocks are decidedly fragmented, however during their 1879 season with the National Association, the team won the league pennant with a 23-14 record, with two future inductees of the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] on their roster, [[Mickey Welch]] and [[Roger Connor]], as well as four additional players who would later play in the [[MLB]]: [[Larry Corcoran]], [[Jerry Dorgan]], [[Patrick Gillespie (baseball)|Peter Gillespie]], and [[Fergy Malone]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|archive-date=August 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803062122/https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/62fde0bd|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/62fde0bd|title=Mickey Welch|last=Lamb|first=Bill}}</ref> Roger Connor, became known for his repeated home runs, knocking balls across the fields of Tigertown into the Connecticut River. Boss Bob Ferguson, of Springfield, Massachusetts, took notice of the young Connor in Holyoke, and signed him on to the majors in the Troy Trojans, launching a long baseball career.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Irish in Baseball: An Early History|last=Fleitz|first=David L|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|location=Jefferson, NC|year=2009|oclc=404919208}}</ref> Raised in Holyoke, [[Jack Doyle (baseball)|Jack \"Dirty Jack\" Doyle]] would go on to become the city's police commission from 1908 to 1909 before returning to baseball as an umpire, and eventual scout for the [[Chicago Cubs]]. Even in a varied career across the United States, he would call the city his home his entire life, eventually retiring there.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|archive-date=August 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803112906/https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/1b894e54|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/62fde0bd|title=Jack Doyle|last=Spatz|first=Lyle}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Irish identity would be less prominent in later baseball teams, Holyoke's pioneers were predecessors of many successive professional minor league teams through the next century, including the [[Holyoke Paperweights]], [[Holyoke Millers]], and the collegiate [[Valley Blue Sox]] today.\n\n===Representation on Beacon Hill===\n[[File:James_E_Delaney.jpg|170px|thumb|right|Col. James E. Delaney, among the first of Holyoke's Irish mayors, who also served as city clerk, auditor, and as a member of [[William E. Russell (politician)|Governor Russell]]'s military staff]]\n\nWith the exception of the earliest Yankee Protestants, Holyoke's political history encompasses an exhaustive list of Irish and Irish-American figures represented in all years of the city's civic operation, even during those times where it has not been the largest voting bloc, in offices too numerous to name in entirety. A handful of key figures in the Irish community however, especially in the 20th century, would grant it broader influence on the discourse of the Commonwealth in Boston's [[body politic]]. \nOne early example was Francis X. Quigley, a member of the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society and a journalist, who served as a member of the Massachusetts House (1908-1911) and of the state Senate (1911-1913), and was appointed by President [[Woodrow Wilson]] in 1913 to be appraiser to the [[Port of Boston]].<ref>{{cite book|page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinstatepo1917bost/page/14 14]|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinstatepo1917bost|title=Who's Who in State Politics|year=1917|publisher=Practical Politics|location=Boston}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Francis Quigley, Political Figure|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=2|date=January 23, 1954|work=Springfield Union}}</ref>\n\nOne of Holyoke's earliest members of the Irish community to see representation in a municipal, state, and federal capacity was Mayor James \nDelaney. A son of John Delaney, he was born in Lowell during his father's work on that city's canals, came to Holyoke at the age of one, and eventually graduated from [[Eastman Business College]]. Delaney would go on to work for the Holyoke Water Power Company and serve on the city's board of assessors for a year.<ref name=\"bostobit\">{{cite news|title=Ex-Mayor Delaney is Found Dead; Was Three Times Head of Holyoke and Served on Governor's Staff|year=July 14, 1910|location=Boston|work=Boston Journal}}</ref> In 1875 he was elected to the common council, from 1877 to 1882 served as city clerk, and was elected mayor twice in 1883 and 1884, serving two terms before being elected again in 1888 for a third. During that same year Delaney served as delegate-at-large to the convention nominating Grover Cleveland, and elected an alternate for the next Democratic convention. [[William E. Russell (politician)|Governor Russell]] would grant him the honorary title of colonel of the governor's military staff, under [[Adjutant General of Massachusetts]] Samuel Dalton.<ref name=\"bostobit\"/> Posthumously the ''[[Springfield Republican]]'' would describe him as having bipartisan support, and holding a legacy of growth in the city upon leaving office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke Newsboy Licenses; School Board to Handle Them; Will Thus Place Question Where It Can be Well Regulated\u2013Death of Col. Delaney|date=July 17, 1910|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Republican}}</ref> During his time on the governor's military staff, Delaney attended the inauguration of Pres. Cleveland as well as serve in the state delegation to the [[World's Columbian Exposition]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Personal and Social Gossip|work=Boston Herald|date=March 12, 1893|page=27|location=Boston|quote=The party consisting of Col. James E. Delaney of the Governor's staff, and Mrs. Delaney of Holyoke, Mr. and Mrs. Eugene Lynch of this city, have returned home, after a delightful trip to Baltimore and Washington, where they attended the inauguration}}\n* {{cite news|title=Delegation to World's Fair; Itinerary of the Trip Given Out by Adjt.-Gen. Dalton|page=8|date=June 9, 1893|work=Boston Herald|location=Boston|quote=Governor's staff\u2014Col. Michael T. Donahoe, Col. Spender Borden. Col. D. Howard Vincent, Col. James E. Delaney}}</ref> Attending events such as the inauguration of Russell's successor [[Frederic T. Greenhalge]] and events such as charity balls in Boston, spread the influence of the then-still 20 year old city during its greatest period of industrial growth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=6|date=January 3, 1894|quote=Col James E. Delaney will attend the inaugural exercises of Gov Greenhalge. He will dine with Gov Russell, and in the evening, with his wife and daughter, will attend a charity ball}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John_Collins_and_Maurice_Donahue_1960s_Massachsuetts_USA_11191699173.jpg|left|220px|thumb|Maurice Donahue (center), stands behind Boston's [[John F. Collins|Mayor Collins]] (front), c. 1960\u20131968]] \n\nIn the latter half of the 20th century, [[Maurice A. Donahue]] was a Holyoke figure who loomed large in Massachusetts politics. First elected as part of the Commonwealth's first Democratic Party majority in the Massachusetts House of Representatives in 1948, Donahue would go on join the State Senate in 1950, and by 1958 had become the Senate Majority Leader. In this position he lobbied for a number of interests in Western Massachusetts, including for the restoration of the old [[Mount Holyoke]] Prospect Summit House at [[J. A. Skinner State Park]] and its incline railroad. Though the latter is lost to history, the former would be restored in Donahue's lifetime.<ref>{{cite book|title=Cultivating a Past: Essays on the History of Hadley, Massachusetts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R16hSpCuzLQC&pg=PA344|page=344|editor=Marla R. Miller|year=2009|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst, Mass.|isbn = 978-1558497009}}</ref> By 1964 Donahue had risen to the rank of [[President of the Massachusetts Senate]], a position he held until 1971, longer than any Democratic politician in that post before him.<ref>{{cite web|website=Special Collections and University Archives, UMass Libraries|publisher=University of Massachusetts|title=Maurice A. Donahue Papers, 1960-1971|year=2015|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums311|archive-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926042520/http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums311}}</ref> Though a prominent figure in state politics, in a 1976 interview for the [[John F. Kennedy Library]], Donahue would describe John Kennedy's electoral campaigns as lacking the same connections in Holyoke\u2013Chicopee\u2013Springfield as he and his staff had, noting a common respect between the region and Boston but less \"down-the-line Democrat\" territories than rural towns where Kennedy was able to build a substantial ground staff. Donahue's political career would end in 1971 after failing to garner the post of Democrat nominee for governor in the previous year. Choosing not to seek re-election to the senate, he would be appointed as a professor of political science at the University of Massachusetts and became the first director of the Institute for Governmental Services, a publicly funded consultancy and think-tank which would later bear his name, the UMass Donahue Institute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sen. Donahue Named to 2 Posts at UMass|work=Boston Record American|date=December 23, 1970|page=4|location=Boston, Mass.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our Background|website=UMass Donahue Institute|publisher=University of Massachusetts|archive-date=September 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902182757/http://www.donahue.umassp.edu/about-us/background|url=http://www.donahue.umassp.edu/about-us/background}}</ref>\n\n[[File:David M Bartley.jpg|thumb|160px|right|[[David M. Bartley]], c. 1963, as a member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives]]\n\nAnother influential resident of Holyoke in Beacon Hill politics was [[David M. Bartley]], son of a Holyoke police chief James Bartley, who followed a similar career to Donahue's in the [[Massachusetts General Court|General Court]], though in the Massachusetts House rather than the Senate. In describing the difference between the two in a 1969 interview with the ''[[Boston Herald]]'', Bartley noted their views had \"a shade of difference{{nbsp}}... After all Donahue grew up through the depression which I did not. And this has given him a certain different Democratic emphasis\".<ref name=\"1969bartleyherald\">{{cite news|title=Bartley in Line As New Speaker|date=January 2, 1969|page=3|work=Boston Herald}}</ref> Taking the post as Speaker that same year, Bartley was the youngest to assume the second-most powerful political position in Massachusetts in 200 years. As Speaker, Bartley lobbied for what became known as the [[Bartley-Fox Law]], a nationally-studied law which, in 1974, imposed a 1-year [[mandatory minimum sentence]] on anyone possessing an illegal firearm; the law has since received mixed appraisal in its efficacy in curbing violent crime.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Deutsch |first=Stuart Jay |last2=Alt |first2=Francis B. |date=1977-11-01 |title=The Effect of Massachusetts' Gun Control Law On Gun-Related Crimes in the City of Boston |journal=Evaluation Quarterly |language=en |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=543\u2013568 |doi=10.1177/0193841x7700100402 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8-dDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA356 |title=The Oxford Handbook of Law and Economics: Volume 3: Public Law and Legal Institutions |last=Parisi |first=Francesco |date=2017-04-04 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191507205 |pages=356\u20137 |language=en}}</ref> In contrast, Bartley received overwhelming praise for his work in sponsoring, with education committee chairman Michael Daly, what was known as the \"[[Bartley-Daly Law]]\". A culmination of efforts by the Coalition for Special Education, now known as the Federation for Children with Special Needs, the 1971 law removed the legal terms \"mentally retarded\" or \"emotionally disturbed\" and placed them under the broader label, \"school age children with special needs.\" The law would also remove IQ test qualifications, and created a legal mechanism by which parents could appeal student placement, as well as incentivized public schools to accommodate such special needs students by mandating public coverage of their tuitions if they were enrolled in private schools.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Rittenhouse|url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED182956|publisher=Illinois State University|first=Robert K|date=January 14, 1980|series=ED182956|title=The Bartley-Daly Act: Regulations for the Implementation of Chapter 766 of the Acts of 1972: The Comprehensive Special Education Law of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts: An Analysis Within the Context of Public Law 94-142|via=US [[Education Resources Information Center|ERIC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|work=The Harvard Crimson|location=Cambridge, Mass.|archive-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907232946/https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1973/3/12/the-bartley-bill-a-new-philosophy/|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1973/3/12/the-bartley-bill-a-new-philosophy/|title=The Bartley Bill: A New Philosophy in Special Education|last=Bennett|first=Amanda|date=March 12, 1973|publisher=Harvard University}}</ref> The bill, and programs created by Massachusetts school districts in response, would be the subject of extensive study, influencing [[special education]] programs across the United States as the first law providing state funds in the pursuit of \"maximum feasible potential\" of disabled persons in public education.<ref>{{cite web|website=Newsletter (FCSN)|publisher=Federation for Children with Special Needs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717135513/https://fcsn.org/newsletter/2015/springv35n2/from-ed|archive-date=July 17, 2015|url=https://fcsn.org/newsletter/2015/springv35n2/from-ed|title=From the Executive Director: From Humble Beginnings to National Involvement|date=Fall 2015}}</ref> In the wake of a crisis, wherein an estimated 40,000 to 60,000 students were not receiving education in a language they understood, Bartley and Daly also passed the nation's first bilingual state education law, mandating transitional bilingual programs in districts with 20 or more students of inadequate English proficiency, and temporarily waiving certain teacher certification requirements to encourage more with necessary Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese skills to enter the workforce.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands of Non-English-Speaking Children Not in School; Tierney Admits Language Crisis|last=Forman|first=Ian|work=Boston Herald|pages=1, 10}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|title=National Conference, Early Childhood Education and the Chicanito, Pima Community College, Tucson, Arizona, August 3, 4, 5, 1972|page=19|publisher=Pima Community College|editor=Rafael Ch\u00e1vez|year=1972|quote=...{{nbsp}}and [in] 1969 only four Puerto Rican students graduated from Boston high schools. Three years later, through the efforts of Sister Francis Georgia, community leader Alex Rodriguez, the Boston task force, and two key legislators, Education Committee Chairman Michael Daly and House Speaker David Barley [sic], Massachusetts passed the nation's first comprehensive state bilingual education law|oclc=1162872}}</ref> Bartley would leave the legislature in 1975 when he was appointed president of his alma mater [[Holyoke Community College]], a post he retained until 2004.<ref name=\"legendary\">{{cite book|last=Sears|first=Jacqueline M.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mTcrBwAAQBAJ|title=Legendary Locals of Holyoke|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Charleston, S.C.|year=2015|isbn=9781467101813}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n{{further|Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade}}\n[[File:Runners leave the starting line at the 44th annual Holyoke St Patrick's Road Race (2019).jpeg|thumb|right|Runners cross the starting line during the 44th annual St. Patrick's Road Race, 2019]]\n\nMany of Holyoke's Irish cultural events center around the Holyoke St Patrick's Day Parade; leading up to it there are several events, including the Grand Colleen Pageant, typically held the first Saturday in January, of which five young women are selected who go on to the Grand Colleen Ball, at which one is crowned as the parade's Grand Colleen based on presentation and questions related to their Irish heritage.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Queen of the Green|last=Blais|first=Madelaine|pages=58\u201363|magazine=The New York Times Magazine|date=March 26, 1995}}</ref>\n\nOther events include the Grand Marshal Reception, held the second Friday of January,<ref>{{cite web|archive-date=September 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921212309/https://www.masslive.com/news/2019/09/john-j-driscoll-named-grand-marshal-of-2020-holyoke-st-patricks-parade.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2019/09/john-j-driscoll-named-grand-marshal-of-2020-holyoke-st-patricks-parade.html|title=John J. Driscoll named Grand Marshal of 2020 Holyoke St. Patrick's Parade|last=Hohenberger|first=Dennis|date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> a reception at [[The Student Prince (restaurant)|The Student Prince]] in Springfield with participants of the parade such as the Mummers bands and [[Holyoke Caledonian Pipe Band]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Student Prince Cafe, Fort Restaurant begin four-day St. Patrick's Day celebration|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/student-prince-cafe-fort-restaurant-begin-four-day-st-patricks-day-celebration|last=Carretaro|first=Kristina|date=March 14, 2019|work=22 News WWLP-TV}}</ref> and two [[road run]]s. Since 2014, every September the Parade Committee has held the Halfway [[5K run|5K Run]], marking the six months before the next parade, and the better-known [[10k run|10k]], the Holyoke St. Patrick's Day Road Race. Hosted annually the day before the parade since 1975, it has been called by Olympian [[John Treacy]] \"a miniature Boston\", had a record 6,800 contestants complete the course in 2014, and was placed among the best St. Patrick's runs in the nation by ''[[Runner's World]]'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921212644/https://www.masslive.com/sports/2014/09/1st_holyoke_halfway_to_st_patricks_day_road_race_facts_figures.html|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url=https://www.masslive.com/sports/2014/09/1st_holyoke_halfway_to_st_patricks_day_road_race_facts_figures.html|title=1st Holyoke Halfway to St. Patrick's Day Road Race, Facts, Figures|last=Roberts|first=Seth|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=September 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817172445/https://www.masslive.com/sports/2016/03/2016_st_patrick_road_race_fast.html|archive-date=August 17, 2016|url=https://www.masslive.com/sports/2016/03/2016_st_patrick_road_race_fast.html|title=Fast facts about the 2016 Holyoke St. Patrick's Road Race|last=Roberts|first=Seth|date=March 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Runner's World|title=Stellar St. Patrick's Day Runs\n|archive-date=March 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325094317/https://www.runnersworld.com/races-places/g20839691/stellar-st-patricks-day-runs/|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/races-places/g20839691/stellar-st-patricks-day-runs/|last1=Lange|last2=Nall|first1=Ali Taylor|first2=McGee|date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Institutions==\n[[File:StPatricksCommitteeHolyokeMass.svg|left|thumb|Emblem of the Holyoke St. Patrick's Day Parade Committee, which has held its namesake event annually since 1952]]\n\nIn addition to the role played by labor unions, soon after the arrival of Holyoke's Irish workers many of the city's earliest immigrants would organize cultural institutions. By 1865 it was reported that a Circle of the [[Fenian Brotherhood]] had been established.<ref name=\"fenian\">{{cite news|work=Irish American|location=New York|date=October 21, 1865|page=4|title=[Holyoke Circle of the Fenian Brotherhood]}}</ref> Among the early institutions of the Irish were local courts of the [[Catholic Order of Foresters#Massachusetts Foresters|Massachusetts Catholic Order of Foresters]]. According to the Irish Ancestral Research Association, the first of four was organized in 1887,<ref name=\"tiara\">{{cite web|archive-date=September 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908140626/https://tiara.ie/projects/foresters-courts/|url=https://tiara.ie/projects/foresters-courts/|website=The Irish Ancestral Research Association|location=Sudbury, Massachusetts|title=Massachusetts Catholic Order of Foresters Courts Instituted From 1879 To 1935}}</ref> however newspapers from the time reference such groups in Holyoke as early as 1880, a year after the Massachusetts Order was first organized in Boston.<ref name=\"tiara\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=To-Day|quote=At Southwick ponds, picnic Holyoke Foresters|page=5|date=September 8, 1880|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> A [[fraternal benefit society]], the Order was predominantly Irish, but also one of the few groups which, in its Catholic origins, had members of both Irish and French-Canadian backgrounds,<ref name=\"souv\">{{cite book | last1=Alcorn | first1=W. M. |last2=Shirley |first2=P. E.| title=Holyoke, Past and Present Progress and Prosperity; Historical and Industrial Notes | year=1910 | publisher=W.M. Alcorn Souvenir Association | oclc= 50033673 |page=41|url = https://archive.org/stream/holyokepastprese00wmal#page/40/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book  |year=1902  |chapter=The City of Holyoke and the Factors in its History |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/n23/mode/2up |chapter-format= |editor1-last=Copeland |editor1-first=Alfred Minot  |title=\"Our county and its people\" : A history of Hampden County, Massachusetts |volume=III |pages=659 |publisher= The Century Memorial Publishing Company |url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/658/mode/2up |oclc= 5692695963 }}</ref> though not without being at odds over the matter of conduct in the English language.<ref>{{cite news|date=July 9, 1905|page=26|location=Boston|work=Boston Sunday Globe|title=FOR FRENCH ALONE; Holyoke Foresters Want New High Court. Dissatisfaction Because English Is Official Language}}</ref>\n\n===Philo-Celtic Society===\nOne of the few city institutions to define itself by the use of the Irish language, the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society was an Irish cultural group organized by Patrick J. Judge in 1895,<ref>{{cite book|title=Holyoke City Directory, 1900|publisher=Price, Lee & Co.|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=514}}</ref> who sought to make it \"the banner society\" among those in America studying the language and literature, offering free courses to all Irish men and women.<ref name=\"1898IA\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|page=4|work=Irish American|date=March 14, 1898|location=New York}}</ref><ref name=\"1896Philo\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|page=4|work=Irish American|date=January 27, 1896|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|author=Editorship|work=Irish American|date=April 30, 1898|location=New York|page=4|via=NewsBank}}</ref> The society would regularly feature dancing and social functions including regular violin playing of jigs and reels, at most it met on Sundays, Mondays and Fridays in its Emmet Hall, a floor above a \"High Street Bank\", and described itself as being among the only of such societies to have its own hall and regularly meeting three times a week.<ref name=\"1898IA\"/>The platform for its speakers was described as decorated in alternating small American and Irish flags, with a portrait of [[Irish republican]] martyr [[Robert Emmet]] at its center.<ref name=\"sheehymtg\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|date=April 11, 1898|page=1|location=New York|work=Irish American|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\nThough serving its Irish community, the society also sought to promote interest in Irish culture and language to the general public and was known to have published at least one small book described as \"Irish in design as well as partly so in language\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Our Gaelic World|work=Irish World|date=November 5, 1898|page=11|location=New York|quote=At a recent ball given by the Ancient Order of Hibernians of Springfield, Mass., the order of dances was printed in Irish and English. The Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society a short time before showed the example in this regard, having got out a neat little book, Irish in design as well as partly so in language. Every little idea of this kind marks a step forward, and no opportunity of this kind, no matter how small, should be lost to excite the curiousity and the interest of the general public}}</ref> Indeed by 1898 the ''Irish American'' in New York printed remarks made during a meeting of a Providence counterpart which compared New York and Holyoke's societies as comparably outstanding in the advancement of the study of the Irish language among their peers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Providence Irish Language Society|work=Irish American|date=February 7, 1898|location=New York|page=8|quote=The ex-treasurer [of the Providence Society], Mr. M. J. Henehan, was a welcome visitor, and gave an interesting account of the splendid work achieved by other societies he had visited, and urged those present to look out for their laurels, as there was danger that the Philo-Celtic Society of New York and the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society would lead them as to attendance and advancement in studies,\u2014these two bodies showing marked enthusiasm in the good work}}</ref> Though considerably smaller, the population drew regular coverage from the [[Irish in New York City|Irish of New York City]], with the New York ''Irish American'' lauding that \"Holyoke seems to be destined to have the banner Irish Language Society, notwithstanding it has only a population of about 40,000\".<ref name=\"sheehymtg\"/> A similar praise came from New York's ''Irish World'',{{efn|Not to be confused with the 1987 established ''[[The Irish World (London)|The Irish World]]''}} which lauded Holyoke's Philo-Celtics as \"probably ahead of any other societies in the United States in having [their] own rooms and in meeting three times a week. They have quite a few good Irish scholars there, and a number of active workers\".<ref>{{cite news|work=Irish World|location=New York|via=NewsBank|page=7|date=July 9, 1898|title=The Holyoke Philo Celtic Society is probably...}}</ref>\n\nIn 1898, the Holyoke society became a founding organization of the Gaelic League of America, an American counterpart of [[Conradh na Gaeilge]], with 12 other societies including groups from Boston, New York, and Chicago.<ref name=\"IrishIdentity\"/><ref name=\"join\"/><ref name=\"GLD\">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Gael (An Gaodhal)|title=Gaelic League Directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oc0GAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA29|page=33|volume=XX|issue=1|date=January 1901|location=New York}}</ref> The two stated objectives of the League were \"the preservation of Irish as the National Language of Ireland, and the extension of its use as a spoken tongue\" and \"the study and publication of existing Gaelic Literatue, and the cultivation of a modern literature in Irish\".<ref name=\"GLD\"/> Though the Gaelic League and its member societies described themselves as \"non-political and unsectarian\", they were not solely a literary or language movement, but one supporting the Irish Cause abroad in financial assistance, though such societies were rarely patronized by the wealthy.<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://dspace.mic.ul.ie/handle/10395/1529|chapter=American influence on the Gaelic League: Inspiration or control?|title=The Irish Revival Reappraised|location=Dublin|publisher=Four Courts Press|pages=63\u201370|year=2001|last=Bhroim\u00e9il|first=\u00dana N\u00ed}}</ref> By 1908 the Society had also affiliated itself among the ranks of the [[Irish Texts Society]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Publications|volume=10|chapter=List of Members|publisher=Irish Texts Society|page=xix|year=1908|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAQAAIAAJ&pg=PR19}}</ref>\n\n===Hibernians===\nThe Ancient Order of Hibernians Division No.{{nbsp}}1 of Holyoke, now known as the Ancient Order of Hibernians of Hampden/Hampshire Counties, James A. Curran Div.{{nbsp}}1 and Ladies Auxiliary Div.{{nbsp}}2, was first established in February of 1872.<ref>{{cite book|title=Price & Lee's Holyoke City Directory, including South Hadley|year=1884|publisher=Price & Lee Company|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=308}}</ref><ref name=\"curran\">{{cite news|archive-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915193142/https://www.masslive.com/news/2010/11/ancient_order_of_hibernians_na.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2010/11/ancient_order_of_hibernians_na.html|title=Ancient Order of Hibernians naming Holyoke chapter after James Curran|date=November 3, 2010|last=Cahill|first=Patricia|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> Much of Holyoke's international outreach to Ireland would be made through the AOH throughout the decades,<ref>{{cite work|title=Holyoke|quote=A mass-meeting was held at the Hibernian hall last evening to make arrangements for the welcoming meeting to be given Members of Parliament Kettle and Hazelton November 9. The committee of arrangements will be chosen this week, and invitations extended to the Irish people of Holyoke as well as sympathizers with the Irish movement started by T. P. O'Connor and being furthered by Messrs Kettle and Hazelton on their tour, to meet at the Hibernian hall that evening, when arrangements will be made for an overflow meeting|date=October 29, 1906|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"consul1951\">{{cite news|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=32|title=Irish People Said Thankful to Holyokers; Shields, Consul From Ireland, Addresses Alumnae of Elms College|date=April 19, 1951}}</ref><ref name=\"nellie\">{{cite news|title=For Dubin Martyrs; Miss Nellie Gifford Addresses Temperance Hall Meeting|date=December 4, 1916|page=7|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> and the division would host Massachusetts' Hibernian convention in 1904.<ref>{{cite news|title=A. O. H. State Conventions - Massachusetts Hibernians|work=Irish World|location=New York|date=September 3, 1904|page=3}}</ref>\n\nFacing financial difficulties and dwindling membership, Holyoke's AOH credits its continued existence to Holyoke contractor James Curran, who began hosting its meetings with the establishment of his \"Wherehouse\" banquet hall in 1977; the division would be named in his honor in 2010.<ref name=\"curran\"/>\nIn addition to its involvement in organizing the Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade Committee, the AOH continues to organize banquets, fundraisers, and Irish cultural events primarily at The Wherehouse Banquet Hall in the downtown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/cultural-celebration-at-hibernian-irish-night-in-holyoke/|title=Cultural celebration at Hibernian Irish Night in Holyoke|date=February 23, 2019|publisher=22 News, WWLP-TV|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> Of the 16 divisions extant in Massachusetts today, it is the only one remaining west of Worcester, outside the Greater Boston area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Divisions|website=MASSAOH.COM|publisher=Massachusetts State Board Ancient Order of Hibernians in America, Inc.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903043509/http://www.massaoh.com/?page_id=17|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url=http://www.massaoh.com/?page_id=17}}</ref>\n\n===Brian Boru Club===\nOn July 20, 1949, the Brian Boru Club of Holyoke was incorporated as a social club, within the year branching out to sponsor its own basketball team in a local league. One day a couple of business men tossed out the idea of holding a St. Patrick's Parade at a Club meeting, and in the following year the group would work with the Hibernians, fire, and police departments, to organize the first annual Holyoke St. Patrick Day Parade in 1952.<ref name=\"bigday\">{{cite news|title=Big Day in Holyoke|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=1|date=March 22, 1970}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=October 22, 1949|page=30|title=Brian Boru Will Have Cage Team|quote=Organized within the past year, the Brian Boru Club of this city, which has confined itself to social activities, will make its entrance into sports circles by sponsoring a basketball team this coming season}}</ref>\n\nBy 1960, the Club had acquired the former Union Club Hall, designed by [[George P. B. Alderman]] in 1909, and while keeping the Brian Boru name have retained its original liquor license, appearing as \"The Union Club of Holyoke Inc. DBA Brian Boru Club\" in temporary license applications for the St. Patrick's Day Parade as recently as 2016.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217161319/https://www.holyoke.org/events/license-board-meeting-8/|archive-date=February 17, 2017|url=https://www.holyoke.org/events/license-board-meeting-8/|publisher=City of Holyoke|title=License Board Commission Meeting|date=December 21, 2016|quote=The Union Club of Holyoke Inc. DBA Brian Boru Club, 37 Commercial St}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Brian Boru Club Will Keep Name|work=Springfield Union|date=August 18, 1960|page=42|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n\n===Newspapers and publishers===\n[[File:In Gaeldom column on Holyoke and Harlem, Irish American (January 18, 1913, p 5).png|right|thumb|An example of [[Irish language]] coverage set in [[Gaelic type|Gaelic script]], of a [[feis]] in Holyoke; as it appeared in New York City's ''Irish American'' newspaper, 1913]]\n\nMuch of the Irish community's affairs were documented in the ''[[Holyoke Transcript-Telegram]]'', with its publishers including Mary \"Minnie\" Dwight (n\u00e9e Ryan), a daughter of Irish immigrants, who was the first female editor of the paper following the death of her husband William G. Dwight, from 1930 until her death in 1957.<ref name=\"senior\">\"William Dwight, 92, Holyoke Publisher\". Obituary. ''Union-News'', Springfield, Mass. June 5, 1996.</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Stories Carved in Stone: Holyoke, Massachusetts|last=Clark|first=Rusty|year=2006|publisher=Dog Pond Press|location=West Springfield, Mass.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J_elq5tHqQIC&pg=PA172|page=172|isbn=9780975536261}}</ref> Ms. Dwight would also be the first woman to receive an honorary degree from the [[University of Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|website=UMass Physical Plant|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|archive-date=May 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505074919/https://www.umass.edu/physicalplant/dwight-minnie-e-ryan|url=https://www.umass.edu/physicalplant/dwight-minnie-e-ryan|title=Dwight, Minnie E. Ryan - Residential Hall}}</ref> In contrast with other communities, no major circulars were published specifically covering Irish community and much of their stories were those of the daily press, covered in the ''Transcript'' until its closure in 1994, as well as the ''Springfield Union'' and ''[[Springfield Republican]]'' of the late 19th century to the present day. However, in New York City's [[Irish American journalism|Irish press]] the community would see extensive coverage in both [[English language|English]] and [[Irish language|Irish]] from the 1860s through the 1920s, including such papers as the ''Irish American'', ''Irish Nation'', and ''Irish World''.<ref>{{cite web|url-access=subscription|url=https://www.genealogybank.com/explore/newspapers/all/usa/new-york/new-york?fname=&lname=&fullname=&kwinc=Holyoke&kwexc=&rgfromDate=&rgtoDate=&formDate=&formDateFlex=exact&dateType=range&pub%5B0%5D=irish-american&pub%5B1%5D=irish-nation&pub%5B2%5D=irish-world|website=GenealogyBank|publisher=Newsbank|title=New York City Newspaper Archives|access-date=11 August 2019|postscript=. [Filtered for ''Irish American'', ''Irish Nation'', and ''Irish World'']}}</ref> Even today the city's St. Patrick's Day Parade and announcements related to the Hibernians and other groups are covered by Manhattan's ''[[The Irish Echo]]'', as well as ''[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=[Search for 'Holyoke']|archive-date=September 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908023208/https://www.irishecho.com/?s=Holyoke|url=https://www.irishecho.com/?s=Holyoke|access-date=September 7, 2019|publisher=The Irish Echo}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Holyoke's Irish Heart|magazine=Irish America|publisher=Irish America, LLC|archive-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910085504/https://irishamerica.com/2009/06/holyokes-irish-heart/|url=https://irishamerica.com/2009/06/holyokes-irish-heart/|last=Harty|first=Patricia}}</ref>\n\n==International relations==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | The Holyoke Catholic Benevolent Society has proved by its action that its works of benevolence are not confined to its members; but that it looks above and beyond its local duties, and sees that there is another work of the purest benevolence to be done, and charitably and patriotically it comes forward to assist in its accomplishment.\n\nWe hope the example given by this society will be followed by the other Irish societies in the United States and Canada, that are independent of the Brotherhood, and it will show to the world that though Irishmen are not all members of the Fenian Brotherhood, yet their hearts are united in the one grand object, the liberation of Ireland\u2014from Hudson's Bay to Long Island Sound, from the Pacific to the Atlantic, and from the Ganges to the Shannon.<br>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\"|&mdash;I remain respectfully yours,<br>Patrick McGee<br>Secretary\n|-\n| style=\"border-top: 1px solid black;\"|Vote of thanks given by Holyoke Circle of the Fenian Brotherhood for $100 given to them by the Benevolent Society, declared Sept. 30, 1865, and printed in the New York ''Irish American'' and the ''Boston Pilot''<ref name=\"fenian\"/>\n|-\n|}\nIn a speech at the Roger Smith Hotel in 1951 to alumni of [[Elms College]], the Irish consul at Boston, Joseph F. Shields would describe Holyoke as \"very well known among the people of Ireland,\" especially for its support of The Cause.<ref name=\"consul1951\"/> In its history, Holyoke's Irish would maintain relations between the Emerald Isle, and their newfound home in the Commonwealth, and receive numerous figures and officials during [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British rule]] and independence thereafter, often raising funds for the cause of Irish republicanism.\n\nBetween [[Fenian raids|the raids of 1866 and 1871]], [[John O'Neill (Fenian)|General John O'Neill]] of the [[Fenian Brotherhood]] would make a stop in Holyoke on March 13, 1868, as an honored guest of the Brotherhood's unit in that city. With the meeting chaired by builder John Delaney, O'Neill would rally Holyoke's Irish men and women, saying they must be \"ready and willing to aid their suffering native land by money and men in its struggle for Irish liberty.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Gen. O'Neill in Holyoke|date=April 4, 1868|work=Irish American|page=4|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nIn 1887 the ''[[New York Herald]]'' reported that Mayor [[James J. O'Connor]] presided over a meeting organized by a local body of the Irish national league hosting [[Irish Home Rule movement|Home Rule]] members of parliament, [[Sir Thomas Esmonde, 11th Baronet|Sir Thomas Esmonde]] and [[Arthur O'Connor (MP)|Arthur O'Connor]] during their tour of the Commonwealth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Urging Ireland's Cause; the Irish Ambassadors Address a Meeting at Holyoke|date=October 9, 1887|work=New York Herald|location=New York|page=13}}\n:* {{cite news|title=Speeches at Fall River|date=October 8, 1887|page=2|location=Savannah, Ga.|work=Morning News}}</ref> Received by a large party of local politicians including [[William Whiting II|Congressman William Whiting]] and former Mayor [[William B. C. Pearsons]], the two offered speeches decrying British rule to rousing applause from what was described as one of the largest audiences ever in the [[Holyoke City Hall]] up until that time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anti-Coercian at Holyoke; Last Night's Demonstration; With Speeches by Thomas Grattan Esmonde and Arthur O'Connor|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=October 9, 1887|page=7|work=Springfield Republican}}</ref>\n\nIn 1898 the Philo-Celtic Society would host [[Eugene Sheehy (priest)|Rev. Father Eugene Sheehy]] of County Limerick for one of their meetings. Sheehy would offer a speech titled the \"Language and Music of Our Race\" to a packed Emmet Hall, including a delegation from the Springfield Irish Language Society. A series of traditional tunes such as ''Barney, Come Home'' and ''The Meeting of the Waters'' were played and the meeting concluded with Sheehy reciting the [[Lord's Prayer]] in [[Irish language|Irish]].<ref name=\"sheehymtg\"/>\n\nOn May 17, 1903, the United Irish League's Holyoke chapter would host Mr. [[Joseph Devlin]], Irish journalist and future MP, who, with [[Arthur Chapin|Mayor Chapin]] presiding, spent the evening discussing the ramifications of Ireland's [[Irish Land Acts#Wyndham Land (Purchase) Act 1903|Wyndham Land Act]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Mass-Meeting at Holyoke; the City Hall was Crowded to Hear Messrs Devlin and Mitchell\u2014Mayor Chapin Presided|date=May 18, 1903|page=12|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> Three years later on November 9, 1906, [[Nathan P. Avery|Mayor Avery]] would receive MPs [[Richard Hazleton]], and [[Tom Kettle]] during their tour of the United States for the Cause. Describing the realities of British rule and progress made toward independence, the two would draw comparison between the independence of the United States and Ireland from the Crown and during the evening some $700, about $20,000 in 2017 US Dollars, was raised.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irish Envoys at Holyoke; an Enthusiastic Reception|date=November 10, 1906|page=7|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 1911, [[Michael O'Flanagan]] [[Shane Leslie]] gave speeches at Holyoke's Empire Theater at the behest of the local Ladies' Division of the Hibernians as envoys of the [[Gaelic League]].<ref>{{cite news|title=In Gaeldom; Father O'Flanagan and Shane Leslie Plead for Irish Ireland at Holyoke, Mass.|page=1|work=Irish American|location=New York|date=November 27, 1911}}</ref> Following the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916, in December of that year [[Nellie Gifford]] was hosted in the city, remarking her pleasant surprise to see the [[Statue of Liberty]] represented as a woman, and giving her account of the events of the preceding months, including the [[Proclamation of the Irish Republic]] and the possibility of moving further toward Irish independence.<ref name=\"nellie\"/>\n\nEven after [[Proclamation of the Irish Republic|Irish independence]], the city would receive members of the Irish Republic. In 1966, [[Se\u00e1n Flanagan]], minister of health in the Irish government, would be an honored guest among those marching in the St. Patrick's Day Parade,<ref>{{cite news|title=Colorful Floats, Marching Units Take Over Holyoke|date=March 21, 1966|page=11|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> and in recent years the city would twice host [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] leader [[Gerry Adams]]. Adams would march in the parade in 2006 and 2015, giving a press conference at City Hall at his first appearance, as a guest of honor by Congressman [[Richard Neal]], a Holyoke Community College alumnus,<ref>Neal, Richard E. \"[http://www.house.gov/neal/link4.html Biography].\" ''Congressman Richard Neal'' (official website). [[United States House of Representatives]].</ref> who worked with both the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] and [[Ulster loyalism|Ulster loyalists]] and members of Congress to ensure an American role in Irish peace after the [[Good Friday Agreement]].<ref>{{cite news|archive-date=September 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914223302/http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/03/19/sinn_feins_adams_detained_at_airport/|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/03/19/sinn_feins_adams_detained_at_airport/|title=Sinn Fein's Adams detained at airport|publisher=Associated Press|date=March 19, 2006|via=Boston.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|archive-date=August 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820064407/https://www.masslive.com/entertainment/2015/03/faces_of_the_holyoke_st_patric.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/entertainment/2015/03/faces_of_the_holyoke_st_patric.html|work=The Republican|title=Faces of the Holyoke St. Patrick's Day Parade|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=March 2015|last=Kelly|first=Ray}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|archive-date=September 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914222947/https://www.masslive.com/news/2014/04/gerry_adams_sinn_fein_leader_s.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2014/04/gerry_adams_sinn_fein_leader_s.html|title=Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein leader arrested for suspected involvement in 40-year-old murder, has strong ties to Western Massachusetts|date=May 1, 2014|last=Johnson|first=Patrick}}</ref><ref name=\"cq-2004\">Duncan, Philip D., and Nutting, Brian (eds.) (2004). \"Neal, Richard E., D-Mass.\" ''[[CQ's Politics in America|CQ's Politics in America 2004: The 108th Congress]]''. Washington: [[Congressional Quarterly]]. pp. 483\u2013484. {{ISBN|978-1-56802-813-2}}.</ref> In 2017, Mayor [[Alex Morse]] would work with Neal's office to formally establish a [[sister city]] relationship between Holyoke and [[Tralee]], of [[County Kerry]], mirroring a sister city agreement with neighboring Springfield.<ref>{{cite web|author=Plaisance, Mike|url=http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2017/04/exchange_program_linking_holyo.html|title=School exchange program linking Holyoke, Tralee, Ireland benefit of sister-city relationship: Mayor Alex Morse|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426142811/http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2017/04/exchange_program_linking_holyo.html|archive-date=April 26, 2017|date=April 26, 2014|accessdate=August 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mayor Sarno and Congressman Neal Welcome Toireasa Ferris, Kerry County Councilor for Tralee, Ireland|publisher=City of Springfield (Mass.)|url=https://www3.springfield-ma.gov/cos/index.php?id=news-story&tx_news_pi1%5Bnews%5D=13663&tx_news_pi1%5Bcontroller%5D=News&tx_news_pi1%5Baction%5D=detail&cHash=424e591bef53bcd4ec20616318b03f43|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Saint Patrick Chapel, Saint Jerome Church, Holyoke, Massachusetts.JPG|thumb|left|The Saint Patrick Chapel at Saint Jerome Parish]]\n\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 180\n   | align = right\n   | footer = The John F. Kennedy Memorial, at the corner of Suffolk and Appleton in front of Our Lady of the Cross Parish, dedicated in 1967; Holyoke Police officers lead the St. Patrick's Parade with the colors of the Holyoke, Ireland, and the United States\n   | image1 = John_F._Kennedy_Memorial,_Holyoke,_Massachusetts.jpg\n   | image2 = Flag carrying officers lead the 2019 Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade.jpg}}\nToday Holyoke's Irish leave the legacy of not only the cultural institutions and structures they built but also the cultural diaspora. Perhaps most famously at the start of the 20th century, two brothers from Holyoke, the Sheas, would contribute a song which resonates in popular culture to this day. The [[Victory March (fight song)|Victory March]] of [[Fighting Irish|Notre Dame's Fighting Irish]], was first written and publicly performed in Holyoke in the winter of 1908 by John and Rev. Michael Shea, both alumni of the college. Michael Shea was the organist for [[St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)|St. Patrick's Cathedral]] in New York City at that time, and returned to Holyoke to devise the song with his brother who lived there. Shortly after completing their composition, Father Michael would run into his childhood music teacher, Professor [[William C. Hammond (organist)|William C. Hammond]] of [[Mount Holyoke College]], who was the music director of the Second Congregational Church. Upon telling Hammond about their aspiring rally song, Hammond suggested Shea perform it in on the church's organ, and in 1908 the fight song for a world renowned Catholic research university was first publicly performed at a Protestant church in Holyoke. At the conclusion of the performance, a group of the church's deacons walked in and \"were not a little shocked to see a man wearing a Roman collar energetically thumping away on the keys of their organ. One deacon had a remark to make when the recital was finished. 'Brother,' he said, 'you've got something there.'\"<ref>{{cite book|pages=209\u2013210|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.80345#page/n221/mode/2up/|title=The Notre Dame Story|year=1949|last=Wallace|first=Francis|publisher=Rinehart & Company, Inc|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Catholic Digest|volume=7|title=He Had Something|year=1942|publisher=College of St. Thomas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5wUAAAAIAAJ|quote=They[, the church deacons,] were not a little shocked to see a man wearing a Roman collar energetically thumping away on the keys of their organ. One deacon had a remark to make when the recital was finished. 'Brother,' he said, 'you've got something there'\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=Game Day|publisher=University of Notre Dame|archive-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915212434/https://gameday.nd.edu/traditions/notre-dame-music/victory-march/|url=https://gameday.nd.edu/traditions/notre-dame-music/victory-march/|title=Notre Dame Victory March}}</ref> The tune has since been described by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' and [[CBS Sports]] as the most recognizable fight song in college football today.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 15 all-time greatest college football fight songs, ranked|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/photos/best-college-football-fight-songs/15/|archive-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915215222/https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/photos/best-college-football-fight-songs/|quote=1. \"Victory March\" (Notre Dame Fighting Irish) Whether or not you're a fan of the Fighting Irish, you gotta admit that few fight songs in college football carry the prestige, recognition and gravitas as that of Notre Dame's \"Victory March.\" The song was composed in 1908 by two brothers who had attended Notre Dame, John and Michael Shea, and went on to make an appearance in the classic 1940 biographical film, ''Knute Rockne, All American''|website=CBS Sports|date=August 19, 2015}}</ref>\n \n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | \"It is nice to be Irish anytime, but it is especially nice on March 17 in Holyoke\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\"|&mdash;Sen. John F. Kennedy, receiving inaugural parade award as a Distinguished American of Irish Descent, March 16, 1958<ref>{{cite news|title=Colorful Tribute Paid Irish; Kennedy is Hailed As Great Example of Irish American|pages=1, 7|date=March 17, 1958|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\nFollowing a memorial mass at Holy Cross Parish, on May 30, 1967, a year after [[Ted Kennedy]] received his brother's namesake award and marched in the St. Patrick's Parade,<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards|archive-date=July 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710153941/https://holyokestpatricksparade.com/awards/|url=https://holyokestpatricksparade.com/awards/|publisher=Holyoke St. Patrick's Parade Committee|year=2019}}</ref> the Parade Committee dedicated a bust of John F. Kennedy at the corner of Suffolk and Appleton Streets. Presiding over the ceremony were Mayor [[Daniel F. Dibble]], Bishop [[Christopher Joseph Weldon]], Maurice J. Ferriter, and William Rogers, who all played active roles in fundraising for the monument. Cousin Robert P. Fitzgerald would be in attendance, and although the ceremony was unable to be attended by Ted or [[Bobby Kennedy]], the former would make a special phone call to the dedication site from Washington, and the latter would send a telegram noting their late brother's affection for Holyoke and its people. [[David M. Bartley]] would serve as the ceremonies key speaker.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bust of Kennedy Dedicated in Holyoke|page=21|work=The Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=May 31, 1967}}</ref> The memorial remains a part of the ceremonies of the St. Patrick's Day Parade events every year.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921230701/https://www.masslive.com/news/2017/02/irish_flag_raised_in_holyoke_k.html|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2017/02/irish_flag_raised_in_holyoke_k.html|title=Irish flag raised in Holyoke, kicking off St. Patrick's Day Parade celebrations|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Elizabeth|date=February 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn recent decades Irish identity in the Holyoke area has seen renewed interest in language. As recently as 2016 Holyoke Community College maintained a small Irish Studies department offering coursework in Island Literature, Culture, and the study of the Irish diaspora,<ref>{{cite report|title=2016 Course Equivalency Guide|publisher=Holyoke Community College|url=https://www.hcc.edu/Documents/Courses-Programs/Transfer/Westfieldcourseguide.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713062221/https://www.hcc.edu/Documents/Courses-Programs/Transfer/Westfieldcourseguide.pdf|archive-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> and today Elms College in Chicopee offers a minor in Irish Studies.<ref>{{cite report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811192230/https://www.elms.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Fact-Book-2018.pdf|url=https://www.elms.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Fact-Book-2018.pdf|archive-date=August 11, 2019|publisher=Elms College|title=Fact Book 2018}}</ref> The latter was largely created through the efforts of local scholar Thomas Moriarty, a professor emeritus of history. Moriarty, along with Sister Kathleen Keating, then-president of Elms, and Sean Cahillane, would launch the Irish Cultural Center at the college in 1999, and in 2015 it was spun off into a separate entity, the Irish Cultural Center of Western New England based out of [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]]. Sponsored in part by the [[Irish Abroad Unit|Emigrant Support Programme]] of the Government of Ireland, today the center offers classes in the Irish language as well as tours of Ireland, and hosts events around Irish cuisine, literature, and song.<ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Cultural Center of Western New England|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811191641/https://www.irishcenterwne.org/|archive-date=August 11, 2019|url=https://www.irishcenterwne.org/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811192226/https://www.masslive.com/news/2015/07/iirish_cultural_center_announces_move_from_elms_college_to_former_elks_lodge_in_west_springfield.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2015/07/iirish_cultural_center_announces_move_from_elms_college_to_former_elks_lodge_in_west_springfield.html|archive-date=August 11, 2019|title=Irish Cultural Center announces move from Elms College to former Elks Lodge in West Springfield|work=The Republican|last=Flynn|first=Anne-Gerard}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\nAmong Holyoke's few literary works was Mary Doyle Curran's ''The Parish and the Hill''. Published in 1948 by [[Houghton Mifflin]], it was the only novel its author would publish, and would be republished by the [[City University of New York]]'s [[Feminist Press]] in 1986 and 2002; their editors lauded it as \"one of the first to explore Irish life from a woman's point of view\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Parish and the Hill|last=Curran|first=Mary Doyle|oclc=1025481370|publisher=Feminist Press at the City University of New York}}</ref> Described by ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' as an \"evocative, effective picture of the disintegration occurring when prejudicial discrimination and derision uproots the pride of nationality\", the book shows the hardships of a first generation Irish immigrant family of the later waves, and their \"climb from shanty Irish to lace curtain Irish\".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Kirkus Reviews|location=New York|archive-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907203440/https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/mary-doyle-curran/the-parish-and-the-hill/|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/mary-doyle-curran/the-parish-and-the-hill/|title=The Parish and the Hill \u2013 Kirkus Review|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> Curran's poetry was featured in the Boston literary journal ''[[Ploughshares]]'' in 1979, and posthumously her unpublished anthology ''The Paper City'' has been featured in ''MELUS'', the journal of the [[The Society for the Study of the Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States|Society for the Study of the Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]], for early portrayals of the uneasy interethnic relations between early Irish and French immigrant arrivals as well as attitudes toward an indifferent Yankee upper class.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Ploughshares|publisher=Emerson College|location=Boston|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907203842/https://www.pshares.org/authors/mary-doyle-curran|url=https://www.pshares.org/authors/mary-doyle-curran|archive-date=September 7, 2019|title=Mary Doyle Curran}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/467499|title=Mary Doyle Curran: 'Over These Prison Walls I Would Fly'|last=Halley|first=Anne|journal=MELUS|volume=15|issue=3|date=Autumn 1988|pages=3\u20136|jstor=467499}}</ref> Toward the end of her career Curran would head the Irish Studies department at [[UMass Boston]], today the university offers a need-based creative writing scholarship to both graduate and undergraduate students in her name.<ref>{{cite web|website=UMass Boston College of Liberal Arts|publisher=University of Massachusetts|access-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907205611/https://www.umb.edu/academics/cla/english/prizes_and_scholarships|archive-date=September 7, 2019|url=https://www.umb.edu/academics/cla/english/prizes_and_scholarships|title=Prizes and Scholarships for English Majors}}</ref> Today Curran's papers and unpublished manuscripts are in the Special Collections of the [[W.E.B. DuBois Library]] at [[UMass Amherst]].<ref>{{cite web|website=Special Collections and University Archives|publisher=UMass Amherst|title=Mary Doyle Curran Papers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907210833/http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums435|archive-date=September 7, 2019|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums435}}</ref>\n\nThough not as specifically discussing the social conditions of Irish families in Holyoke, 20th-century American novelist [[Raymond Kennedy]] would draw heavily on his own childhood in the city in his works, portraying several in a fictional backdrop of the city, identified by its historical moniker as \"Ireland Parish\".<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|url=https://wwwz.nytimes.com/1988/04/17/books/paperback-her-mind-ran-to-lurid-extremes.html|title=PAPERBACK; Her Mind Ran to Lurid Extremes|last=Huggan|first=Isabel|date=April 17, 1988}}</ref><ref name=\"legendary\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Fifty Years of Marching Together 1952-2001: A Social History of the St. Patrick's Committee of Holyoke, Massachusetts Parade|last1=Gold|first1=Catherine Dower|location=Westhampton, Mass.|year=2001|publisher=Edgar C. Alward & Jean A. Alward; Esparto Press}}\n* {{cite book | last1=Harper | first=Wyatt E. | title=The Story of Holyoke | year=1973 | publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke | oclc=8060402 |url = https://archive.org/stream/storyofholyoke00harp#page/n0/mode/2up}}\n* {{cite book | last=Hartford |first=William F. | title=Working people of Holyoke : class and ethnicity in a Massachusetts mill town, 1850\u20131960|location=New Brunswick, NJ.| publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1990| isbn= 9780813515762|oclc= 21041495}}\n* {{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=izf0clTZf7cC&pg=PA61|pages=61\u201371|chapter=Chapter 8: Irish Immigrants Build Holyoke|last1=Juravich|last2=Hartford|last3=Green|first1=Tom|first2=William F.|first3=James R.|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst, Mass.|year=1996|title=Commonwealth of Toil, Chapters in the History of Massachusetts Workers and Their Unions|oclc=34598201}}\n* {{cite book|title=History of St. Jerome's Parish, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Diocese of Springfield; issued in connection with the Observance of its Diamond Jubilee|year=1931|last=Lucey|first=P. J.|publisher=Diocese of Springfield|location=Holyoke, Mass.|oclc=42457185}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Irish Legacy: A History of the Irish in Western Massachusetts|year=2012|location=Springfield, Mass.|publisher=The Republican|oclc=819651686}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://aoh-holyoke.com/ Ancient Order of Hibernians of Hampden/Hampshire Counties], Holyoke, Massachusetts\n* [https://www.irishcenterwne.org/ Irish Cultural Center of Western New England], West Springfield, Massachusetts\n* [https://lvirishslowsession.wordpress.com/ Lower Valley Irish Slow Session], Irish traditional music session based in Holyoke\n* [http://ourpluralhistory.stcc.edu/industrial/irish.html Irish Immigrants in Holyoke], Our Plural History, Springfield Technical Community College\n\n{{Holyoke, Massachusetts}}\n{{Irish Americans by location}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Holyoke, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture by city]]\n[[Category:Irish-American history]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:History of Holyoke, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Irish people in Holyoke\n| native_name      = ''\u00c9ireannaigh Holyoke''\n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Banquet held by Holyoke Irish Centennial Anniversary Committee 1973.jpg\n| image_caption    = Attendees of a banquet held by the Holyoke Irish Centennial Anniversary Committee, 1973\n| total            = 6,076\n| total_year       = 2010\n| total_source     = <!-- source of total population; may be ''census'' or ''estimate'' -->\n| total_ref        = <!-- references supporting total population -->\n| genealogy        = \n| regions          = <!-- for e.g. a list of regions (countries), especially if regionN etc below not used -->\n\n| region1          = <!-- first region (country)'s name -->\n| pop1             = <!-- population in first region -->\n| ref1             = <!-- <ref>erence/s supporting pop1 data -->\n| region2          = \n| pop2             = \n| ref2             = \n| region3          = \n| pop3             = \n| ref3             = \n<!-- etc, to: -->\n| region33         = \n| pop33            = \n| ref33            = \n\n| languages        = [[American English]],<br>[[Irish language]] <small>(in 19th century, rare)</small>\n| religions        = \n| footnotes        = \n}}\n{{Ethnic Holyoke sidebar}}\n\nFrom the beginning of the city's history as the western bank of [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]], Irish families have resided in and contributed to the development of the civics and culture of [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]]. Among the first appellations given to the city were the handles \"Ireland\", \"Ireland Parish\", or \"Ireland Depot\", after the village was designated the 3rd Parish of [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]] in 1786.<ref name=Holland1855>{{cite book |last=Holland |first=Josiah Gilbert |date=1855 |title=History of Western Massachusetts; the counties of Hampden, Hampshire, Franklin, and Berkshire |url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofwestern02holluoft#page/70/mode/2up |location=Springfield, Mass. |publisher=Samuel Bowles |pages=70 |isbn= |author-link= |quote=On the 7th of July, 1786, the part of West Springfield now embraced in Holyoke was incorporated as the Third Parish of West Springfield, and was called 'Ireland', and 'Ireland Parish', from the fact that several Irish families were the first settlers of the territory, though there is no record of the date of their settlement}}</ref> Initially occupied by a mixture of [[Yankee#Early usage|Yankee English]] and [[Irish Protestant]] families, many of whom belonged to the Baptist community of [[Elmwood, Holyoke, Massachusetts|Elmwood]], from 1840 through 1870 the area saw a large influx of [[Irish Catholic]] workers, immigrants to the United States, initially from the exodus of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]].<ref name=\"constance\">{{cite book | last1=Green | first=Constance McLaughlin|chapter=XII. Social Life|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.59808/2015.59808.Holyoke-Massachusetts-A-Case-History-Of-The-Inkistrial-Revolution-In-America#page/n387/mode/2up/search/1889 |author-link=Constance McLaughlin Green|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.59808/2015.59808.Holyoke-Massachusetts-A-Case-History-Of-The-Inkistrial-Revolution-In-America#page/n11/mode/2up|title=Holyoke, Massachusetts; a case history of the industrial revolution in America | year=1939 | publisher=Yale University Press |location = New Haven |series=Yale Historical Publications|number=XXXIV}}</ref> During that period Irish immigrants and their descendants comprised the largest demographic in Holyoke and built much of the early city's infrastructure, including the dams, canals, and factories.<ref name=\"modern\">{{cite book|last=Zuckerman|first=Molly K|title=Modern Environments and Human Health: Revisiting the Second Epidemiologic Transition|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2014|page=165|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EdYVAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT165&lpg=PT165&dq=prue+french+holyoke#v=onepage&q=&f=false|isbn=9781118504291}}</ref> Facing early hardships from [[Anti-Irish sentiment]], Holyoke's Irish would largely build the early [[Labor unions in the United States|labor movement]] of the city's textile and paper mills, and remained active in the national [[Irish nationalist]] and [[Gaelic revival]] movements of the United States, with the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society being one of 13 signatory organizations creating the Gaelic League of America, an early 20th century American counterpart of [[Conradh na Gaeilge]].<ref name=\"IrishIdentity\">{{cite book|title=Building Irish Identity in America, 1870-1915: The Gaelic Revival|last=Bhroim\u00e9il|first=\u00dana N\u00ed|year=2003|page=51|publisher=Four Courts|location=Dublin|oclc=238503444}}</ref><ref name=\"join\">{{cite magazine|magazine=F\u00e1inne an lae|year=1898|page=27|quote=From the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society which, at the close of its last session, affiliated with the Gaelic League here, comes a very hearty fraternal greeting|title=[\"From the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society\"]}}</ref>\n\nChanges in industry and culture, and successive waves of different immigrant demographics would displace the Irish community to an extent, however the demographic remained an active identity in civic life throughout the 20th century. The Irish community today organizes the largest public event held in Holyoke annually, the [[Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade]], with representatives from surrounding towns and cities, which has gradually become a collective celebration for people of Irish parentage as well as the city's syncretic culture. Today people of Irish ancestry are the second largest demographic in Holyoke and the largest non-Hispanic group, representing about 15% of all residents, and 17% of residents of Hampden County, the second-largest single group by ancestry.<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0600000US2501330840|title=DP02 Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006\u20132010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates for Holyoke, Massachusetts|accessdate=August 11, 2019|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213161216/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0600000US2501330840|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US25013|title=DP02 Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006\u20132010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates for Hampden County, Massachusetts|accessdate=August 11, 2019|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early settlement and Ireland Parish===\n[[File:Ireland, the 3rd Parish of West Springfield, Holyoke (1827).png|right|thumb|One of the earliest maps of Holyoke, as \"Ireland, or 3<sup>d</sup> Parish of Springfield\", often corrupted as \"Ireland Parish\", 1827]]\n\nWhile the earliest settlers of Springfield would largely be of Yankee English stock, the first of the residents of the 3rd Parish of West Springfield were Irish immigrants who began settling in the region before the construction of the dam and industrialization that followed, granting the area the name \"Ireland\" or \"Ireland Parish.\" Colonists had claimed lands by 1655, and early accounts refer to John Riley as the first permanent settler of Holyoke,<ref>{{cite book|quote=[T]he dwellers on the west side are spoken of in old records as 'our neighbors'{{nbsp}}... John Riley went as far away as the southern part of the present Holyoke and may be considered as the first settler of that city.|last=Barrows|first=Charles Henry|title=The History of Springfield in Massachusetts for the Young|publisher=The Connecticut Valley Historical Society|year=1911|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyspringfi00barrgoog/page/n52 88]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyspringfi00barrgoog}}</ref><ref name=\"storyof\">{{cite book | last1=Harper | first=Wyatt E. | title=The Story of Holyoke | year=1973 | publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke | oclc=8060402 |url = https://archive.org/stream/storyofholyoke00harp#page/172/mode/2up}}</ref>{{rp|12}} but though Riley owned 28 acres along \"Riley's Brook\" (Tannery Brook in modern-day [[Ingleside, Holyoke, Massachusetts|Ingleside]]), his daughters Mary and Margaret, and their [[Irish Protestant]] husbands, Joseph Ely and William MacCranny, would first establish their homesteads in 1667.<ref name=\"stone\">{{cite book|title=Stories Carved in Stone: Holyoke, Massachusetts|last=Clark|first=Rusty|year=2006|publisher=Dog Pond Press|location=West Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>{{rp|10}} By the time West Springfield was partitioned in 1707, numerous Irish families had moved to the Parish, and eventually it was chartered as such, the 3rd Parish of West Springfield, on July 7, 1786. Quickly it gained the nickname '''Ireland''', for in those days a number of other families had joined the descendants of the Elys and MacCrannys; these names have also been in the past combined into the better known '''Ireland Parish''' handle.<ref>{{cite book|title=The History of the First Baptist Church of Holyoke, Mass; Together with the Proceedings of the Centennial Services|last=Hungate|first=Jesse A.|location=Holyoke, Mass.|year=1904}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke Celebrates Semi-Centennial; Holyoke's History Had Its Roots in Ireland Parish|page=31|work=Springfield Republican|date=September 2, 1923|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland Depot era===\n[[File:Dam workers construct the first or second Holyoke Dam c1849.jpg|right|thumb|Dam workers pose for a group photo during the construction of the first or second timber dam, c. 1848\u20131849]]\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 230\n   | align = left\n   | footer = The contrast between \"The Patch\" (''top''), and 1840s worker housing in \"The Flats\" (''bottom''); within a generation most Irish laborers would find improved conditions representative of the latter, as \"New City\" and its infrastructure were built from field and forest\n   | image1 = The Patch, Holyoke, circa 1850s.jpg\n   | image2 = HolyokeMA CompanyHousing.jpg}}\n\nThe growth of the Irish community up until this time can be found in birth records of West Springfield, of which Holyoke was its 3rd parish. In 1847 there were 14 births, none of which were of Irish surnames, but by 1848, 19 of 87 were, and by 1849 105 out of 221 West Springfield births were of Irish parentage.<ref name=\"stjeromes\">{{cite book|title=History of St. Jerome's Parish, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Diocese of Springfield; issued in connection with the Observance of its Diamond Jubilee|year=1931|author=P. J. Lucey|publisher=Diocese of Springfield|location=Holyoke, Mass.|oclc=42457185}}</ref>{{rp|24}} Many of the new arrivals came to find work in the construction of the dam and the factories that would be built with it. In the fall of 1848 the Hadley Falls Company put their building lots on the market, and of these lots, many were purchased by recently-arrived Irish. From these arrivals there formed three small villages, the abodes of the [[Hadley Falls Company Housing District|Hadley Falls Company Housing]], otherwise known as the \"North Flats\" at the time, designed by mill engineer John Chase, and built by one Charles MacClellan.<ref>[http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=HLY.36 HLY.36], MACRIS, Massachusetts Historical Commission.</ref> Long lost to history there existed two smaller shanty villages, \"The Patch\", lying where [[Pulaski Park (Holyoke, Massachusetts)|Pulaski Park]] stands today,<ref name=\"storyof\"/>{{rp|41}} and \"The Bush\", a series of dwellings in the fields of [[South Holyoke]].<ref name=\"stjeromes\"/>{{rp|24}} Another early settlement, simply referred to as \"The Field\", would be rechristened \"Ireland Depot\" with the arrival of the railroad in 1845,<ref>{{cite book|title=Immigrant and Native Families: The Impact of Immigration on the Demographic Transformation of Western Massachusetts, 1850 to 1900|last=Golden|first=Hilda H|publisher=University Press of America|location=Lanham, Md.|page=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4yOkZ-cGb60C&pg=PA3|isbn=9780819192875|year=1994}}</ref> today being part of the broader-defined \"The Flats\" or more specifically \"Depot Hill\", which was used for tillage predating the development of the grid and [[Holyoke Canal System|canal system]].<ref>{{cite book |year=1891|editor1-last=Warner |editor1-first=Charles F.  |editor2-last=Johnson |editor2-first=Clifton |title=Picturesque Hampden |script-title= |trans-title= |url=https://archive.org/stream/picturesquehampd00warn#page/n0/mode/2up  |series=Picturesque Massachusetts Series |volume=Part II - West |location=Northampton, Mass. |publisher=Picturesque Publishing Company |pages=1\u2013152|oclc= 70679168 }}</ref>{{rp|7}}\n\nIn contrast with the skilled-labor class and the rowhouses of the Hadley Falls Company in The Flats, the early dwellings of The Patch were primitive, ephemeral, and described as shanties. Construction of these structures was described in Clifton Johnson's ''Hampden County'' as \"a shanty built by putting four upright posts, to which rough boards were nailed{{nbsp}}... a roof of overlapping boards was put on top, places cut for a door and windows{{nbsp}}... Inside the shanty the earth was smoothed{{nbsp}}... and a rude floor of boards put down\".<ref name=\"hampden1936\">{{cite book|title=Hampden County, 1636-1936|editor-last=Johnson|editor-first=Clifton|page=667|chapter-url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=wu.89067299834;view=1up;seq=125|oclc=9479870|volume=II|chapter=Holyoke, the Paper City}}</ref>{{rp|681}} These buildings typically housed a single family, however some were boarding houses for large groups of workers, the largest described as being 40 feet long at its longest wall and housing 30 people. Livestock would often be seen milling freely about between such buildings in areas like The Patch.<ref name=\"hampden1936\"/>{{rp|681}} \n\nTragedy struck in 1849, when the immigrant colonies suffered a severe epidemic of [[cholera]]. Men, women and children would get sick in the evening, and perish by the morning; with no cemetery other than one across the river in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]], the epidemic spread quickly and acutely.<ref name=\"storyof\"/>{{rp|41}} It was reported to have resulted in hundreds of deaths, and the outbreak resulted in the deaths of 10% of the city's early Irish population. Part of a national phenomena, the cause of the outbreak was likely from the unsanitary conditions on ships bringing large groups seeking refuge from the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]].<ref name=\"stjeromes\"/>{{rp|24-25}} Prior to the construction of [[Pulaski Park (Holyoke, Massachusetts)|Prospect Park]] on the site and the construction of a modern sewage system, conditions at The Patch led to outbreaks that would persist for its residents there in the ensuing decades.<ref>{{cite news|title=[\"Holyoke had the cholera...\"]|work=Springfield Republican|page=8|location=Springfield, Mass.|quote=Holyoke had the cholera or something much like it\u2014a disease that has caused several deaths after short illness in some of the factory boarding houses, inhabited mostly by foreigners and very filthy, and at the 'Patch,' an Irish settlement|date=October 6, 1866}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/reasonableusepeo0000cumb|url-access=registration|title=Reasonable Use: The People, the Environment, and the State, New England...|last=Cumbler|first=John T.|page=[https://archive.org/details/reasonableusepeo0000cumb/page/47 47]|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=9780195138139}}</ref>\n\nIn 1850 following a meeting of the Hadley Falls Company, the New City was dubbed Holyoke. Emigration from Ireland to Holyoke would continue well into the 20th century and yet, with some irony it was after the changing of the name \"Ireland Parish\" from the New City to an English surname, that the area changed from more predominantly English Yankee, into a city substantially more Irish in character.<ref name=\"della\">{{cite book|title=Holyoke|last=Della Penna|first=Craig P.|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=1997|location=Charleston, SC|oclc=1035596870}}</ref>{{rp|6}} With the emergence of industry and a new wave of immigration, by 1855 more than a third of residents in Holyoke were of Irish origin.<ref name=\"toil\">{{cite book|title=Commonwealth of Toil|last1=Juravich|last2=Hartford|last3=Green|first1=Tom|first2=William F.|first3=James R.|page=[https://archive.org/details/commonwealthofto00jura/page/63 63]|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|year=1996|url=https://archive.org/details/commonwealthofto00jura|url-access=registration|isbn=1558490469}}</ref>\n\n===Tradesmen and builders===\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | width1 = 149\n   | width2 = 298\n   | align = right\n   | footer = Left to right: John Delaney (1815\u20131887), and \"Delaney's Marble Block\", or Marble Hall, as it appeared on the corner of Dwight and High Street the late 1880s\n   | image1 = John Delaney (1815-1887).jpg\n   | image2 = Delaney's Marble Block.jpg}}\n\nIrish immigration to Holyoke would continue well into the 20th century, however the majority of immigrants to the city would be Irish predominantly in the first decades of the city's existence, from the famine refugees of the 1840s through the later factory worker arrivals of the 1890s.<ref name=\"institutes\">{{cite journal|publisher=National Institutes of Health|doi=10.1017/ssh.2017.26|pmid = 29307945|title=Immigration, Occupation and Inequality in Emergent Nineteenth-Century New England Cities|date=Winter 2017|journal=Social Science History|volume=XLI|issue=4|pages=645\u2013671|pmc=5751957|last1 = Leonard|first1 = Susan Hautaniemi|last2 = Robinson|first2 = Christopher|last3 = Anderton|first3 = Douglas L.}}</ref> By 1900, larger groups of French-Canadians had begun to arrive, however with their early arrival and the separation of French language institutions, the Irish would however come to define Holyoke's identity as founders. They, along a much smaller and separate German demographic, would establish much of the city's early social, political, and labor institutions.<ref name=\"constance\"/>\n\nAlthough many of Holyoke's earliest arrivals would be farmers, these would-be laborers included a number of tradesmen such as carpenters, masons, and blacksmiths, some of the industrial city's workers who would construct its dam, canals, and factories in subsequent decades.<ref name=\"modern\"/><ref>{{cite web|website=Our Plural History, Springfield, MA|title=Irish Immigrants in Holyoke|url=http://ourpluralhistory.stcc.edu/industrial/irish.html|publisher=Springfield Technical Community College|year=2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607134120/http://ourpluralhistory.stcc.edu/industrial/irish.html|archive-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref> This was reflected in a shifting demography: in 1860, three in four skilled construction workers were Yankee Americans; by 1880 fewer than one in five reflected the same demographic, the vast majority being Irish tradesmen who would define the labor community of unions and local politics for virtually the entirety of the city's history.<ref name=\"toil\"/> One of Ireland's notable sculptor's [[Jerome Connor]], was brought to the United States as a boy as his stonemason father, Patrick Connor, was among Holyoke's early tradesmen.\n\nDespite [[anti-Irish sentiment]] in the United States during the 19th century, the Irish were split into two classes, with about 50% working in industry between 1860 and 1900, and 25\u201336% represented in [[professional services]], such as lawyers, architects, bankers, and other occupations, during the same period, exceeding the proportions of the other immigrant demographics and native-born populations in such occupations during that time.<ref name=\"institutes\">{{cite journal|publisher=National Institutes of Health|doi=10.1017/ssh.2017.26|pmid = 29307945|title=Immigration, Occupation and Inequality in Emergent Nineteenth-Century New England Cities|date=Winter 2017|journal=Social Science History|volume=XLI|issue=4|pages=645\u2013671|pmc=5751957|last1 = Leonard|first1 = Susan Hautaniemi|last2 = Robinson|first2 = Christopher|last3 = Anderton|first3 = Douglas L.}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 250\n   | align = left\n   | footer = Top to bottom: Johanna (n\u00e9e Brassil), Daniel O'Connell and Sons, c. 1908; the Holy Cross Church, now Our Lady of the Cross, erected by the Daniel O'Connell's Sons firm in 1926 when they incorporated under that name, one of many projects the firm would complete, including the [[W. E. B. DuBois Library]] at [[UMass Amherst]] and Springfield's [[Monarch Place]]\n   | image1 = Daniel J. O'Connell, Johanna Brassil, and Sons.jpg\n   | image2 = Holy Cross Church, Holyoke, Mass (71668).jpg}}\n[[File:Chief John T. Lynch, Holyoke Fire Dept, hero fireman as Lt in Precious Blood Church fire.jpg|150px|right|thumb|Fire Chief John T. Lynch, a fixture in Holyoke for decades, best remembered for his bravery as a lieutenant in rescuing parishioners in the 1875 [[Precious Blood Church fire]]]]\nAmong the earliest arrivals in Holyoke's workmen and contractors was John Delaney, a stonemason. By the time he would arrive in Holyoke in April of 1849,<ref name=\"marble\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke's Marble Building; Which John Delaney has Built at a Cost of $100,000|date=April 18, 1886|page=3|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Republican}}</ref> Delaney had previously worked on the [[Croton Watershed|Croton Water-works]] supplying the City of New York, [[Fort Warren (Massachusetts)|Fort Warren]] in Boston, and the [[Lowell Power Canal System and Pawtucket Gatehouse|Lowell Canal System]]. In his time in Holyoke he would become known for supervising the construction of the [[Holyoke Canal System]], as well as a number of its mills, and oversaw the construction of [[Holyoke City Hall]]'s foundations.<ref name=\"storyof\"/>{{rp|42}}<ref>{{cite book  |year=1879  |chapter=Holyoke |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofconnect02ever#page/n557/mode/2up |chapter-format=  |title=History of the Connecticut Valley in Massachusetts, with illustrations and biographical sketches of some of its prominent men and pioneers |volume=II |pages=915\u2013938 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Louis H. Everts; Press of J.B. Lippincott and Co |url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofconnect02ever#page/n7/mode/2up |oclc= 866692568 }}</ref> In the latter years of his career, Delaney wished to build \"a worthy monument to leave behind him\", and purchased the old Second Congregational Church that once sat across from City Hall in 1884. By January of 1885, work had begun in razing the old structure and plans had been drawn up by architect [[James A. Clough]] to build a grand building made of [[Proctor, Vermont|Sutherland Falls]] marble from Vermont, from a quarry owned by Vermont Governor [[Redfield Proctor]]'s family, with foundational ashlar facing Dwight Street taken from Delaney's quarry at [[Mount Tom (Massachusetts)|Mount Tom]].<ref name=\"marble\"/> When Proctor would visit Holyoke, Springfield, or one of its surrounding towns thereafter, he would make a point to pass that corner of Dwight and High \"to see how his marble weathered.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Holyoke|last=Dawson|first=Devon|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C8InX3IfhlUC&pg=PA26|year=2004|publisher=Arcadia|location=Charleston, SC|lccn=2003116189|isbn=9780738535265}}</ref> Unfortunately Delaney's monument to Holyoke's tradesmen would succumb to the wrecking ball after 65 years, for by 1950 its tenant the [[W. T. Grant|W. T. Grant Department Store]] sought a more modern building. Demolished in January and February of 1950, a total of 195 trucks hauled the dismantled marble South Hadley, where it was used as ground fill in a new housing development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Going|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=40|date=January 19, 1950}}</ref><ref name=\"della\"/>{{rp|54}} Today the legacy of Delaney and his men remains most visible in the stone facades of the city's canal system.\n\nA prominent figure in Holyoke's printing industry was one Michael J. Doyle.<ref name=\"water\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Water Commissioner Looks Like ex-Alderman M. J. Doyle for the Place\u2014Democratic Aldermen Will Caucus Late This Week\u2014President Kennedy Wanted Again\u2014Dr McIntee's Letter|date=December 25, 1904|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=6|quote=Indications pointed last evening to the election by the Holyoke board of aldermen a week from to-morrow of ex-Alderman Michael J. Doyle of the M. J. Doyle printing company to the water board to succeed Chairman John J. Sullivan}}</ref> Born in [[Ireland]] on September 27, 1872 to Thomas and Mary Doyle (n\u00e9e Murphy), Doyle would arrive in America with his parents in 1880. Educated in [[Holyoke Public Schools]], he would eventually take up an engraving apprenticeship in Springfield, and began a firm under the handle \"M. J. Doyle Printing Company\" in 1893, was elected to the board of aldermen in 1897 and water commission in 1904,<ref name=\"water\"/> running many jobs for the city's annual reports and publications through the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite book  |year=1902  |chapter=The City of Holyoke and the Factors in its History |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/n23/mode/2up |chapter-format= |editor1-last=Copeland |editor1-first=Alfred Minot  |title=\"Our county and its people\" : A history of Hampden County, Massachusetts |volume=III |pages=659 |publisher= The Century Memorial Publishing Company |url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/658/mode/2up |oclc= 5692695963 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Holyoke: The Skinner Family and Wistariahurst|series=Images of America|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Charleston, S.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QI4Dhk5_KBgC&pg=PA61|page=61|quote=M. J. Doyle Printing Company was a printing and negraving company that began in the late 1890s. It was located on Front Street in Holyoke and advertised having a telephone connection for those needing to contact the company|isbn=9780738539447|date=March 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=[\"M. J. Doyle Printing\"] Full-text Search Results - HathiTrust Digital Library|website=HathiTrust|access-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907200139/https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/ls?field1=ocr%3Bq1%3D%22M.%20J.%20Doyle%20Printing%22%3Ba%3Dsrchls%3Blmt%3Dft|archive-date=September 7, 2019|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/ls?field1=ocr;q1=\"M._J._Doyle_Printing\";a=srchls;lmt=ft|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDaniel O'Connell was one of the most influential of the early Irish tradesmen. Born in [[County Kerry]] in 1833, he and his family arrived in Chicopee Falls and subsequently Holyoke in 1847. His first job was as a water boy for the workers of the first, ill-fated dam.<ref name=\"storyof\"/> In 1864 he began serving as superintendent of streets, an early counterpart of the superintendent of the department of public works. Following the election of Mayor William Ruddy in 1879, O'Connell was called into the new mayor's offices and told to put four new men on his payroll, and initially to fire the six he already had under employ.<ref name=\"storyof\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=International Directory of Company Histories|volume=C|year=2009|pages=306\u2013308|publisher=St. James Press|oclc=224417874|editor-last=Grant|editor-first=Tina}}</ref> Even after Ruddy retracted this demand and told O'Connell to simply add the four as a political favor, O'Connell would not abide and resigned, starting an independent contracting business. The next morning [[William Skinner (manufacturer)|William Skinner]] knocked on O'Connell's front door and after discussing the circumstances, hired him to pave the yards of the [[William Skinner and Sons|Skinner and Sons Silk]] mills in the city.<ref name=\"1988oconnell\">{{cite news|title=Water boy job gave start to Holyoke's O'Connell firm|last1=Lauer|first1=Martin J.|last2=Hachadourian|first2=Kris|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=F-87, F-90|date=January 24, 1988}}</ref> The first O'Connell would go on to serve as one of the subcontractors for the granite [[Holyoke Dam]], and would work on a number of other projects including the construction of the New Bedford reservoir. Following his death in 1916, his sons and their descendants would continue his legacy, formally incorporating the company as Daniel O'Connell's Sons in 1926, and going on to work on a number of major projects in the Commonwealth, the broader United States, and as far away as South America.<ref name=\"storyof\"/> Among their notable works are the world's tallest academic library, [[W.E.B. DuBois Library]] at UMass Amherst, Springfield's [[Monarch Place]], [[Interstate 391]], [[Steven Holl]]'s [[Simmons Hall]] for [[MIT]], as well as the [[Frank Gehry]]-designed [[Richard B. Fisher Center for the Performing Arts]] of [[Bard College]].<ref name=\"1988oconnell\"/><ref>{{cite web|publisher=The O'Connell Companies|archive-date=April 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422174636/http://www.oconnells.com/projects/signature-projects/|url=http://www.oconnells.com/projects/signature-projects/|title=Signature Projects}}</ref>\n\n===Second wave, labor, and trade unions===\n[[File:Holyoke, Massachusetts - Paper. American Writing Paper Co. Rag sorting (Irish). - NARA - 518336.jpg|right|thumb|\"Rag girls\" cut up cotton rags used in making [[fine paper|fine writing paper]] in a Holyoke mill of the [[American Writing Paper Company]], c. 1937]]\n\nIn the decades after the [[Irish Potato Famine]] up until the [[Great Depression]], a number of single Irish women would immigrate to the United States, following the footsteps of families and male relatives who had come before. Many would take up work as domestic servants for wealthy families in larger cities, and while some of Holyoke's wealthier mill owners like the [[Wistariahurst|Skinner family]] would have servants in their homes,<ref>{{cite web|title=Skinner Servants|archive-date=July 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729051718/https://wistariahurst.org/skinner-servants/|url=https://wistariahurst.org/skinner-servants/|website=Wistariahurst|year=2013}}</ref> many of Holyoke's would find work in the city's textile factories.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|archive-date=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919025854/https://www.masslive.com/living/2013/03/the_irish_legacy_excerpt_anna_sullivan_of_holyoke.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/living/2013/03/the_irish_legacy_excerpt_anna_sullivan_of_holyoke.html|title='The Irish Legacy' excerpt: Anna Sullivan of Holyoke played dominant role in organizing Weaver's Union|date=March 8, 2013|last=Shannon|first=Catherine B.}}</ref> Holyoke would also have among the first woman police officers in the Commonwealth, Mary McMahon, who was appointed to that role in 1917 and retired after marrying in 1921. Although historian Marcella Kelly would place her as the first woman police officer in the Commonwealth, and her appointment predated Boston's first by several years, early accounts also refer to previous woman officers in Springfield and Northampton at the time of her tenure.<ref>{{cite book|title=Behind Eternity: Holyoke Women Who Made a Difference, 1873-1973|publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke|year=1973|last=Kelly|first=Marcella R.|oclc=38305604|pages=187\u2013188}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=To Have Police Woman; Mary McMahon, a Teacher, Recommended to the Mayor for Appointment|page=12|date=June 28, 1917|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Republican|quote=Police women from Springfield and Northampton were present at the meeting and explained the duties of the position}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922161829/https://archive.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/04/21/90_years_later_bostons_first_policewomen_get_fresh_recognition/|url=https://archive.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/04/21/90_years_later_bostons_first_policewomen_get_fresh_recognition/|archive-date=September 22, 2019|date=April 21, 2011|last=Cramer|first=Maria|work=The Boston Globe|title=They upended barriers\u2014and criminals; 90 years later, city's first policewomen get fresh recognition}}</ref>\n\nMany of the earliest factory worker arrivals saw new tensions between their unions and the arrival of French-Canadian workers, who while some would participate in unionism elsewhere in New England, were largely unorganized in Holyoke and brought in by mill owners to undermine the workers' leverage for better wages and working hours. In the successive generations more ethnic groups would be taken into the fold but much of the city's earliest union movements comprised Irish and German laborers.<ref name=\"toil\"/><ref name=\"masshumanities\">{{cite web|website=MassHumanities|publisher=Massachusetts Foundation for the Humanities|location=Northampton, Mass.|url=http://www.masshumanities.org/ph_fear-of-uniting-labor-movements-in-early-holyoke/|title=Fear of Uniting: Labor Movements in Early Holyoke|last=Lotspeich|first=Charlie|date=November 18, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022060923/http://masshumanities.org/ph_fear-of-uniting-labor-movements-in-early-holyoke/|archive-date=October 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hartford |first=William F. | title=Working people of Holyoke : class and ethnicity in a Massachusetts mill town, 1850\u20131960|location=New Brunswick, NJ.| publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1990| isbn= 9780813515762|oclc= 21041495}}</ref> Irish identity in the working class community became synonymous with unionism, as unions gradually took on the roles associated with ethnic organizations in public meetings and cultural events. Examples of such trade unions include a local of the [[United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners of America]] which was organized in the city soon after the formation of that trade union in 1881,<ref name=\"toil\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners of America. Springfield District Council Records, 1885-1975|archive-date=July 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701134742/http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums110|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums110|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|website=Special Collections & University Archives, UMass Amherst Libraries}}</ref> and also the Holyoke Irish role in founding the United Brotherhood of Paperworkers. Ultimately representing workers of all backgrounds, it first began as a social club within the city's Irish trade unionists known as the Eagle Lodge, receiving charter as Local{{nbsp}}1 from the [[American Federation of Labor]] in May of 1883. Even as the organization grew, it would remain tied to the community through the 20th century, among other occasions, the city would host the International Brotherhood's president in 1913, and during Holyoke's centennial in 1973, the union, then a member of the AFL-CIO, would be one of the ceremonies sponsors.<ref>{{cite news|title=President Carey Guest of Honor; Holyoke Paper Makers Entertain Prominent Union Officials|date=September 1, 1913|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Union|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Holyoke, Massachusetts Centennial Souvenir Program | year=1973 | publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke | oclc= 49709901 |url = https://archive.org/stream/holyokemassachus00holy#page/n0/mode/2up}}</ref>{{rp|87}} The union would reorganize and merge several times over the subsequent decades, eventually becoming the [[Paper, Allied-Industrial, Chemical and Energy Workers International Union]] in 1999, ultimately folding into [[United Steelworkers]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite journal|volume=XXXIII|issue=3|journal=The Massachusetts Review|location=Amherst, Mass.|last=Jacobson-Hardy|first=Michael|title=Faces, Machines, and Voices: The Fading Landscape of Papermaking in Holyoke, Massachusetts|date=Autumn 1992|pages=361\u2013384|jstor=25090356}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103134830/http://scua.library.umass.edu/umarmot/international-brotherhood-of-paper-makers-eagle-lodge/|archive-date=January 3, 2018|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/umarmot/international-brotherhood-of-paper-makers-eagle-lodge/|title=International Brotherhood of Paper Makers Local 1 (Eagle Lodge : Holyoke, Mass.) Records|publisher=University of Massachusetts|website=Special Collections and University Archives}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/files/docs/publications/bls/bls_0420_1926.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528121916/https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/files/docs/publications/bls/bls_0420_1926.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-05-28|title=Handbook of American Trade-Unions|issue=420|date=October 1926|publisher=US Department of Labor; Government Printing Office (GPO)|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=103\u2013104}}</ref>\n[[File:Anna_Sullivan_(labor_organizer).jpg|left|thumb|Anna Sullivan, who first unionized Holyoke's silk industry]]\nOne of Holyoke's leading figures in organized labor into the twentieth century was Anne B Sullivan (n\u00e9e Burns), whom Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] would describe as the \"first lady of labor\" at a testimonial dinner in 1975.<ref name=\"histjourno\">{{cite journal|journal=Historical Journal of Massachusetts|date=Summer 2008|location=Westfield, Mass.|publisher=Westfield State University|last=Dodge|first=L. Mara|title=Anna B. Sullivan, 1903\u20131983: The Formative Years of a Textile Mill Union Organizer (Holyoke, Massachusetts)|pages=184\u2013225|volume=XXXVI|issue=2}}</ref> Sullivan, born in Holyoke in 1903 to an Irish father and second generation Irish and German mother, began her career in labor joining the Weavers Union in 1932 and, inspired by the [[Textile workers strike (1934)|Textile Workers Strike of 1934]], by she had 1936 had organized workers to join the [[Textile Workers Union of America|Textile Workers Union]] at [[William Skinner and Sons]], the first mill in Western Massachusetts to unionize under the [[Congress of Industrial Organizations|CIO]].<ref>{{cite news|page=20H|date=September 23, 1983|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|title=Anna F. Sullivan; 'first lady of labor'}}</ref><ref name=\"womenmakingchange\">{{cite web|title=Anna Sullivan|website=Women Making Change; Wistariahurst|archive-date=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919015742/https://wistariahurst.org/women-making-change/anna-sullivan/|url=https://wistariahurst.org/women-making-change/anna-sullivan/|year=2017}}</ref> Up until this time, workers were offered no real guarantee of consistent pay or work, with one example being a mill which would lay off its employees for two weeks at the holidays, with no pay at Christmas.<ref name=\"womenmakingchange\"/> Besides the dangers of the loud, heavy machinery used in the mills and common respiratory illnesses from particulate in the air, foremen could fire workers for any reason, and with women workers, as Sullivan recalled, \"if [the foreman] liked the color of your hair today you were alright. If he didn't like it tomorrow, good bye.\" By the end of the 1920s, the urgency of additional work for the same wages as well as a practice of fining workers for flaws made in satins were part of the impetus which led to unionization at Skinner's mills in the next decade.<ref name=\"histjourno\"/> Despite labor being replaced by successive generations of immigrant labor, and the movement of many factories to cheaper operations in the South, part of what Sullivan attributed to the union's leverage was the skill required to be a weaver, especially in silk, which meant months of training with each hire, which didn't even guarantee mastery from each worker's efforts.<ref name=\"histjourno\"/>\n\nSullivan would go on to serve as manager of the Holyoke Joint Board of Textile Workers from 1944 to 1966, and the Berkshire Joint Board in Pittsfield from 1958 until 1966 when deindustrialization severely reduced textile work. Sullivan would also run once for Congress in 1950 on the Democratic ticket, losing to incumbent [[John W. Heselton]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Sullivan Concedes Win For Heselton|page=1|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=November 8, 1950}}</ref> part of her reason for running being to fight rising food costs attributed to shortages from the [[Korean War]]. During her campaign she gathered more than 1000 signatures in a petition to President Truman stating in part that \"we pledge ourselves to support our soldiers, in Korea by refusing to hoard foodstuffs{{nbsp}}... We earnestly petition you to request the Congress to roll back prices to their levels of June 15, 1950, and to request the Anti-Trust Division of the Department of Justice to investigate whether a conspiracy exists to profiteer in food in violation of our laws.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=1000 Holyokers Sign Petitions Asking Truman for Rollback; Mrs Sullivan's Supporters Get Names in 24-Hour Period; Price Curb Backing Is Seen|date=August 5, 1950|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=16|work=Springfield Union}}</ref> Even after entering state government in 1966 as a representative for Springfield's office of the [[Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination]], she remained active member of the Springfield-Chicopee-Westfield Labor Council and on the board of directors of the Springfield Chapter of the [[American Red Cross]]. In a memorial address delivered before Congress Rep. [[Edward P. Boland]] lionized her as a pioneer in Massachusetts labor, a good friend, and described her as a close personal friend of [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref>[[s:Anna F. Sullivan, Pioneer in the Labor Movement and Western Massachusetts' First Lady of Labor - Congressional Record: September 27, 1983|Anna F. Sullivan, Pioneer in the Labor Movement and Western Massachusetts' First Lady of Labor]]. Congressional Record. September 27, 1983. Extensions of Remarks. Page 26005. 98 Cong. Rec. (Bound) - Volume 98, First Session</ref>\n\n===Baseball===\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | width1 = 149\n   | width2 = 146\n   | align = left\n   | footer = [[Mickey Welch]] (''left''), and [[Roger Connor]] (''right''), both [[MLB]] [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] inductees who started early in their careers on the roster of the Holyoke Shamrocks\n   | image1 = Mickey_Welch_baseball_card.jpg\n   | image2 = 1888_N403_Yum_Yum_Tobacco_Roger_Connor,_Redemption_Back_SGC_60_EX_5.png}}\n\nIn the national context, Irish players were a key part of professional baseball in its formative years. Between 1871 and 1920, 23 percent of all baseball players were Irish or Irish-American, with about 58 percent born in American towns outside the largest 14 cities of the United States. In his 2014 book ''The Irish and the Making of American Sport, 1835-1920'', historian Patrick Redmond, would describe Holyoke specifically as \"crucial to baseball's Irish history\", with 19 major league players born in the city, 10 of whom were Irish Americans from during that period.<ref name=\"redmond\">{{cite book|title=The Irish and the Making of American Sport|last=Redmond|first=Patrick R|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|year=2014}}</ref>{{rp|57}} South Holyoke, known as Tigertown in the 1870s, was a frequent venue for baseball and earned its name from the tensions that ran between competing teams, particularly between Holyoke and Springfield, including at least one such game where a squad of police larger than both teams was required to break up a riot that had broken out between the two.<ref>{{cite news|work=Boston Sunday Globe|location=Boston|date=November 14, 1897|page=62|title=Holyoke; Mayor Smith Indorsed [sic] in the Caucuses\u2014 Old Names of Suburban Villages|quote=South Holyoke of today bears little resemblance to the 'Tigertown' of former days. In the days gone by the local baseball men played for blood and showed such tigerish propensities toward rival teams if the game did not go to their liking that perhaps this may have earned the cognomen of 'Tigertown.' A well-known baseball man recalls the feverish excitement which was developed whenever Springfield and Holyoye [sic] met on a ball field. It was invariably a gory battle, so much so that when Springfield came up here to play the local team, a squad of police, larger than the two ball nines, was required to bring the game to a peaceful ending}}</ref>\n\nThough not on any Holyoke professional team, there would be a number of players during this era born in the city, such as [[Tommy Tucker (baseball)|Tommy Tucker]], and [[Tommy Dowd (baseball)|Tommy Dowd]].<ref name=\"redmond\"/>{{rp|57}} However more than being the hometown of such players, for a time the city hosted a number of baseball teams itself. A wealth of largely-Irish baseball clubs were formed in the 19th century and teams named the \"Shamrocks\" abounded, however of the period between 1871 and 1920, only the Holyoke Shamrocks would attain professional status, competing in the [[National Association of Professional Base Ball Players|National Association]] and the [[International League]].<ref name=\"redmond\"/>{{rp|291}} \n\nRecords for Holyoke Shamrocks are decidedly fragmented, however during their 1879 season with the National Association, the team won the league pennant with a 23-14 record, with two future inductees of the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] on their roster, [[Mickey Welch]] and [[Roger Connor]], as well as four additional players who would later play in the [[MLB]]: [[Larry Corcoran]], [[Jerry Dorgan]], [[Patrick Gillespie (baseball)|Peter Gillespie]], and [[Fergy Malone]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|archive-date=August 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803062122/https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/62fde0bd|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/62fde0bd|title=Mickey Welch|last=Lamb|first=Bill}}</ref> Roger Connor, became known for his repeated home runs, knocking balls across the fields of Tigertown into the Connecticut River. Boss Bob Ferguson, of Springfield, Massachusetts, took notice of the young Connor in Holyoke, and signed him on to the majors in the Troy Trojans, launching a long baseball career.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Irish in Baseball: An Early History|last=Fleitz|first=David L|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|location=Jefferson, NC|year=2009|oclc=404919208}}</ref> Raised in Holyoke, [[Jack Doyle (baseball)|Jack \"Dirty Jack\" Doyle]] would go on to become the city's police commission from 1908 to 1909 before returning to baseball as an umpire, and eventual scout for the [[Chicago Cubs]]. Even in a varied career across the United States, he would call the city his home his entire life, eventually retiring there.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|archive-date=August 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803112906/https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/1b894e54|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/62fde0bd|title=Jack Doyle|last=Spatz|first=Lyle}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Irish identity would be less prominent in later baseball teams, Holyoke's pioneers were predecessors of many successive professional minor league teams through the next century, including the [[Holyoke Paperweights]], [[Holyoke Millers]], and the collegiate [[Valley Blue Sox]] today.\n\n===Representation on Beacon Hill===\n[[File:James_E_Delaney.jpg|170px|thumb|right|Col. James E. Delaney, among the first of Holyoke's Irish mayors, who also served as city clerk, auditor, and as a member of [[William E. Russell (politician)|Governor Russell]]'s military staff]]\n\nWith the exception of the earliest Yankee Protestants, Holyoke's political history encompasses an exhaustive list of Irish and Irish-American figures represented in all years of the city's civic operation, even during those times where it has not been the largest voting bloc, in offices too numerous to name in entirety. A handful of key figures in the Irish community however, especially in the 20th century, would grant it broader influence on the discourse of the Commonwealth in Boston's [[body politic]]. \nOne early example was Francis X. Quigley, a member of the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society and a journalist, who served as a member of the Massachusetts House (1908-1911) and of the state Senate (1911-1913), and was appointed by President [[Woodrow Wilson]] in 1913 to be appraiser to the [[Port of Boston]].<ref>{{cite book|page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinstatepo1917bost/page/14 14]|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinstatepo1917bost|title=Who's Who in State Politics|year=1917|publisher=Practical Politics|location=Boston}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Francis Quigley, Political Figure|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=2|date=January 23, 1954|work=Springfield Union}}</ref>\n\nOne of Holyoke's earliest members of the Irish community to see representation in a municipal, state, and federal capacity was Mayor James \nDelaney. A son of John Delaney, he was born in Lowell during his father's work on that city's canals, came to Holyoke at the age of one, and eventually graduated from [[Eastman Business College]]. Delaney would go on to work for the Holyoke Water Power Company and serve on the city's board of assessors for a year.<ref name=\"bostobit\">{{cite news|title=Ex-Mayor Delaney is Found Dead; Was Three Times Head of Holyoke and Served on Governor's Staff|year=July 14, 1910|location=Boston|work=Boston Journal}}</ref> In 1875 he was elected to the common council, from 1877 to 1882 served as city clerk, and was elected mayor twice in 1883 and 1884, serving two terms before being elected again in 1888 for a third. During that same year Delaney served as delegate-at-large to the convention nominating Grover Cleveland, and elected an alternate for the next Democratic convention. [[William E. Russell (politician)|Governor Russell]] would grant him the honorary title of colonel of the governor's military staff, under [[Adjutant General of Massachusetts]] Samuel Dalton.<ref name=\"bostobit\"/> Posthumously the ''[[Springfield Republican]]'' would describe him as having bipartisan support, and holding a legacy of growth in the city upon leaving office.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke Newsboy Licenses; School Board to Handle Them; Will Thus Place Question Where It Can be Well Regulated\u2013Death of Col. Delaney|date=July 17, 1910|location=Springfield, Mass.|work=Springfield Republican}}</ref> During his time on the governor's military staff, Delaney attended the inauguration of Pres. Cleveland as well as serve in the state delegation to the [[World's Columbian Exposition]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Personal and Social Gossip|work=Boston Herald|date=March 12, 1893|page=27|location=Boston|quote=The party consisting of Col. James E. Delaney of the Governor's staff, and Mrs. Delaney of Holyoke, Mr. and Mrs. Eugene Lynch of this city, have returned home, after a delightful trip to Baltimore and Washington, where they attended the inauguration}}\n* {{cite news|title=Delegation to World's Fair; Itinerary of the Trip Given Out by Adjt.-Gen. Dalton|page=8|date=June 9, 1893|work=Boston Herald|location=Boston|quote=Governor's staff\u2014Col. Michael T. Donahoe, Col. Spender Borden. Col. D. Howard Vincent, Col. James E. Delaney}}</ref> Attending events such as the inauguration of Russell's successor [[Frederic T. Greenhalge]] and events such as charity balls in Boston, spread the influence of the then-still 20 year old city during its greatest period of industrial growth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=6|date=January 3, 1894|quote=Col James E. Delaney will attend the inaugural exercises of Gov Greenhalge. He will dine with Gov Russell, and in the evening, with his wife and daughter, will attend a charity ball}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John_Collins_and_Maurice_Donahue_1960s_Massachsuetts_USA_11191699173.jpg|left|220px|thumb|Maurice Donahue (center), stands behind Boston's [[John F. Collins|Mayor Collins]] (front), c. 1960\u20131968]] \n\nIn the latter half of the 20th century, [[Maurice A. Donahue]] was a Holyoke figure who loomed large in Massachusetts politics. First elected as part of the Commonwealth's first Democratic Party majority in the Massachusetts House of Representatives in 1948, Donahue would go on join the State Senate in 1950, and by 1958 had become the Senate Majority Leader. In this position he lobbied for a number of interests in Western Massachusetts, including for the restoration of the old [[Mount Holyoke]] Prospect Summit House at [[J. A. Skinner State Park]] and its incline railroad. Though the latter is lost to history, the former would be restored in Donahue's lifetime.<ref>{{cite book|title=Cultivating a Past: Essays on the History of Hadley, Massachusetts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R16hSpCuzLQC&pg=PA344|page=344|editor=Marla R. Miller|year=2009|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst, Mass.|isbn = 978-1558497009}}</ref> By 1964 Donahue had risen to the rank of [[President of the Massachusetts Senate]], a position he held until 1971, longer than any Democratic politician in that post before him.<ref>{{cite web|website=Special Collections and University Archives, UMass Libraries|publisher=University of Massachusetts|title=Maurice A. Donahue Papers, 1960-1971|year=2015|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums311|archive-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926042520/http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums311}}</ref> Though a prominent figure in state politics, in a 1976 interview for the [[John F. Kennedy Library]], Donahue would describe John Kennedy's electoral campaigns as lacking the same connections in Holyoke\u2013Chicopee\u2013Springfield as he and his staff had, noting a common respect between the region and Boston but less \"down-the-line Democrat\" territories than rural towns where Kennedy was able to build a substantial ground staff. Donahue's political career would end in 1971 after failing to garner the post of Democrat nominee for governor in the previous year. Choosing not to seek re-election to the senate, he would be appointed as a professor of political science at the University of Massachusetts and became the first director of the Institute for Governmental Services, a publicly funded consultancy and think-tank which would later bear his name, the UMass Donahue Institute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sen. Donahue Named to 2 Posts at UMass|work=Boston Record American|date=December 23, 1970|page=4|location=Boston, Mass.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our Background|website=UMass Donahue Institute|publisher=University of Massachusetts|archive-date=September 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902182757/http://www.donahue.umassp.edu/about-us/background|url=http://www.donahue.umassp.edu/about-us/background}}</ref>\n\n[[File:David M Bartley.jpg|thumb|160px|right|[[David M. Bartley]], c. 1963, as a member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives]]\n\nAnother influential resident of Holyoke in Beacon Hill politics was [[David M. Bartley]], son of a Holyoke police chief James Bartley, who followed a similar career to Donahue's in the [[Massachusetts General Court|General Court]], though in the Massachusetts House rather than the Senate. In describing the difference between the two in a 1969 interview with the ''[[Boston Herald]]'', Bartley noted their views had \"a shade of difference{{nbsp}}... After all Donahue grew up through the depression which I did not. And this has given him a certain different Democratic emphasis\".<ref name=\"1969bartleyherald\">{{cite news|title=Bartley in Line As New Speaker|date=January 2, 1969|page=3|work=Boston Herald}}</ref> Taking the post as Speaker that same year, Bartley was the youngest to assume the second-most powerful political position in Massachusetts in 200 years. As Speaker, Bartley lobbied for what became known as the [[Bartley-Fox Law]], a nationally-studied law which, in 1974, imposed a 1-year [[mandatory minimum sentence]] on anyone possessing an illegal firearm; the law has since received mixed appraisal in its efficacy in curbing violent crime.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Deutsch |first=Stuart Jay |last2=Alt |first2=Francis B. |date=1977-11-01 |title=The Effect of Massachusetts' Gun Control Law On Gun-Related Crimes in the City of Boston |journal=Evaluation Quarterly |language=en |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=543\u2013568 |doi=10.1177/0193841x7700100402 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8-dDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA356 |title=The Oxford Handbook of Law and Economics: Volume 3: Public Law and Legal Institutions |last=Parisi |first=Francesco |date=2017-04-04 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191507205 |pages=356\u20137 |language=en}}</ref> In contrast, Bartley received overwhelming praise for his work in sponsoring, with education committee chairman Michael Daly, what was known as the \"[[Bartley-Daly Law]]\". A culmination of efforts by the Coalition for Special Education, now known as the Federation for Children with Special Needs, the 1971 law removed the legal terms \"mentally retarded\" or \"emotionally disturbed\" and placed them under the broader label, \"school age children with special needs.\" The law would also remove IQ test qualifications, and created a legal mechanism by which parents could appeal student placement, as well as incentivized public schools to accommodate such special needs students by mandating public coverage of their tuitions if they were enrolled in private schools.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Rittenhouse|url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED182956|publisher=Illinois State University|first=Robert K|date=January 14, 1980|series=ED182956|title=The Bartley-Daly Act: Regulations for the Implementation of Chapter 766 of the Acts of 1972: The Comprehensive Special Education Law of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts: An Analysis Within the Context of Public Law 94-142|via=US [[Education Resources Information Center|ERIC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|work=The Harvard Crimson|location=Cambridge, Mass.|archive-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907232946/https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1973/3/12/the-bartley-bill-a-new-philosophy/|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1973/3/12/the-bartley-bill-a-new-philosophy/|title=The Bartley Bill: A New Philosophy in Special Education|last=Bennett|first=Amanda|date=March 12, 1973|publisher=Harvard University}}</ref> The bill, and programs created by Massachusetts school districts in response, would be the subject of extensive study, influencing [[special education]] programs across the United States as the first law providing state funds in the pursuit of \"maximum feasible potential\" of disabled persons in public education.<ref>{{cite web|website=Newsletter (FCSN)|publisher=Federation for Children with Special Needs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717135513/https://fcsn.org/newsletter/2015/springv35n2/from-ed|archive-date=July 17, 2015|url=https://fcsn.org/newsletter/2015/springv35n2/from-ed|title=From the Executive Director: From Humble Beginnings to National Involvement|date=Fall 2015}}</ref> In the wake of a crisis, wherein an estimated 40,000 to 60,000 students were not receiving education in a language they understood, Bartley and Daly also passed the nation's first bilingual state education law, mandating transitional bilingual programs in districts with 20 or more students of inadequate English proficiency, and temporarily waiving certain teacher certification requirements to encourage more with necessary Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese skills to enter the workforce.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands of Non-English-Speaking Children Not in School; Tierney Admits Language Crisis|last=Forman|first=Ian|work=Boston Herald|pages=1, 10}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|title=National Conference, Early Childhood Education and the Chicanito, Pima Community College, Tucson, Arizona, August 3, 4, 5, 1972|page=19|publisher=Pima Community College|editor=Rafael Ch\u00e1vez|year=1972|quote=...{{nbsp}}and [in] 1969 only four Puerto Rican students graduated from Boston high schools. Three years later, through the efforts of Sister Francis Georgia, community leader Alex Rodriguez, the Boston task force, and two key legislators, Education Committee Chairman Michael Daly and House Speaker David Barley [sic], Massachusetts passed the nation's first comprehensive state bilingual education law|oclc=1162872}}</ref> Bartley would leave the legislature in 1975 when he was appointed president of his alma mater [[Holyoke Community College]], a post he retained until 2004.<ref name=\"legendary\">{{cite book|last=Sears|first=Jacqueline M.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mTcrBwAAQBAJ|title=Legendary Locals of Holyoke|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Charleston, S.C.|year=2015|isbn=9781467101813}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n{{further|Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade}}\n[[File:Runners leave the starting line at the 44th annual Holyoke St Patrick's Road Race (2019).jpeg|thumb|right|Runners cross the starting line during the 44th annual St. Patrick's Road Race, 2019]]\n\nMany of Holyoke's Irish cultural events center around the Holyoke St Patrick's Day Parade; leading up to it there are several events, including the Grand Colleen Pageant, typically held the first Saturday in January, of which five young women are selected who go on to the Grand Colleen Ball, at which one is crowned as the parade's Grand Colleen based on presentation and questions related to their Irish heritage.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Queen of the Green|last=Blais|first=Madelaine|pages=58\u201363|magazine=The New York Times Magazine|date=March 26, 1995}}</ref>\n\nOther events include the Grand Marshal Reception, held the second Friday of January,<ref>{{cite web|archive-date=September 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921212309/https://www.masslive.com/news/2019/09/john-j-driscoll-named-grand-marshal-of-2020-holyoke-st-patricks-parade.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2019/09/john-j-driscoll-named-grand-marshal-of-2020-holyoke-st-patricks-parade.html|title=John J. Driscoll named Grand Marshal of 2020 Holyoke St. Patrick's Parade|last=Hohenberger|first=Dennis|date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> a reception at [[The Student Prince (restaurant)|The Student Prince]] in Springfield with participants of the parade such as the Mummers bands and [[Holyoke Caledonian Pipe Band]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Student Prince Cafe, Fort Restaurant begin four-day St. Patrick's Day celebration|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/student-prince-cafe-fort-restaurant-begin-four-day-st-patricks-day-celebration|last=Carretaro|first=Kristina|date=March 14, 2019|work=22 News WWLP-TV}}</ref> and two [[road run]]s. Since 2014, every September the Parade Committee has held the Halfway [[5K run|5K Run]], marking the six months before the next parade, and the better-known [[10k run|10k]], the Holyoke St. Patrick's Day Road Race. Hosted annually the day before the parade since 1975, it has been called by Olympian [[John Treacy]] \"a miniature Boston\", had a record 6,800 contestants complete the course in 2014, and was placed among the best St. Patrick's runs in the nation by ''[[Runner's World]]'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921212644/https://www.masslive.com/sports/2014/09/1st_holyoke_halfway_to_st_patricks_day_road_race_facts_figures.html|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url=https://www.masslive.com/sports/2014/09/1st_holyoke_halfway_to_st_patricks_day_road_race_facts_figures.html|title=1st Holyoke Halfway to St. Patrick's Day Road Race, Facts, Figures|last=Roberts|first=Seth|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=September 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817172445/https://www.masslive.com/sports/2016/03/2016_st_patrick_road_race_fast.html|archive-date=August 17, 2016|url=https://www.masslive.com/sports/2016/03/2016_st_patrick_road_race_fast.html|title=Fast facts about the 2016 Holyoke St. Patrick's Road Race|last=Roberts|first=Seth|date=March 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Runner's World|title=Stellar St. Patrick's Day Runs\n|archive-date=March 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325094317/https://www.runnersworld.com/races-places/g20839691/stellar-st-patricks-day-runs/|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/races-places/g20839691/stellar-st-patricks-day-runs/|last1=Lange|last2=Nall|first1=Ali Taylor|first2=McGee|date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Institutions==\n[[File:StPatricksCommitteeHolyokeMass.svg|left|thumb|Emblem of the Holyoke St. Patrick's Day Parade Committee, which has held its namesake event annually since 1952]]\n\nIn addition to the role played by labor unions, soon after the arrival of Holyoke's Irish workers many of the city's earliest immigrants would organize cultural institutions. By 1865 it was reported that a Circle of the [[Fenian Brotherhood]] had been established.<ref name=\"fenian\">{{cite news|work=Irish American|location=New York|date=October 21, 1865|page=4|title=[Holyoke Circle of the Fenian Brotherhood]}}</ref> Among the early institutions of the Irish were local courts of the [[Catholic Order of Foresters#Massachusetts Foresters|Massachusetts Catholic Order of Foresters]]. According to the Irish Ancestral Research Association, the first of four was organized in 1887,<ref name=\"tiara\">{{cite web|archive-date=September 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908140626/https://tiara.ie/projects/foresters-courts/|url=https://tiara.ie/projects/foresters-courts/|website=The Irish Ancestral Research Association|location=Sudbury, Massachusetts|title=Massachusetts Catholic Order of Foresters Courts Instituted From 1879 To 1935}}</ref> however newspapers from the time reference such groups in Holyoke as early as 1880, a year after the Massachusetts Order was first organized in Boston.<ref name=\"tiara\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=To-Day|quote=At Southwick ponds, picnic Holyoke Foresters|page=5|date=September 8, 1880|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> A [[fraternal benefit society]], the Order was predominantly Irish, but also one of the few groups which, in its Catholic origins, had members of both Irish and French-Canadian backgrounds,<ref name=\"souv\">{{cite book | last1=Alcorn | first1=W. M. |last2=Shirley |first2=P. E.| title=Holyoke, Past and Present Progress and Prosperity; Historical and Industrial Notes | year=1910 | publisher=W.M. Alcorn Souvenir Association | oclc= 50033673 |page=41|url = https://archive.org/stream/holyokepastprese00wmal#page/40/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book  |year=1902  |chapter=The City of Holyoke and the Factors in its History |script-chapter= |trans-chapter= |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/n23/mode/2up |chapter-format= |editor1-last=Copeland |editor1-first=Alfred Minot  |title=\"Our county and its people\" : A history of Hampden County, Massachusetts |volume=III |pages=659 |publisher= The Century Memorial Publishing Company |url=https://archive.org/stream/ourcountyitspeop03cope#page/658/mode/2up |oclc= 5692695963 }}</ref> though not without being at odds over the matter of conduct in the English language.<ref>{{cite news|date=July 9, 1905|page=26|location=Boston|work=Boston Sunday Globe|title=FOR FRENCH ALONE; Holyoke Foresters Want New High Court. Dissatisfaction Because English Is Official Language}}</ref>\n\n===Philo-Celtic Society===\nOne of the few city institutions to define itself by the use of the Irish language, the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society was an Irish cultural group organized by Patrick J. Judge in 1895,<ref>{{cite book|title=Holyoke City Directory, 1900|publisher=Price, Lee & Co.|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=514}}</ref> who sought to make it \"the banner society\" among those in America studying the language and literature, offering free courses to all Irish men and women.<ref name=\"1898IA\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|page=4|work=Irish American|date=March 14, 1898|location=New York}}</ref><ref name=\"1896Philo\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|page=4|work=Irish American|date=January 27, 1896|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|author=Editorship|work=Irish American|date=April 30, 1898|location=New York|page=4|via=NewsBank}}</ref> The society would regularly feature dancing and social functions including regular violin playing of jigs and reels, at most it met on Sundays, Mondays and Fridays in its Emmet Hall, a floor above a \"High Street Bank\", and described itself as being among the only of such societies to have its own hall and regularly meeting three times a week.<ref name=\"1898IA\"/>The platform for its speakers was described as decorated in alternating small American and Irish flags, with a portrait of [[Irish republican]] martyr [[Robert Emmet]] at its center.<ref name=\"sheehymtg\">{{cite news|title=Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society|date=April 11, 1898|page=1|location=New York|work=Irish American|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\nThough serving its Irish community, the society also sought to promote interest in Irish culture and language to the general public and was known to have published at least one small book described as \"Irish in design as well as partly so in language\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Our Gaelic World|work=Irish World|date=November 5, 1898|page=11|location=New York|quote=At a recent ball given by the Ancient Order of Hibernians of Springfield, Mass., the order of dances was printed in Irish and English. The Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society a short time before showed the example in this regard, having got out a neat little book, Irish in design as well as partly so in language. Every little idea of this kind marks a step forward, and no opportunity of this kind, no matter how small, should be lost to excite the curiousity and the interest of the general public}}</ref> Indeed by 1898 the ''Irish American'' in New York printed remarks made during a meeting of a Providence counterpart which compared New York and Holyoke's societies as comparably outstanding in the advancement of the study of the Irish language among their peers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Providence Irish Language Society|work=Irish American|date=February 7, 1898|location=New York|page=8|quote=The ex-treasurer [of the Providence Society], Mr. M. J. Henehan, was a welcome visitor, and gave an interesting account of the splendid work achieved by other societies he had visited, and urged those present to look out for their laurels, as there was danger that the Philo-Celtic Society of New York and the Holyoke Philo-Celtic Society would lead them as to attendance and advancement in studies,\u2014these two bodies showing marked enthusiasm in the good work}}</ref> Though considerably smaller, the population drew regular coverage from the [[Irish in New York City|Irish of New York City]], with the New York ''Irish American'' lauding that \"Holyoke seems to be destined to have the banner Irish Language Society, notwithstanding it has only a population of about 40,000\".<ref name=\"sheehymtg\"/> A similar praise came from New York's ''Irish World'',{{efn|Not to be confused with the 1987 established ''[[The Irish World (London)|The Irish World]]''}} which lauded Holyoke's Philo-Celtics as \"probably ahead of any other societies in the United States in having [their] own rooms and in meeting three times a week. They have quite a few good Irish scholars there, and a number of active workers\".<ref>{{cite news|work=Irish World|location=New York|via=NewsBank|page=7|date=July 9, 1898|title=The Holyoke Philo Celtic Society is probably...}}</ref>\n\nIn 1898, the Holyoke society became a founding organization of the Gaelic League of America, an American counterpart of [[Conradh na Gaeilge]], with 12 other societies including groups from Boston, New York, and Chicago.<ref name=\"IrishIdentity\"/><ref name=\"join\"/><ref name=\"GLD\">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Gael (An Gaodhal)|title=Gaelic League Directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oc0GAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA29|page=33|volume=XX|issue=1|date=January 1901|location=New York}}</ref> The two stated objectives of the League were \"the preservation of Irish as the National Language of Ireland, and the extension of its use as a spoken tongue\" and \"the study and publication of existing Gaelic Literatue, and the cultivation of a modern literature in Irish\".<ref name=\"GLD\"/> Though the Gaelic League and its member societies described themselves as \"non-political and unsectarian\", they were not solely a literary or language movement, but one supporting the Irish Cause abroad in financial assistance, though such societies were rarely patronized by the wealthy.<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://dspace.mic.ul.ie/handle/10395/1529|chapter=American influence on the Gaelic League: Inspiration or control?|title=The Irish Revival Reappraised|location=Dublin|publisher=Four Courts Press|pages=63\u201370|year=2001|last=Bhroim\u00e9il|first=\u00dana N\u00ed}}</ref> By 1908 the Society had also affiliated itself among the ranks of the [[Irish Texts Society]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Publications|volume=10|chapter=List of Members|publisher=Irish Texts Society|page=xix|year=1908|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAQAAIAAJ&pg=PR19}}</ref>\n\n===Hibernians===\nThe Ancient Order of Hibernians Division No.{{nbsp}}1 of Holyoke, now known as the Ancient Order of Hibernians of Hampden/Hampshire Counties, James A. Curran Div.{{nbsp}}1 and Ladies Auxiliary Div.{{nbsp}}2, was first established in February of 1872.<ref>{{cite book|title=Price & Lee's Holyoke City Directory, including South Hadley|year=1884|publisher=Price & Lee Company|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=308}}</ref><ref name=\"curran\">{{cite news|archive-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915193142/https://www.masslive.com/news/2010/11/ancient_order_of_hibernians_na.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2010/11/ancient_order_of_hibernians_na.html|title=Ancient Order of Hibernians naming Holyoke chapter after James Curran|date=November 3, 2010|last=Cahill|first=Patricia|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> Much of Holyoke's international outreach to Ireland would be made through the AOH throughout the decades,<ref>{{cite work|title=Holyoke|quote=A mass-meeting was held at the Hibernian hall last evening to make arrangements for the welcoming meeting to be given Members of Parliament Kettle and Hazelton November 9. The committee of arrangements will be chosen this week, and invitations extended to the Irish people of Holyoke as well as sympathizers with the Irish movement started by T. P. O'Connor and being furthered by Messrs Kettle and Hazelton on their tour, to meet at the Hibernian hall that evening, when arrangements will be made for an overflow meeting|date=October 29, 1906|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"consul1951\">{{cite news|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=32|title=Irish People Said Thankful to Holyokers; Shields, Consul From Ireland, Addresses Alumnae of Elms College|date=April 19, 1951}}</ref><ref name=\"nellie\">{{cite news|title=For Dubin Martyrs; Miss Nellie Gifford Addresses Temperance Hall Meeting|date=December 4, 1916|page=7|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> and the division would host Massachusetts' Hibernian convention in 1904.<ref>{{cite news|title=A. O. H. State Conventions - Massachusetts Hibernians|work=Irish World|location=New York|date=September 3, 1904|page=3}}</ref>\n\nFacing financial difficulties and dwindling membership, Holyoke's AOH credits its continued existence to Holyoke contractor James Curran, who began hosting its meetings with the establishment of his \"Wherehouse\" banquet hall in 1977; the division would be named in his honor in 2010.<ref name=\"curran\"/>\nIn addition to its involvement in organizing the Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade Committee, the AOH continues to organize banquets, fundraisers, and Irish cultural events primarily at The Wherehouse Banquet Hall in the downtown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/cultural-celebration-at-hibernian-irish-night-in-holyoke/|title=Cultural celebration at Hibernian Irish Night in Holyoke|date=February 23, 2019|publisher=22 News, WWLP-TV|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> Of the 16 divisions extant in Massachusetts today, it is the only one remaining west of Worcester, outside the Greater Boston area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Divisions|website=MASSAOH.COM|publisher=Massachusetts State Board Ancient Order of Hibernians in America, Inc.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903043509/http://www.massaoh.com/?page_id=17|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url=http://www.massaoh.com/?page_id=17}}</ref>\n\n===Brian Boru Club===\nOn July 20, 1949, the Brian Boru Club of Holyoke was incorporated as a social club, within the year branching out to sponsor its own basketball team in a local league. One day a couple of business men tossed out the idea of holding a St. Patrick's Parade at a Club meeting, and in the following year the group would work with the Hibernians, fire, and police departments, to organize the first annual Holyoke St. Patrick Day Parade in 1952.<ref name=\"bigday\">{{cite news|title=Big Day in Holyoke|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|page=1|date=March 22, 1970}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=October 22, 1949|page=30|title=Brian Boru Will Have Cage Team|quote=Organized within the past year, the Brian Boru Club of this city, which has confined itself to social activities, will make its entrance into sports circles by sponsoring a basketball team this coming season}}</ref>\n\nBy 1960, the Club had acquired the former Union Club Hall, designed by [[George P. B. Alderman]] in 1909, and while keeping the Brian Boru name have retained its original liquor license, appearing as \"The Union Club of Holyoke Inc. DBA Brian Boru Club\" in temporary license applications for the St. Patrick's Day Parade as recently as 2016.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217161319/https://www.holyoke.org/events/license-board-meeting-8/|archive-date=February 17, 2017|url=https://www.holyoke.org/events/license-board-meeting-8/|publisher=City of Holyoke|title=License Board Commission Meeting|date=December 21, 2016|quote=The Union Club of Holyoke Inc. DBA Brian Boru Club, 37 Commercial St}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Brian Boru Club Will Keep Name|work=Springfield Union|date=August 18, 1960|page=42|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n\n===Newspapers and publishers===\n[[File:In Gaeldom column on Holyoke and Harlem, Irish American (January 18, 1913, p 5).png|right|thumb|An example of [[Irish language]] coverage set in [[Gaelic type|Gaelic script]], of a [[feis]] in Holyoke; as it appeared in New York City's ''Irish American'' newspaper, 1913]]\n\nMuch of the Irish community's affairs were documented in the ''[[Holyoke Transcript-Telegram]]'', with its publishers including Mary \"Minnie\" Dwight (n\u00e9e Ryan), a daughter of Irish immigrants, who was the first female editor of the paper following the death of her husband William G. Dwight, from 1930 until her death in 1957.<ref name=\"senior\">\"William Dwight, 92, Holyoke Publisher\". Obituary. ''Union-News'', Springfield, Mass. June 5, 1996.</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Stories Carved in Stone: Holyoke, Massachusetts|last=Clark|first=Rusty|year=2006|publisher=Dog Pond Press|location=West Springfield, Mass.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J_elq5tHqQIC&pg=PA172|page=172|isbn=9780975536261}}</ref> Ms. Dwight would also be the first woman to receive an honorary degree from the [[University of Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|website=UMass Physical Plant|publisher=University of Massachusetts Amherst|archive-date=May 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505074919/https://www.umass.edu/physicalplant/dwight-minnie-e-ryan|url=https://www.umass.edu/physicalplant/dwight-minnie-e-ryan|title=Dwight, Minnie E. Ryan - Residential Hall}}</ref> In contrast with other communities, no major circulars were published specifically covering Irish community and much of their stories were those of the daily press, covered in the ''Transcript'' until its closure in 1994, as well as the ''Springfield Union'' and ''[[Springfield Republican]]'' of the late 19th century to the present day. However, in New York City's [[Irish American journalism|Irish press]] the community would see extensive coverage in both [[English language|English]] and [[Irish language|Irish]] from the 1860s through the 1920s, including such papers as the ''Irish American'', ''Irish Nation'', and ''Irish World''.<ref>{{cite web|url-access=subscription|url=https://www.genealogybank.com/explore/newspapers/all/usa/new-york/new-york?fname=&lname=&fullname=&kwinc=Holyoke&kwexc=&rgfromDate=&rgtoDate=&formDate=&formDateFlex=exact&dateType=range&pub%5B0%5D=irish-american&pub%5B1%5D=irish-nation&pub%5B2%5D=irish-world|website=GenealogyBank|publisher=Newsbank|title=New York City Newspaper Archives|access-date=11 August 2019|postscript=. [Filtered for ''Irish American'', ''Irish Nation'', and ''Irish World'']}}</ref> Even today the city's St. Patrick's Day Parade and announcements related to the Hibernians and other groups are covered by Manhattan's ''[[The Irish Echo]]'', as well as ''[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=[Search for 'Holyoke']|archive-date=September 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908023208/https://www.irishecho.com/?s=Holyoke|url=https://www.irishecho.com/?s=Holyoke|access-date=September 7, 2019|publisher=The Irish Echo}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Holyoke's Irish Heart|magazine=Irish America|publisher=Irish America, LLC|archive-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910085504/https://irishamerica.com/2009/06/holyokes-irish-heart/|url=https://irishamerica.com/2009/06/holyokes-irish-heart/|last=Harty|first=Patricia}}</ref>\n\n==International relations==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | The Holyoke Catholic Benevolent Society has proved by its action that its works of benevolence are not confined to its members; but that it looks above and beyond its local duties, and sees that there is another work of the purest benevolence to be done, and charitably and patriotically it comes forward to assist in its accomplishment.\n\nWe hope the example given by this society will be followed by the other Irish societies in the United States and Canada, that are independent of the Brotherhood, and it will show to the world that though Irishmen are not all members of the Fenian Brotherhood, yet their hearts are united in the one grand object, the liberation of Ireland\u2014from Hudson's Bay to Long Island Sound, from the Pacific to the Atlantic, and from the Ganges to the Shannon.<br>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\"|&mdash;I remain respectfully yours,<br>Patrick McGee<br>Secretary\n|-\n| style=\"border-top: 1px solid black;\"|Vote of thanks given by Holyoke Circle of the Fenian Brotherhood for $100 given to them by the Benevolent Society, declared Sept. 30, 1865, and printed in the New York ''Irish American'' and the ''Boston Pilot''<ref name=\"fenian\"/>\n|-\n|}\nIn a speech at the Roger Smith Hotel in 1951 to alumni of [[Elms College]], the Irish consul at Boston, Joseph F. Shields would describe Holyoke as \"very well known among the people of Ireland,\" especially for its support of The Cause.<ref name=\"consul1951\"/> In its history, Holyoke's Irish would maintain relations between the Emerald Isle, and their newfound home in the Commonwealth, and receive numerous figures and officials during [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British rule]] and independence thereafter, often raising funds for the cause of Irish republicanism.\n\nBetween [[Fenian raids|the raids of 1866 and 1871]], [[John O'Neill (Fenian)|General John O'Neill]] of the [[Fenian Brotherhood]] would make a stop in Holyoke on March 13, 1868, as an honored guest of the Brotherhood's unit in that city. With the meeting chaired by builder John Delaney, O'Neill would rally Holyoke's Irish men and women, saying they must be \"ready and willing to aid their suffering native land by money and men in its struggle for Irish liberty.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Gen. O'Neill in Holyoke|date=April 4, 1868|work=Irish American|page=4|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nIn 1887 the ''[[New York Herald]]'' reported that Mayor [[James J. O'Connor]] presided over a meeting organized by a local body of the Irish national league hosting [[Irish Home Rule movement|Home Rule]] members of parliament, [[Sir Thomas Esmonde, 11th Baronet|Sir Thomas Esmonde]] and [[Arthur O'Connor (MP)|Arthur O'Connor]] during their tour of the Commonwealth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Urging Ireland's Cause; the Irish Ambassadors Address a Meeting at Holyoke|date=October 9, 1887|work=New York Herald|location=New York|page=13}}\n:* {{cite news|title=Speeches at Fall River|date=October 8, 1887|page=2|location=Savannah, Ga.|work=Morning News}}</ref> Received by a large party of local politicians including [[William Whiting II|Congressman William Whiting]] and former Mayor [[William B. C. Pearsons]], the two offered speeches decrying British rule to rousing applause from what was described as one of the largest audiences ever in the [[Holyoke City Hall]] up until that time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anti-Coercian at Holyoke; Last Night's Demonstration; With Speeches by Thomas Grattan Esmonde and Arthur O'Connor|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=October 9, 1887|page=7|work=Springfield Republican}}</ref>\n\nIn 1898 the Philo-Celtic Society would host [[Eugene Sheehy (priest)|Rev. Father Eugene Sheehy]] of County Limerick for one of their meetings. Sheehy would offer a speech titled the \"Language and Music of Our Race\" to a packed Emmet Hall, including a delegation from the Springfield Irish Language Society. A series of traditional tunes such as ''Barney, Come Home'' and ''The Meeting of the Waters'' were played and the meeting concluded with Sheehy reciting the [[Lord's Prayer]] in [[Irish language|Irish]].<ref name=\"sheehymtg\"/>\n\nOn May 17, 1903, the United Irish League's Holyoke chapter would host Mr. [[Joseph Devlin]], Irish journalist and future MP, who, with [[Arthur Chapin|Mayor Chapin]] presiding, spent the evening discussing the ramifications of Ireland's [[Irish Land Acts#Wyndham Land (Purchase) Act 1903|Wyndham Land Act]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Mass-Meeting at Holyoke; the City Hall was Crowded to Hear Messrs Devlin and Mitchell\u2014Mayor Chapin Presided|date=May 18, 1903|page=12|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> Three years later on November 9, 1906, [[Nathan P. Avery|Mayor Avery]] would receive MPs [[Richard Hazleton]], and [[Tom Kettle]] during their tour of the United States for the Cause. Describing the realities of British rule and progress made toward independence, the two would draw comparison between the independence of the United States and Ireland from the Crown and during the evening some $700, about $20,000 in 2017 US Dollars, was raised.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irish Envoys at Holyoke; an Enthusiastic Reception|date=November 10, 1906|page=7|work=Springfield Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 1911, [[Michael O'Flanagan]] [[Shane Leslie]] gave speeches at Holyoke's Empire Theater at the behest of the local Ladies' Division of the Hibernians as envoys of the [[Gaelic League]].<ref>{{cite news|title=In Gaeldom; Father O'Flanagan and Shane Leslie Plead for Irish Ireland at Holyoke, Mass.|page=1|work=Irish American|location=New York|date=November 27, 1911}}</ref> Following the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916, in December of that year [[Nellie Gifford]] was hosted in the city, remarking her pleasant surprise to see the [[Statue of Liberty]] represented as a woman, and giving her account of the events of the preceding months, including the [[Proclamation of the Irish Republic]] and the possibility of moving further toward Irish independence.<ref name=\"nellie\"/>\n\nEven after [[Proclamation of the Irish Republic|Irish independence]], the city would receive members of the Irish Republic. In 1966, [[Se\u00e1n Flanagan]], minister of health in the Irish government, would be an honored guest among those marching in the St. Patrick's Day Parade,<ref>{{cite news|title=Colorful Floats, Marching Units Take Over Holyoke|date=March 21, 1966|page=11|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref> and in recent years the city would twice host [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] leader [[Gerry Adams]]. Adams would march in the parade in 2006 and 2015, giving a press conference at City Hall at his first appearance, as a guest of honor by Congressman [[Richard Neal]], a Holyoke Community College alumnus,<ref>Neal, Richard E. \"[http://www.house.gov/neal/link4.html Biography].\" ''Congressman Richard Neal'' (official website). [[United States House of Representatives]].</ref> who worked with both the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] and [[Ulster loyalism|Ulster loyalists]] and members of Congress to ensure an American role in Irish peace after the [[Good Friday Agreement]].<ref>{{cite news|archive-date=September 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914223302/http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/03/19/sinn_feins_adams_detained_at_airport/|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/03/19/sinn_feins_adams_detained_at_airport/|title=Sinn Fein's Adams detained at airport|publisher=Associated Press|date=March 19, 2006|via=Boston.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|archive-date=August 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820064407/https://www.masslive.com/entertainment/2015/03/faces_of_the_holyoke_st_patric.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/entertainment/2015/03/faces_of_the_holyoke_st_patric.html|work=The Republican|title=Faces of the Holyoke St. Patrick's Day Parade|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=March 2015|last=Kelly|first=Ray}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|archive-date=September 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914222947/https://www.masslive.com/news/2014/04/gerry_adams_sinn_fein_leader_s.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2014/04/gerry_adams_sinn_fein_leader_s.html|title=Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein leader arrested for suspected involvement in 40-year-old murder, has strong ties to Western Massachusetts|date=May 1, 2014|last=Johnson|first=Patrick}}</ref><ref name=\"cq-2004\">Duncan, Philip D., and Nutting, Brian (eds.) (2004). \"Neal, Richard E., D-Mass.\" ''[[CQ's Politics in America|CQ's Politics in America 2004: The 108th Congress]]''. Washington: [[Congressional Quarterly]]. pp. 483\u2013484. {{ISBN|978-1-56802-813-2}}.</ref> In 2017, Mayor [[Alex Morse]] would work with Neal's office to formally establish a [[sister city]] relationship between Holyoke and [[Tralee]], of [[County Kerry]], mirroring a sister city agreement with neighboring Springfield.<ref>{{cite web|author=Plaisance, Mike|url=http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2017/04/exchange_program_linking_holyo.html|title=School exchange program linking Holyoke, Tralee, Ireland benefit of sister-city relationship: Mayor Alex Morse|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426142811/http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2017/04/exchange_program_linking_holyo.html|archive-date=April 26, 2017|date=April 26, 2014|accessdate=August 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mayor Sarno and Congressman Neal Welcome Toireasa Ferris, Kerry County Councilor for Tralee, Ireland|publisher=City of Springfield (Mass.)|url=https://www3.springfield-ma.gov/cos/index.php?id=news-story&tx_news_pi1%5Bnews%5D=13663&tx_news_pi1%5Bcontroller%5D=News&tx_news_pi1%5Baction%5D=detail&cHash=424e591bef53bcd4ec20616318b03f43|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Saint Patrick Chapel, Saint Jerome Church, Holyoke, Massachusetts.JPG|thumb|left|The Saint Patrick Chapel at Saint Jerome Parish]]\n\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = vertical\n   | width = 180\n   | align = right\n   | footer = The John F. Kennedy Memorial, at the corner of Suffolk and Appleton in front of Our Lady of the Cross Parish, dedicated in 1967; Holyoke Police officers lead the St. Patrick's Parade with the colors of the Holyoke, Ireland, and the United States\n   | image1 = John_F._Kennedy_Memorial,_Holyoke,_Massachusetts.jpg\n   | image2 = Flag carrying officers lead the 2019 Holyoke Saint Patrick's Day Parade.jpg}}\nToday Holyoke's Irish leave the legacy of not only the cultural institutions and structures they built but also the cultural diaspora. Perhaps most famously at the start of the 20th century, two brothers from Holyoke, the Sheas, would contribute a song which resonates in popular culture to this day. The [[Victory March (fight song)|Victory March]] of [[Fighting Irish|Notre Dame's Fighting Irish]], was first written and publicly performed in Holyoke in the winter of 1908 by John and Rev. Michael Shea, both alumni of the college. Michael Shea was the organist for [[St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)|St. Patrick's Cathedral]] in New York City at that time, and returned to Holyoke to devise the song with his brother who lived there. Shortly after completing their composition, Father Michael would run into his childhood music teacher, Professor [[William C. Hammond (organist)|William C. Hammond]] of [[Mount Holyoke College]], who was the music director of the Second Congregational Church. Upon telling Hammond about their aspiring rally song, Hammond suggested Shea perform it in on the church's organ, and in 1908 the fight song for a world renowned Catholic research university was first publicly performed at a Protestant church in Holyoke. At the conclusion of the performance, a group of the church's deacons walked in and \"were not a little shocked to see a man wearing a Roman collar energetically thumping away on the keys of their organ. One deacon had a remark to make when the recital was finished. 'Brother,' he said, 'you've got something there.'\"<ref>{{cite book|pages=209\u2013210|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.80345#page/n221/mode/2up/|title=The Notre Dame Story|year=1949|last=Wallace|first=Francis|publisher=Rinehart & Company, Inc|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Catholic Digest|volume=7|title=He Had Something|year=1942|publisher=College of St. Thomas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5wUAAAAIAAJ|quote=They[, the church deacons,] were not a little shocked to see a man wearing a Roman collar energetically thumping away on the keys of their organ. One deacon had a remark to make when the recital was finished. 'Brother,' he said, 'you've got something there'\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=Game Day|publisher=University of Notre Dame|archive-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915212434/https://gameday.nd.edu/traditions/notre-dame-music/victory-march/|url=https://gameday.nd.edu/traditions/notre-dame-music/victory-march/|title=Notre Dame Victory March}}</ref> The tune has since been described by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' and [[CBS Sports]] as the most recognizable fight song in college football today.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 15 all-time greatest college football fight songs, ranked|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/photos/best-college-football-fight-songs/15/|archive-date=September 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915215222/https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/photos/best-college-football-fight-songs/|quote=1. \"Victory March\" (Notre Dame Fighting Irish) Whether or not you're a fan of the Fighting Irish, you gotta admit that few fight songs in college football carry the prestige, recognition and gravitas as that of Notre Dame's \"Victory March.\" The song was composed in 1908 by two brothers who had attended Notre Dame, John and Michael Shea, and went on to make an appearance in the classic 1940 biographical film, ''Knute Rockne, All American''|website=CBS Sports|date=August 19, 2015}}</ref>\n \n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | \"It is nice to be Irish anytime, but it is especially nice on March 17 in Holyoke\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\"|&mdash;Sen. John F. Kennedy, receiving inaugural parade award as a Distinguished American of Irish Descent, March 16, 1958<ref>{{cite news|title=Colorful Tribute Paid Irish; Kennedy is Hailed As Great Example of Irish American|pages=1, 7|date=March 17, 1958|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\nFollowing a memorial mass at Holy Cross Parish, on May 30, 1967, a year after [[Ted Kennedy]] received his brother's namesake award and marched in the St. Patrick's Parade,<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards|archive-date=July 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710153941/https://holyokestpatricksparade.com/awards/|url=https://holyokestpatricksparade.com/awards/|publisher=Holyoke St. Patrick's Parade Committee|year=2019}}</ref> the Parade Committee dedicated a bust of John F. Kennedy at the corner of Suffolk and Appleton Streets. Presiding over the ceremony were Mayor [[Daniel F. Dibble]], Bishop [[Christopher Joseph Weldon]], Maurice J. Ferriter, and William Rogers, who all played active roles in fundraising for the monument. Cousin Robert P. Fitzgerald would be in attendence, and although the ceremony was unable to be attended by Ted or [[Bobby Kennedy]], the former would make a special phone call to the dedication site from Washington, and the latter would send a telegram noting their late brother's affection for Holyoke and its people. [[David M. Bartley]] would serve as the ceremonies key speaker.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bust of Kennedy Dedicated in Holyoke|page=21|work=The Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=May 31, 1967}}</ref> The memorial remains a part of the ceremonies of the St. Patrick's Day Parade events every year.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Republican|location=Springfield, Mass.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921230701/https://www.masslive.com/news/2017/02/irish_flag_raised_in_holyoke_k.html|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2017/02/irish_flag_raised_in_holyoke_k.html|title=Irish flag raised in Holyoke, kicking off St. Patrick's Day Parade celebrations|last=Rom\u00e1n|first=Elizabeth|date=February 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn recent decades Irish identity in the Holyoke area has seen renewed interest in language. As recently as 2016 Holyoke Community College maintained a small Irish Studies department offering coursework in Island Literature, Culture, and the study of the Irish diaspora,<ref>{{cite report|title=2016 Course Equivalency Guide|publisher=Holyoke Community College|url=https://www.hcc.edu/Documents/Courses-Programs/Transfer/Westfieldcourseguide.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713062221/https://www.hcc.edu/Documents/Courses-Programs/Transfer/Westfieldcourseguide.pdf|archive-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> and today Elms College in Chicopee offers a minor in Irish Studies.<ref>{{cite report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811192230/https://www.elms.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Fact-Book-2018.pdf|url=https://www.elms.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Fact-Book-2018.pdf|archive-date=August 11, 2019|publisher=Elms College|title=Fact Book 2018}}</ref> The latter was largely created through the efforts of local scholar Thomas Moriarty, a professor emeritus of history. Moriarty, along with Sister Kathleen Keating, then-president of Elms, and Sean Cahillane, would launch the Irish Cultural Center at the college in 1999, and in 2015 it was spun off into a separate entity, the Irish Cultural Center of Western New England based out of [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]]. Sponsored in part by the [[Irish Abroad Unit|Emigrant Support Programme]] of the Government of Ireland, today the center offers classes in the Irish language as well as tours of Ireland, and hosts events around Irish cuisine, literature, and song.<ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Cultural Center of Western New England|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811191641/https://www.irishcenterwne.org/|archive-date=August 11, 2019|url=https://www.irishcenterwne.org/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|location=Springfield, Mass.|date=July 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811192226/https://www.masslive.com/news/2015/07/iirish_cultural_center_announces_move_from_elms_college_to_former_elks_lodge_in_west_springfield.html|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2015/07/iirish_cultural_center_announces_move_from_elms_college_to_former_elks_lodge_in_west_springfield.html|archive-date=August 11, 2019|title=Irish Cultural Center announces move from Elms College to former Elks Lodge in West Springfield|work=The Republican|last=Flynn|first=Anne-Gerard}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\nAmong Holyoke's few literary works was Mary Doyle Curran's ''The Parish and the Hill''. Published in 1948 by [[Houghton Mifflin]], it was the only novel its author would publish, and would be republished by the [[City University of New York]]'s [[Feminist Press]] in 1986 and 2002; their editors lauded it as \"one of the first to explore Irish life from a woman's point of view\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Parish and the Hill|last=Curran|first=Mary Doyle|oclc=1025481370|publisher=Feminist Press at the City University of New York}}</ref> Described by ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' as an \"evocative, effective picture of the disintegration occurring when prejudicial discrimination and derision uproots the pride of nationality\", the book shows the hardships of a first generation Irish immigrant family of the later waves, and their \"climb from shanty Irish to lace curtain Irish\".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Kirkus Reviews|location=New York|archive-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907203440/https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/mary-doyle-curran/the-parish-and-the-hill/|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/mary-doyle-curran/the-parish-and-the-hill/|title=The Parish and the Hill \u2013 Kirkus Review|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> Curran's poetry was featured in the Boston literary journal ''[[Ploughshares]]'' in 1979, and posthumously her unpublished anthology ''The Paper City'' has been featured in ''MELUS'', the journal of the [[The Society for the Study of the Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States|Society for the Study of the Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]], for early portrayals of the uneasy interethnic relations between early Irish and French immigrant arrivals as well as attitudes toward an indifferent Yankee upper class.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Ploughshares|publisher=Emerson College|location=Boston|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907203842/https://www.pshares.org/authors/mary-doyle-curran|url=https://www.pshares.org/authors/mary-doyle-curran|archive-date=September 7, 2019|title=Mary Doyle Curran}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/467499|title=Mary Doyle Curran: 'Over These Prison Walls I Would Fly'|last=Halley|first=Anne|journal=MELUS|volume=15|issue=3|date=Autumn 1988|pages=3\u20136|jstor=467499}}</ref> Toward the end of her career Curran would head the Irish Studies department at [[UMass Boston]], today the university offers a need-based creative writing scholarship to both graduate and undergraduate students in her name.<ref>{{cite web|website=UMass Boston College of Liberal Arts|publisher=University of Massachusetts|access-date=September 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907205611/https://www.umb.edu/academics/cla/english/prizes_and_scholarships|archive-date=September 7, 2019|url=https://www.umb.edu/academics/cla/english/prizes_and_scholarships|title=Prizes and Scholarships for English Majors}}</ref> Today Curran's papers and unpublished manuscripts are in the Special Collections of the [[W.E.B. DuBois Library]] at [[UMass Amherst]].<ref>{{cite web|website=Special Collections and University Archives|publisher=UMass Amherst|title=Mary Doyle Curran Papers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907210833/http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums435|archive-date=September 7, 2019|url=http://scua.library.umass.edu/ead/mums435}}</ref>\n\nThough not as specifically discussing the social conditions of Irish families in Holyoke, 20th-century American novelist [[Raymond Kennedy]] would draw heavily on his own childhood in the city in his works, portraying several in a fictional backdrop of the city, identified by its historical moniker as \"Ireland Parish\".<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|url=https://wwwz.nytimes.com/1988/04/17/books/paperback-her-mind-ran-to-lurid-extremes.html|title=PAPERBACK; Her Mind Ran to Lurid Extremes|last=Huggan|first=Isabel|date=April 17, 1988}}</ref><ref name=\"legendary\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Fifty Years of Marching Together 1952-2001: A Social History of the St. Patrick's Committee of Holyoke, Massachusetts Parade|last1=Gold|first1=Catherine Dower|location=Westhampton, Mass.|year=2001|publisher=Edgar C. Alward & Jean A. Alward; Esparto Press}}\n* {{cite book | last1=Harper | first=Wyatt E. | title=The Story of Holyoke | year=1973 | publisher=Centennial Committee of the City of Holyoke | oclc=8060402 |url = https://archive.org/stream/storyofholyoke00harp#page/n0/mode/2up}}\n* {{cite book | last=Hartford |first=William F. | title=Working people of Holyoke : class and ethnicity in a Massachusetts mill town, 1850\u20131960|location=New Brunswick, NJ.| publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1990| isbn= 9780813515762|oclc= 21041495}}\n* {{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=izf0clTZf7cC&pg=PA61|pages=61\u201371|chapter=Chapter 8: Irish Immigrants Build Holyoke|last1=Juravich|last2=Hartford|last3=Green|first1=Tom|first2=William F.|first3=James R.|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst, Mass.|year=1996|title=Commonwealth of Toil, Chapters in the History of Massachusetts Workers and Their Unions|oclc=34598201}}\n* {{cite book|title=History of St. Jerome's Parish, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Diocese of Springfield; issued in connection with the Observance of its Diamond Jubilee|year=1931|last=Lucey|first=P. J.|publisher=Diocese of Springfield|location=Holyoke, Mass.|oclc=42457185}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Irish Legacy: A History of the Irish in Western Massachusetts|year=2012|location=Springfield, Mass.|publisher=The Republican|oclc=819651686}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://aoh-holyoke.com/ Ancient Order of Hibernians of Hampden/Hampshire Counties], Holyoke, Massachusetts\n* [https://www.irishcenterwne.org/ Irish Cultural Center of Western New England], West Springfield, Massachusetts\n* [https://lvirishslowsession.wordpress.com/ Lower Valley Irish Slow Session], Irish traditional music session based in Holyoke\n* [http://ourpluralhistory.stcc.edu/industrial/irish.html Irish Immigrants in Holyoke], Our Plural History, Springfield Technical Community College\n\n{{Holyoke, Massachusetts}}\n{{Irish Americans by location}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Holyoke, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture by city]]\n[[Category:Irish-American history]]\n[[Category:Irish-American culture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:History of Holyoke, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Irish_in_Holyoke"}
{"title_page": "Les Chadwick", "text_new": "{{short description|English bassist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n'''John Leslie Chadwick'''<ref name=\"Ask\">{{cite web |url=http://uk.ask.com/music/artist//63537 |title=Ask Jeeves - What's Your Question? |publisher=Uk.ask.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-08 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> (11 May 1943<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0149494/bio|title=Les Chadwick : Biography|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-07}}</ref> &ndash; 26 December 2019), was an [[English people|English]] [[bassist]], best known as a member of [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]].\n\n==Career==\nChadwick was born in [[Aigburth]], [[Liverpool]], [[Merseyside]], England.  His [[bass guitar]] work can be heard on all of the 1960s [[sound recording and reproduction|recordings]] made by the [[pop music|pop]] [[musical ensemble|group]], [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]].<ref name=\"Ask\"/>\n\nChadwick originally did not own a bass guitar and played a standard [[Fender Stratocaster]] with the bass setting exaggerated until obtaining a proper bass. He eventually acquired a sunburst [[Epiphone Rivoli]] bass which he used for most of his performances with the Pacemakers. This bass can be seen in the film ''[[Ferry Cross the Mersey (film)|Ferry Cross the Mersey]]'', in which Chadwick has a substantial role as Gerry Marsden's sidekick \"Chad\". {{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nLike many British bassists of the era, he used a plectrum and favoured short scale hollow body basses such as the [[Epiphone]] and a [[H\u00f6fner]]  Verythin.\n\nOn 19 October 1961, [[the Beatles]] and Gerry and the Pacemakers merged to become the 'Beatmakers', for a one-off performance in [[Litherland]] Town Hall. The line-up comprised [[Gerry Marsden]], [[George Harrison]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[John Lennon]], [[Les Maguire]], [[Pete Best]], Freddy Marsden, plus vocalist Karl Terry from the Cruisers with Chadwick on [[bass guitar]].<ref name=\"NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\">{{cite book\n| first= John\n| last= Tobler\n| year= 1992\n| title= NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Reed International Books Ltd\n| location= London\n| page= [https://archive.org/details/nmerocknrollyear0000unse/page/99 99]\n| isbn= 978-0600576020\n| url= https://archive.org/details/nmerocknrollyear0000unse/page/99\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Pacemakers split up in 1966, he bought a [[Automobile repair shop|garage]] with fellow former Pacemaker, [[Les Maguire]]. In 1973, Chadwick moved to [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], where he set up an [[employment agency]].<ref name=\"Ask\"/>\n\nHe died in Sydney on 26 December 2019, from [[brain cancer]].<ref>[https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Pacemaker+Les%2C+76%2C+loses+battle+with+brain+cancer%3B+FRIENDS+PAY...-a0610092868  Paddy Shennan, \"Pacemaker Les, 76, loses battle with brain cancer\", ''Liverpool Echo'', 2019]. Retrieved 8 January 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/search/top/?q=%22Les%20Chadwick%22&epa=SEARCH_BOX  \"John Leslie \u201cLes\u201d Chadwick, bass guitarist with Gerry & the Pacemakers has passed away.\", ''Facebook'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Gerry and the Pacemakers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chadwick, Les}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:English rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Beat musicians]]\n\n{{England-musician-stub}}\n{{UK-bass-guitarist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English bassist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n'''John Leslie Chadwick'''<ref name=\"Ask\">{{cite web |url=http://uk.ask.com/music/artist//63537 |title=Ask Jeeves - What's Your Question? |publisher=Uk.ask.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-08 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> (11 May 1943<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0149494/bio|title=Les Chadwick : Biography|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-07}}</ref> &ndash; 26 December 2019), was an [[English people|English]] [[bassist]], best known as a member of [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]].\n\n==Career==\nChadwick was born in [[Aigburth]], [[Liverpool]], [[Merseyside]], England.  His [[bass guitar]] work can be heard on all of the 1960s [[sound recording and reproduction|recordings]] made by the [[pop music|pop]] [[musical ensemble|group]], [[Gerry and the Pacemakers]].<ref name=\"Ask\"/>\n\nChadwick originally did not own a bass guitar and played a standard [[Fender Stratocaster]] with the bass setting exaggerated until obtaining a proper bass. He eventually acquired a sunburst [[Epiphone Rivoli]] bass which he used for most of his performances with the Pacemakers. This bass can be seen in the film ''[[Ferry Cross the Mersey]]'', in which Chadwick has a substantial role as Gerry Marsden's sidekick \"Chad\". {{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nLike many British bassists of the era, he used a plectrum and favoured short scale hollow body basses such as the [[Epiphone]] and a [[H\u00f6fner]]  Verythin.\n\nOn 19 October 1961, [[the Beatles]] and Gerry and the Pacemakers merged to become the 'Beatmakers', for a one-off performance in [[Litherland]] Town Hall. The line-up comprised [[Gerry Marsden]], [[George Harrison]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[John Lennon]], [[Les Maguire]], [[Pete Best]], Freddy Marsden, plus vocalist Karl Terry from the Cruisers with Chadwick on [[bass guitar]].<ref name=\"NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\">{{cite book\n| first= John\n| last= Tobler\n| year= 1992\n| title= NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Reed International Books Ltd\n| location= London\n| page= [https://archive.org/details/nmerocknrollyear0000unse/page/99 99]\n| isbn= 978-0600576020\n| url= https://archive.org/details/nmerocknrollyear0000unse/page/99\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Pacemakers split up in 1966, he bought a [[Automobile repair shop|garage]] with fellow former Pacemaker, [[Les Maguire]]. In 1973, Chadwick moved to [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], where he set up an [[employment agency]].<ref name=\"Ask\"/>\n\nHe died in Sydney on 26 December 2019, from [[brain cancer]].<ref>[https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Pacemaker+Les%2C+76%2C+loses+battle+with+brain+cancer%3B+FRIENDS+PAY...-a0610092868  Paddy Shennan, \"Pacemaker Les, 76, loses battle with brain cancer\", ''Liverpool Echo'', 2019]. Retrieved 8 January 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/search/top/?q=%22Les%20Chadwick%22&epa=SEARCH_BOX  \"John Leslie \u201cLes\u201d Chadwick, bass guitarist with Gerry & the Pacemakers has passed away.\", ''Facebook'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Gerry and the Pacemakers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chadwick, Les}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:English rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Beat musicians]]\n\n{{England-musician-stub}}\n{{UK-bass-guitarist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "KR7907", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Les_Chadwick"}
{"title_page": "Lise Thibault", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Lise Thibault\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image            = Lise Thibault (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| order            =\n| office           = 27th [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]]\n| predecessor      = [[Jean-Louis Roux]]\n| successor        = [[Pierre Duchesne]]\n| term_start       = 30 January 1997\n| term_end         = 7 June 2007\n| monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor_general = [[Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc]]<br>[[Adrienne Clarkson]]<br>[[Micha\u00eblle Jean]]\n| premier          = [[Lucien Bouchard]]<br>[[Bernard Landry]]<br>[[Jean Charest]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1939|04|2}}\n| birth_place      = [[Saint-Roch-de-l'Achigan, Quebec]], Canada\n| parents          = Paul Trudel <br> Laurenza Wolfe\n| spouse           = Ren\u00e9 Thibault\n| alma_mater       = [[C\u00e9gep de Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me]]\n| profession       = Civil servant, Teacher, Journalist\n}}\n'''Lise Thibault''' ({{IPA-fr|liz tibo}}; born 2 April 1939) is a Canadian politician who served as the [[List of lieutenant governors of Quebec#Lieutenant Governors of Quebec, 1867\u2013present|27th]] [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]] from 1997 to 2007 and later spent six months in jail for misuse of public funds and ordered to repay the government.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Saint-Roch-de-l'Achigan, Quebec|Saint-Roch-de-l'Achigan]], Quebec, she was the eldest daughter of Paul Trudel and Laurenza Wolfe. She was educated at the Acad\u00e9mie Marie-Anne de Montr\u00e9al, and then went on to teachers' college at [[C\u00e9gep de Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me]]. She married Ren\u00e9 Thibault in 1959.<ref name=LiseThibault>{{cite web  | title=Lise Thibault  | url=http://franco.ca/edimage/grandspersonnages/en/carte_r04.html  | publisher=The Great Names of the French Canadian Community  | year=2000  | accessdate=20 October 2011  | url-status=dead  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827040054/http://franco.ca/edimage/grandspersonnages/en/carte_r04.html  | archivedate=27 August 2011  }}</ref> Thibault was permanently disabled in a [[toboggan]]ing accident as a teenager, and uses a [[wheelchair]].<ref name=\"CBC-Testimony\">{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault, ex-Quebec lieutenant-governor, testifies at her fraud trial|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-ex-quebec-lieutenant-governor-testifies-at-her-fraud-trial-1.2720523|website=CBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=30 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CollectionsCanadaBio\">{{cite web|title=Archived - Celebrating Women's Achievements|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/women/030001-1310-e.html|website=Collections Canada|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=24 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151101124225/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/women/030001-1310-e.html|archive-date=1 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThibault taught with the adult education department of the [[Mille-Isles, Quebec|Milles-\u00celes]] and Des \u00c9cores school boards from 1973 to 1978. She worked for [[TVA (Canada)|T\u00e9l\u00e9-M\u00e9tropole]] from 1977 to 1981. From 1982 to 1984 she was a host and researcher at the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] as for programs about family and community issues. She was the vice president for Quebec's Commission de la sant\u00e9 et de la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 du travail (CSST) from 1987 to 1993. She was President and CEO of the Office des personnes handicap\u00e9es du Qu\u00e9bec from 1993 to 1995.<ref name=LiseThibault/>\n\nShe was closely associated with the federal [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] for many years, and on the advice of Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], the Governor General appointed her Lieutenant-Governor of Quebec, following the resignation of [[Jean-Louis Roux]] in 1997. She became Quebec's first female viceroy, and the first disabled lieutenant governor in Canada. In February 2005 Thibault suffered a stroke.<ref name=\"Gazette-editorial\">{{cite web|title=Editorial: Former lieutenant-governor Lise Thibault 'highly reprehensible' behaviour justly punished|url=https://montrealgazette.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-former-lieutenant-governor-lise-thibault-highly-reprehensible-behaviour-justly-punished|website=Montreal Gazette|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=2 October 2015}}</ref> She was one of the longest serving lieutenant governors in Canadian history, serving for over ten years.\n\n==Trial and imprisonment for fraud==\nBeginning in 2007, Thibault was accused of spending beyond the limits of her expense account.<ref name=\"JournalDeQuebec-timeline\">{{cite web|last1=Racine|first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|title=Huit dates importantes de la saga Lise Thibault|url=http://www.journaldequebec.com/2015/09/29/lise-thibault-doit-connaitre-sa-sentence-mercredi|website=Journal de Quebec|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> Questions on her spending continued after her departure, with federal and provincial auditors general pointing to $700,000 in unjustified expenses.<ref name=\"CBC-auditor report\">{{cite web|title=Auditors challenge $700,000 in spending by Quebec's former Lt.-Gov.|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/auditors-challenge-700-000-in-spending-by-quebec-s-former-lt-gov-1.639176|website=CBC News|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> Among the expenses were:<ref>{{cite web|title=Thibault defends expenses |url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=8ec15a6f-28f2-4ba5-b075-0a9d1e53159a |accessdate=1 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108221937/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=8ec15a6f-28f2-4ba5-b075-0a9d1e53159a |archivedate= 8 November 2015 }}</ref>\n* $45,000 for \"gifts\" without the names of recipients.\n* $24,000 to transport her official van to the United States while she was on vacation, rather than renting a car there.\n* $12,000 to the provincial air service for a one-day fishing trip in the Gaspe region.\n* $44,000 in \"tips\" paid by her bodyguards during hotel stays and sporting activities.\n\nThe files were turned over to the [[S\u00fbret\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]] (SQ) and [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) for investigation. She was criminally charged for offences involving fraud, breach of trust, forgery and fabrication of false documents related to the misspending of public funds during her ten years in office.<ref>The Globe and Mail [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/former-quebec-lieutenant-governor-facing-charges/article1302112/ \"Former Quebec lieutenant-governor facing charges\"]</ref> Thibault's lawyer argued unsuccessfully in [[Quebec Superior Court]] that Thibault should receive [[sovereign immunity]], because \"[[Monarchy of Canada|the Crown]]'s prosecution cannot prosecute the Crown\"\u2014referring to her prior office as the Queen's representative in Quebec.<ref>Canadian Press. \"[https://vancouversun.com/news/court+amused+Canadian+judge+rejects+royal+privilege+argument/7152310/story.html The court is not amused: Canadian judge rejects royal privilege argument.]\" ''The Vancouver Sun'', 27 August 2012.</ref>\n\nIn September 2015 she was sentenced 18 months in jail and was ordered to repay the government $300,000 ($200,000 to Ottawa and $100,000 to Qu\u00e9bec) after pleading guilty to fraud and breach of trust in 2014.<ref name=\"CBC_guilty-plea\">{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault, ex-Quebec lieutenant-governor, pleads guilty to 6 charges|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-ex-quebec-lieutenant-governor-pleads-guilty-to-6-charges-1.2864277|website=CBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=8 December 2014}}</ref> Judge Carol St-Cyr outlined her crimes, pointing out that she \"took advantage of holes in the system and abused her position of authority to pay for trips, golf lessons and birthday parties... [and] forgot that her role as lieutenant-governor was to be a good example for Quebecers.\"<ref name=sentence>{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault ordered to repay $300K, serve 18 months|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-sentencing-1.3249849|website=CBC|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2016, the Quebec Court of Appeal upheld Thibault's 18-month sentence,<ref name=\"CBC_appeal\">{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault's 18-month sentence challenge rejected by Quebec Court of Appeal|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-s-18-month-sentence-challenge-rejected-by-quebec-court-of-appeal-1.3461786|website=CBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=24 February 2016}}</ref> and the next day Thibault surrendered at the Quebec City Detention Centre.<ref name=\"CTV-imprisoned\">{{cite web|title=Former Lt-Gov Thibault now in jail|url=http://montreal.ctvnews.ca/former-lt-gov-thibault-now-in-jail-1.2792448|website=CTV News|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"GLobe-Sentence-begun\">{{cite web|title=Ex-lieutenant-governor Lise Thibault begins prison sentence in Quebec City|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/ex-lieutenant-governor-lise-thibault-begins-prison-sentence-in-quebec-city/article28912036/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Star-begins-sentence\">{{cite web|title=Former Quebec lieutenant-governor Lise Thibault behind bars|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/02/25/former-quebec-lieutenant-governor-lise-thibault-behind-bars.html|website=The Toronto Star|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref> She was transferred in late February 2016 to the Leclerc Detention Centre in Laval, Quebec.<ref name=\"JDQ-transfer\">{{cite web|last1=Racine|first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|title=Lise Thibault a quitt\u00e9 Qu\u00e9bec|url=http://www.journaldequebec.com/2016/03/03/lise-thibault-a-quitte-quebec|website=Le Journal de Quebec|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TVA-transfer\">{{cite web|title=\u00c0 sa demande, Lise Thibault change de prison|url=http://www.tvanouvelles.ca/2016/03/03/exclusif--lise-thibault-change-de-prison|website=TVA Nouvelles|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> She was granted a conditional release on 2 June 2016, and was fully discharged on 17 August 2017. In the meantime, she filed for [[bankruptcy]] in June of that year, citing of debt of $1,5 millions to [[Canada Revenue Agency]] and [[Revenu Qu\u00e9bec]] (the initial $300,000 she was ordered to pay had already been reimbursed).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.journaldequebec.com/2017/06/17/lise-thibault-declare-faillite |title= Lise Thibault d\u00e9clare faillite|first= |last= |date=17 June 2017 |website=Le Journal de Qu\u00e9bec |publisher=|language = fr }}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours, and arms==\n\n{{Infobox viceroy styles\n| image    = \n| name     = Lise Thibault<br>(1997&ndash;2007)\n| dipstyle = {{unbulleted list | Her Honour the Honourable | ''Son Honneur l'honorable''}}\n| offstyle = {{unbulleted list | Your Honour | ''Votre Honneur''}}\n}}\n\n=== Titles ===\n* 2 April 1939 {{spaced ndash}}30 January 1997: ''Ms./Madame'' Lise Thibault\n* 30 January 1997{{spaced ndash}}7 June 2007: ''Her Honour the Honourable'' Lise Thibault, Lieutenant Governor of Quebec\n* 7 June 2007{{spaced ndash}}: ''The Honourable'' Lise Thibault\n\nAs a former [[Viceroy|viceregal]] representative of [[Elizabeth II]], as [[Monarchy in Quebec|Queen in Right of Quebec]], Thibault is styled ''The [[Honourable]]'' for life.<ref name=\"HEritage-styles\">{{cite web|title=Titles|url=http://canada.pch.gc.ca/eng/1452017684393|website=Canadian Heritage|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"GC-CA-Table-Of-Titles\">{{cite web|title=Table of Titles to be used in Canada|url=http://canada.pch.gc.ca/eng/1452187406810/1453733836056|website=Government of Canada|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite web|last1=Hicks|first1=Ryan|title=Lise Thibault should be stripped of pension, title: Democracy Watch|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-should-be-stripped-of-pension-title-democracy-watch-1.3300010|website=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n\nLise Thibault Has Received 3 Honorary Degrees\n\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Province/State</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Quebec}} || November 1999 || [[Concordia University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>http://archives.concordia.ca/degrees-chrono</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Quebec}} || 2 June 2001 || [[Bishop's University]] || [[Doctor of Civil Law]] (DCL)  <ref>http://www3.ubishops.ca/fileadmin/bishops_documents/alumni/files/newsletter/aug_2001.pdf</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Massachusetts}} || 2003 || [[Anna Maria College]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)\n|-\n|}\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = Lise Thibault Arms.svg\n|bannerimage =\n|badgeimage =\n|notes = The arms of Lise Thibault consist of:<ref>{{citation|title=Canadian Heraldic Authority (Volume III)\n|year=1999 |publisher=Ottawa}}</ref>\n|adopted =\n|crest = Upon a helmet mantled Azure doubled Argent within a wreath of these colours upon a grassy mound Vert an oak tree Argent fructed Azure.\n|torse =\n|helm =\n|escutcheon = Azure between two quills in chief and a treble clef in base a swallow volant Argent holding in the beak a Blue Flag Or.\n|supporters = Two does Azure and Argent gorged with maple leaves Or pendant therefrom a bezant the dexter one charged with two ears of wheat the sinister one with two sprigs of flax one bearing two flowers the other four all Azure.\n|compartment = A grassy mound Vert bearing lilies between two maple leaves Or.\n|motto = Cr\u00e9er La Vie\n|orders =\n|other_elements =\n|banner =\n|badge =\n|symbolism =\n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{QCLG}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thibault, Lise}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dames of Justice of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Women in Quebec politics]]\n[[Category:Canadian women viceroys]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of fraud]]\n[[Category:People from Lanaudi\u00e8re]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Lise Thibault\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image            = Lise Thibault (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| order            =\n| office           = 27th [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]]\n| predecessor      = [[Jean-Louis Roux]]\n| successor        = [[Pierre Duchesne]]\n| term_start       = January 30, 1997\n| term_end         = June 7, 2007\n| monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor_general = [[Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc]]<br>[[Adrienne Clarkson]]<br>[[Micha\u00eblle Jean]]\n| premier          = [[Lucien Bouchard]]<br>[[Bernard Landry]]<br>[[Jean Charest]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1939|04|2}}\n| birth_place      = [[Saint-Roch-de-l'Achigan, Quebec]], Canada\n| parents          = Paul Trudel <br> Laurenza Wolfe\n| spouse           = Ren\u00e9 Thibault\n| alma_mater       = [[C\u00e9gep de Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me]]\n| profession       = Civil servant, Teacher, Journalist\n}}\n'''Lise Thibault''' ({{IPA-fr|liz tibo}}; born 2 April 1939) is a Canadian politician who served as the [[List of lieutenant governors of Quebec#Lieutenant Governors of Quebec, 1867\u2013present|27th]] [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]] from 1997 to 2007 and later spent six months in jail for misuse of public funds and ordered to repay the government.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Saint-Roch-de-l'Achigan, Quebec|Saint-Roch-de-l'Achigan]], Quebec, she was the eldest daughter of Paul Trudel and Laurenza Wolfe. She was educated at the Acad\u00e9mie Marie-Anne de Montr\u00e9al, and then went on to teachers' college at [[C\u00e9gep de Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me]]. She married Ren\u00e9 Thibault in 1959.<ref name=LiseThibault>{{cite web  | title=Lise Thibault  | url=http://franco.ca/edimage/grandspersonnages/en/carte_r04.html  | publisher=The Great Names of the French Canadian Community  | year=2000  | accessdate=2011-10-20  | url-status=dead  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827040054/http://franco.ca/edimage/grandspersonnages/en/carte_r04.html  | archivedate=2011-08-27  }}</ref> Thibault was permanently disabled in a [[toboggan]]ing accident as a teenager, and uses a [[wheelchair]].<ref name=\"CBC-Testimony\">{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault, ex-Quebec lieutenant-governor, testifies at her fraud trial|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-ex-quebec-lieutenant-governor-testifies-at-her-fraud-trial-1.2720523|website=CBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=30 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CollectionsCanadaBio\">{{cite web|title=Archived - Celebrating Women's Achievements|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/women/030001-1310-e.html|website=Collections Canada|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=24 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151101124225/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/women/030001-1310-e.html|archive-date=1 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThibault taught with the adult education department of the [[Mille-Isles, Quebec|Milles-\u00celes]] and Des \u00c9cores school boards from 1973 to 1978. She worked for [[TVA (Canada)|T\u00e9l\u00e9-M\u00e9tropole]] from 1977 to 1981. From 1982 to 1984 she was a host and researcher at the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] as for programs about family and community issues. She was the vice president for Quebec's Commission de la sant\u00e9 et de la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 du travail (CSST) from 1987 to 1993. She was President and CEO of the Office des personnes handicap\u00e9es du Qu\u00e9bec from 1993 to 1995.<ref name=LiseThibault/>\n\nShe was closely associated with the federal [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] for many years, and on the advice of Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], the Governor General appointed her Lieutenant-Governor of Quebec, following the resignation of [[Jean-Louis Roux]] in 1997. She became Quebec's first female viceroy, and the first disabled lieutenant governor in Canada. In February 2005 Thibault suffered a stroke.<ref name=\"Gazette-editorial\">{{cite web|title=Editorial: Former lieutenant-governor Lise Thibault 'highly reprehensible' behaviour justly punished|url=https://montrealgazette.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-former-lieutenant-governor-lise-thibault-highly-reprehensible-behaviour-justly-punished|website=Montreal Gazette|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=2 October 2015}}</ref> She was one of the longest serving lieutenant governors in Canadian history, serving for over ten years.\n\n==Trial and imprisonment for fraud==\nBeginning in 2007, Thibault was accused of spending beyond the limits of her expense account.<ref name=\"JournalDeQuebec-timeline\">{{cite web|last1=Racine|first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|title=Huit dates importantes de la saga Lise Thibault|url=http://www.journaldequebec.com/2015/09/29/lise-thibault-doit-connaitre-sa-sentence-mercredi|website=Journal de Quebec|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> Questions on her spending continued after her departure, with federal and provincial auditors general pointing to $700,000 in unjustified expenses.<ref name=\"CBC-auditor report\">{{cite web|title=Auditors challenge $700,000 in spending by Quebec's former Lt.-Gov.|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/auditors-challenge-700-000-in-spending-by-quebec-s-former-lt-gov-1.639176|website=CBC News|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> Among the expenses were:<ref>{{cite web|title=Thibault defends expenses |url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=8ec15a6f-28f2-4ba5-b075-0a9d1e53159a |accessdate=1 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108221937/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=8ec15a6f-28f2-4ba5-b075-0a9d1e53159a |archivedate= 8 November 2015 }}</ref>\n* $45,000 for \"gifts\" without the names of recipients.\n* $24,000 to transport her official van to the United States while she was on vacation, rather than renting a car there.\n* $12,000 to the provincial air service for a one-day fishing trip in the Gaspe region.\n* $44,000 in \"tips\" paid by her bodyguards during hotel stays and sporting activities.\n\nThe files were turned over to the [[S\u00fbret\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]] (SQ) and [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) for investigation. She was criminally charged for offences involving fraud, breach of trust, forgery and fabrication of false documents related to the misspending of public funds during her ten years in office.<ref>The Globe and Mail [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/former-quebec-lieutenant-governor-facing-charges/article1302112/ \"Former Quebec lieutenant-governor facing charges\"]</ref> Thibault's lawyer argued unsuccessfully in [[Quebec Superior Court]] that Thibault should receive [[sovereign immunity]], because \"[[Monarchy of Canada|the Crown]]'s prosecution cannot prosecute the Crown\"\u2014referring to her prior office as the Queen's representative in Quebec.<ref>Canadian Press. \"[https://vancouversun.com/news/court+amused+Canadian+judge+rejects+royal+privilege+argument/7152310/story.html The court is not amused: Canadian judge rejects royal privilege argument.]\" ''The Vancouver Sun'', August 27, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn September 2015 she was sentenced 18 months in jail and was ordered to repay the government $300,000 ($200,000 to Ottawa and $100,000 to Qu\u00e9bec) after pleading guilty to fraud and breach of trust in 2014.<ref name=\"CBC_guilty-plea\">{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault, ex-Quebec lieutenant-governor, pleads guilty to 6 charges|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-ex-quebec-lieutenant-governor-pleads-guilty-to-6-charges-1.2864277|website=CBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=8 December 2014}}</ref> Judge Carol St-Cyr outlined her crimes, pointing out that she \"took advantage of holes in the system and abused her position of authority to pay for trips, golf lessons and birthday parties... [and] forgot that her role as lieutenant-governor was to be a good example for Quebecers.\"<ref name=sentence>{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault ordered to repay $300K, serve 18 months|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-sentencing-1.3249849|website=CBC|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2016, the Quebec Court of Appeal upheld Thibault's 18-month sentence,<ref name=\"CBC_appeal\">{{cite web|title=Lise Thibault's 18-month sentence challenge rejected by Quebec Court of Appeal|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-s-18-month-sentence-challenge-rejected-by-quebec-court-of-appeal-1.3461786|website=CBC News|accessdate=24 February 2016|date=24 February 2016}}</ref> and the next day Thibault surrendered at the Quebec City Detention Centre.<ref name=\"CTV-imprisoned\">{{cite web|title=Former Lt-Gov Thibault now in jail|url=http://montreal.ctvnews.ca/former-lt-gov-thibault-now-in-jail-1.2792448|website=CTV News|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"GLobe-Sentence-begun\">{{cite web|title=Ex-lieutenant-governor Lise Thibault begins prison sentence in Quebec City|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/ex-lieutenant-governor-lise-thibault-begins-prison-sentence-in-quebec-city/article28912036/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Star-begins-sentence\">{{cite web|title=Former Quebec lieutenant-governor Lise Thibault behind bars|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/02/25/former-quebec-lieutenant-governor-lise-thibault-behind-bars.html|website=The Toronto Star|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref> She was transferred in late February 2016 to the Leclerc Detention Centre in Laval, Quebec.<ref name=\"JDQ-transfer\">{{cite web|last1=Racine|first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|title=Lise Thibault a quitt\u00e9 Qu\u00e9bec|url=http://www.journaldequebec.com/2016/03/03/lise-thibault-a-quitte-quebec|website=Le Journal de Quebec|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TVA-transfer\">{{cite web|title=\u00c0 sa demande, Lise Thibault change de prison|url=http://www.tvanouvelles.ca/2016/03/03/exclusif--lise-thibault-change-de-prison|website=TVA Nouvelles|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> She was granted a conditional release on 2 June 2016, and was fully discharged on 17 August 2017. In the meantime, she filed for [[bankruptcy]] in June of that year, citing of debt of $1,5 millions to [[Canada Revenue Agency]] and [[Revenu Qu\u00e9bec]] (the initial $300,000 she was ordered to pay had already been reimbursed).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.journaldequebec.com/2017/06/17/lise-thibault-declare-faillite |title= Lise Thibault d\u00e9clare faillite|first= |last= |date=17 June 2017 |website=Le Journal de Qu\u00e9bec |publisher=|language = fr }}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours, and arms==\n\n{{Infobox viceroy styles\n| image    = \n| name     = Lise Thibault<br>(1997&ndash;2007)\n| dipstyle = {{unbulleted list | Her Honour the Honourable | ''Son Honneur l'honorable''}}\n| offstyle = {{unbulleted list | Your Honour | ''Votre Honneur''}}\n}}\n\n=== Titles ===\n* April 2, 1939 {{spaced ndash}}January 30, 1997: ''Ms./Madame'' Lise Thibault\n* January 30, 1997{{spaced ndash}}June 7, 2007: ''Her Honour the Honourable'' Lise Thibault, Lieutenant Governor of Quebec\n* June 7, 2007{{spaced ndash}}: ''The Honourable'' Lise Thibault\n\nAs a former [[Viceroy|viceregal]] representative of [[Elizabeth II]], as [[Monarchy in Quebec|Queen in Right of Quebec]], Thibault is styled ''The [[Honourable]]'' for life.<ref name=\"HEritage-styles\">{{cite web|title=Titles|url=http://canada.pch.gc.ca/eng/1452017684393|website=Canadian Heritage|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"GC-CA-Table-Of-Titles\">{{cite web|title=Table of Titles to be used in Canada|url=http://canada.pch.gc.ca/eng/1452187406810/1453733836056|website=Government of Canada|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite web|last1=Hicks|first1=Ryan|title=Lise Thibault should be stripped of pension, title: Democracy Watch|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lise-thibault-should-be-stripped-of-pension-title-democracy-watch-1.3300010|website=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n\nLise Thibault Has Received 3 Honorary Degrees\n\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Province/State</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Quebec}} || November 1999 || [[Concordia University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>http://archives.concordia.ca/degrees-chrono</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Quebec}} || 2 June 2001 || [[Bishop's University]] || [[Doctor of Civil Law]] (DCL)  <ref>http://www3.ubishops.ca/fileadmin/bishops_documents/alumni/files/newsletter/aug_2001.pdf</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Massachusetts}} || 2003 || [[Anna Maria College]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)\n|-\n|}\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = Lise Thibault Arms.svg\n|bannerimage =\n|badgeimage =\n|notes = The arms of Lise Thibault consist of:<ref>{{citation|title=Canadian Heraldic Authority (Volume III)\n|year=1999 |publisher=Ottawa}}</ref>\n|adopted =\n|crest = Upon a helmet mantled Azure doubled Argent within a wreath of these colours upon a grassy mound Vert an oak tree Argent fructed Azure.\n|torse =\n|helm =\n|escutcheon = Azure between two quills in chief and a treble clef in base a swallow volant Argent holding in the beak a Blue Flag Or.\n|supporters = Two does Azure and Argent gorged with maple leaves Or pendant therefrom a bezant the dexter one charged with two ears of wheat the sinister one with two sprigs of flax one bearing two flowers the other four all Azure.\n|compartment = A grassy mound Vert bearing lilies between two maple leaves Or.\n|motto = Cr\u00e9er La Vie\n|orders =\n|other_elements =\n|banner =\n|badge =\n|symbolism =\n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{QCLG}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thibault, Lise}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dames of Justice of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Women in Quebec politics]]\n[[Category:Canadian women viceroys]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of fraud]]\n[[Category:People from Lanaudi\u00e8re]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lise_Thibault"}
{"title_page": "H\u00e5kon Wium Lie", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Hakon Lie|the Norwegian politician|Haakon Lie}}\n{{short description|Norwegian software engineer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n| image              = H\u00e5kon-Wium-Lie-2009-03.jpg\n| caption            = H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, March 2009\n| birth_date         = July 16, 1965\n| birth_place        = [[Halden]], Norway\n| employer           = [[Opera Software]]\n| known_for          = [[Cascading Style Sheets]]\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| website            = [http://www.wiumlie.no/en Personal homepage of H\u00e5kon W. Lie]\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''H\u00e5kon Wium Lie''' (born July 16, 1965) is a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] web pioneer, a standards activist, and the [[Chief Technology Officer]] of [[Opera Software]] from 1998 until the browser was sold to new owners in 2016. He is best known for developing [[Cascading Style Sheets]] (CSS) while working with [[Tim Berners-Lee]] and [[Robert Cailliau]] at [[CERN]] in 1994.\n\n== Education and career ==\nH\u00e5kon Wium Lie attended [[\u00d8stfold University College]], [[University of West Georgia|West Georgia College]], and [[MIT Media Lab]], receiving an MS in Visual Studies in 1991.\n\nOn February 17, 2006, he successfully defended his [[PhD]] [[thesis]] at the [[University of Oslo]]. His [[PhD]] thesis is background to the origins of CSS and a rationale to some of the design decisions behind it &ndash; particularly as to why some features were ''not'' included and why CSS avoids trying to become [[DSSSL]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Disputas: Doktorand H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n |url=http://www.matnat.uio.no/tavle/disputas/2006/2006-0013.xml\n |archive-date=2006-02-23\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060223034541/https://www.matnat.uio.no/tavle/disputas/2006/2006-0013.xml\n |access-date=2019-05-20\n |url-status=live\n }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web \n |title=Phd. Thesis: Cascading Style Sheets\n |first=H\u00e5kon Wium\n |last=Lie\n |url=https://www.wiumlie.no/2006/phd/\n}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked for, among others, the [[W3C]], [[INRIA]], [[CERN]], [[MIT Media Lab]], and [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[Telecommunication|telecom]] research in [[Televerket (Norway)|Televerket]].\n\n=== Web Standards ===\n\nWhile working with [[Tim Berners-Lee]] and [[Robert Cailliau]] at [[CERN]] in 1994, he proposed the concept of [[Cascading Style Sheets]] (CSS).<ref>[https://www.w3.org/People/howcome/p/cascade.html Cascading HTML Style Sheets]</ref> As a showcase and [[testbed]], he integrated CSS into the [[Arena (web browser)|Arena]] [[web browser]], which became the first CSS implementation.<ref name=\"chapter20\">{{cite web\n|title=Chapter 20 - The CSS saga\n|url=http://www.w3.org/Style/LieBos2e/history/\n|publisher=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]\n|accessdate=23 June 2010\n|author=H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n|author2=Bert Bos \n|author2-link=Bert Bos\n}}</ref>\n \nAfter joining [[W3C]] in 1995, he worked on the CSS specifications, including CSS1,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-CSS1/\n|title=Cascading Style Sheets, level 1\n|work=World Wide Web Consortium\n|date=1996-12-17\n}}</ref> CSS2,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-CSS1/\n|title=Cascading Style Sheets, level 1\n|work=World Wide Web Consortium\n|date=1996-12-17\n}}</ref> and RFC 2318 (March 1998). Most of these specifications were developed with [[Bert Bos]], who is considered co-creator of CSS.<ref name=\"WWW3\">{{cite web|title=Simple style sheets for SGML & HTML on the web |url=http://www.w3.org/People/Bos/style.html|publisher=World Wide Web Consortium|accessdate=20 June 2010|authorlink=Bert Bos|first=Bert|last=Bos|date=14 April 1995}}</ref> Over the next decade, CSS established itself as one of the fundamental web standards, with profound impact on typography, aesthetics, and accessibility on the web.<ref>{{ cite news |work=Cnet.com \n|first=Stephen \n|last=Shankland \n|date=2010-11-08 \n|title=Browser underdog Opera fights for its survival\n|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/browser-underdog-opera-fights-for-survival/ \n|quote=And its chief technology officer, H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, worked with Web founder Tim Berners-Lee and founded the Web formatting technology called Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) that's now one of the hottest areas of Web design.\n}}</ref>\n\nAlong with his work on the CSS specifications, Wium Lie has been an activist for standards in general.\n\nIn 2005, he wrote an open letter to [[Bill Gates]] of [[Microsoft]], asking why Microsoft's [[Internet Explorer]] did not support common web standards.<ref>{{cite news \n |work=The Register\n |url=http://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/02/11/hakon_on_ms_interroperability/\n |date=2005-02-11\n |title=Opera to MS: Get real about interoperability, Mr Gates\n |quote=So, Mr. Gates, writes Hakon Lie, you say you believe in interoperability. Then why, pray tell, doesn't the web page of your interoperability communiqu\u00e9 conform to the HTML4 standard as it claims to?\n}}</ref> A few day later, when Bill Gates announced that [[Internet Explorer 7]] would be launched, Wium Lie responded by launching the [[Acid2]] challenge to Microsoft.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://news.cnet.com/The-Acid2-challenge-to-Microsoft/2010-1032_3-5618723.html \n |title=The Acid2 challenge to Microsoft \n |first=H\u00e5kon Wium \n |last=Lie \n |authorlink=H\u00e5kon Wium Lie \n |publisher=[[CNET]] \n |date=16 March 2005 \n |accessdate=12 January 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616125128/http://news.cnet.com/The-Acid2-challenge-to-Microsoft/2010-1032_3-5618723.html \n |archivedate=16 June 2011 \n |df=dmy \n |quote=To ensure that IE 7 does not become another failed promise, the Web community will issue a challenge to Microsoft. We will produce a test page, code-named Acid2, that will actively use features Web designers crave, such as fixed positioning of elements.\n}}</ref> Although primarily targeted at Microsoft, the Acid2 test was also difficult for other browsers. Since then, Acid2 and the subsequent [[Acid3]] have established themselves as benchmark tests which all browsers are measured against.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.webstandards.org/action/acid2/guide/\n|title=Acid2: The Guided Tour\n|publisher=The Web Standards Project\n|accessdate=24 December 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Wium Lie started campaigning for browsers to support downloadable web fonts using common font formats.<ref>[https://www.cnet.com/news/microsofts-forgotten-monopoly/ Microsoft's forgotten monopoly]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/2008/atypi/ |title=Web fonts: the view from the free world |access-date=2009-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723210909/http://people.opera.com/howcome/2008/atypi/ |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alistapart.com/articles/cssatten CSS @ Ten: The Next Big Thing]</ref> {{As of|2011}}, all major browser vendors have implemented web fonts this way.<ref>Samples at: [http://www.princexml.com/howcome/2008/webfonts/ ''Webfonts demo and test pages'']. for Prince, Safari, Opera 10 alpha, and a special build of Firefox. Retrieved 02-Aug-2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Wium Lie started campaigning for the video element to make it easier to publish video on the web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/2007/video/ |title=A call for video on the web |access-date=2009-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426030127/http://people.opera.com/howcome/2007/video/ |archive-date=2012-04-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At [[Google I/O]] in 2011, Wium Lie presented the video element in combination with the [[WebM]] format which [[Google]] had open-sourced.<ref>{{ cite news \n| work=The Register\n| first=Cade\n| last=Metz\n| title=Opera CTO still sour on Google native code plugin\n| url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/05/11/opera_cto_on_webp_webm_and_native_client/\n| quote=This morning, at Google I/O in downtown San Francisco, Wium Lie delivered a presentation on Opera's use of WebP, a new \"lossy\" image compression format open sourced by Google last fall. \n}}</ref><ref>[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=5545573096553082541 H\u00e5kon Wium Lie giving a Google Tech Talk on &lt;video&gt;]</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he was spokesperson for a group of technical committee members who resigned over the decision by [[Standards Norway]] to vote for the approval of [[OOXML]].<ref>{{ cite web \n|title=Norwegian standards body implodes over OOXML controversy\n|url=https://arstechnica.com/uncategorized/2008/10/norwegian-standards-body-implodes-over-ooxml-controversy/\n|quote=Opera CTO H\u00e5kon Wium Lie is among the technical committee members who are resigning over the OOXML decision. In the letter, he stresses the importance of open standards and the need for formats that are universally accessible to everyone.\n}}</ref>\n\nWium Lie has also promoted the concept of printing from the web.<ref>{{YouTube|vcXUrNSvjhU|H\u00e5kon Wium Lie and Michael Day giving a Google Tech Talk on printing from the web}}</ref> The third edition of his book on CSS, co-authored with [[Bert Bos]], was produced from HTML and CSS files.<ref>[http://www.alistapart.com/articles/boom Printing a Book with CSS: Boom!]</ref><ref>[http://www.princexml.com/samples/#book A description of how the CSS book was produced from HTML and CSS into PDF]</ref> These files were then converted to [[PDF]] by the [[Prince XML|Prince XML + CSS formatter]]. In 2005, he joined the board of YesLogic, the company that makes the Prince formatter.\n\nBuilding on his experience with web printing, in 2011 Wium Lie proposed to extend CSS to support pagination on screens.<ref>[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/10/12/opera_extends_css/ Opera brings fondleslab-style reading to bog-standard web]</ref>\n\nHe has argued against the use of [[XSL Formatting Objects|formatting objects]] and CSS Regions on the web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/1999/foch.html |title=Formatting Objects considered harmful |access-date=2009-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403232907/http://people.opera.com/howcome/1999/foch.html |archive-date=2011-04-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://alistapart.com/blog/post/css-regions-considered-harmful |title=CSS Regions Considered Harmful |access-date=2017-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525235404/https://alistapart.com/blog/post/css-regions-considered-harmful/ |archive-date=2019-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== CTO of Opera Software ===\n\nIn April 1999, Wium Lie joined [[Opera Software]] in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] as [[Chief technology officer|CTO]]. His move was motivated by seeing Opera programmers make more progress on implementing CSS in three months than what Netscape and Microsoft had achieved in three years.<ref>{{ cite news |\nwork=Computerworld |\ntitle=Why Opera isn't planning to go open source |\nfirst=Neil |\nlast=McAllister | url=http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/tech/982280C3DA7766DFCC257213007BC166 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061109113137/http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/tech/982280C3DA7766DFCC257213007BC166 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2006-11-09 |\ndate=2006-10-30 |\nquote=I joined Opera when I saw that Opera was able to implement as much of CSS in three months as Netscape and Microsoft could in three years\n}}</ref>\n\nAt Opera, he spearheaded the development of mobile browsers, in particular small-screen rendering of web pages. Small-screen rendering enabled Opera to show normal web pages on the small screens commonly found on [[feature phone]]s running the [[Opera Mini]] browser.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title=A quart into a pint pot\n| work=The Economist\n| date=2002-12-14\n| quote=Thank goodness, then, for Opera, a Norwegian software firm. It has devised a clever new way to squeeze grown-up web pages on to diminutive devices, such as smartphones, so that they both look good and are easy to navigate. The trick is to reformat the web page in an intelligent way\u2014by working out which parts are important and which not, says Hakon Lie, Opera's chief technology officer.\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen Opera Software filed a complaint against [[Microsoft]] in the [[EU]] over [[Internet Explorer]] in 2007, Wium Lie was a spokesperson, stressing the need for Microsoft to fully support web standards in their browser.<ref>{{ cite web\n|work=ZDNet\n|first=Larry\n|last=Dignan\n|title=Opera files complaint against Microsoft in the EU over IE, Windows bundle; CTO makes Web standards case\n|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/opera-files-complaint-against-microsoft-in-the-eu-over-ie-windows-bundle-cto-makes-web-standards-case/\n}}</ref> Opera's complaint led to a settlement where Microsoft started offering rival browsers from a [[BrowserChoice.eu|browser choice screen]] to Windows users in Europe, and Wium Lie declared this a victory for the web.<ref>{{ cite web \n|title=EC, Microsoft Settlement Broadly Welcomed\n|first=Paul\n|last=Meller\n|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/184851/article.html\n|quote=The legally binding commitments Microsoft made in the browser case mark \"a victory for the future of the Web and its users,\" Hakon Wium Lie, the chief technology officer at Opera said at a press conference.\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Opera started a gradual transition from its own [[Presto (browser engine)|Presto]] web engine, to the [[WebKit]] engine also used by [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]] and [[Google Chrome]]. Wium Lie said that it made most sense to work with the open-source communities than to continue developing its own engine.<ref>{{ cite web\n|title=Opera joins Google/Apple in-crowd with shift to WebKit and Chromium\n|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/02/13/webkit_sucks_on_webkit_chromium/\n|first=Gavin\n|last=Clarke\n|quote=Opera chief technology officer H\u00e5kon Wium Lie said in a statement: \"It makes more sense to have our experts working with the open source communities to further improve WebKit and Chromium, rather than developing our own rendering engine further.\u201d\n}}</ref>\n\n== Political and civic activities ==\n\nIn 2005, when politicians declared defeat against advertising towers on public pavements in [[Oslo]], Wium Lie started the [[Stans.no]] campaign.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Gir opp kampen mot gigareklame\n| trans-title = Gives up fight against giga-advertising\n| newspaper = KommunalRapport\n| first = Ole\n| last = Pedersen\n| location = Oslo\n| url = https://www.kommunal-rapport.no/artikkel/gir_opp_kampen_mot_gigareklame\n| date = 5 April 2005\n| quote = Leder av byutviklingskomiteen i Oslo, Ola Elvestuen (V), har gitt opp kampen mot reklamet\u00e5rene som firmaet JCDecaux skal sette opp i hovedstaden\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mobiliserer til reklamet\u00e5rn-protest\n| trans-title = Mobilizing protest agains advertising towers\n| newspaper = Kreativt Forum\n| last = Grenne\n| first = Harald\n| url = http://www.kreativtforum.no/sw11852.asp?newsID=2876\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051118181651/http://www.kreativtforum.no/sw11852.asp?newsID=2876\n| archive-date = 18 November 2005\n| date = 18 November 2005\n| quote = N\u00e5 maner grupperingen \u00abStans!\u00bb, best\u00e5ende av folk som beskriver seg selv som Oslo-entusiaster, til aksjon mot det reklamekj\u00f8ret mange Oslo-borgere n\u00e5 f\u00f8ler de f\u00e5r tredd nedover \u00f8rene. P\u00e5 nettsiden www.stans.no har de laget et opprop som folk kan skrive under, og i tillegg har de samlet all mulig relevant informasjon om den betente saken ... Gruppen er partipolitisk uavhengig og f\u00e5r ikke st\u00f8tte av kommersielle akt\u00f8rer. H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, som til daglig er Chief Technology Officer i landets mest offensive teknologibedrift, Opera Software, fungerer som kontaktperson.\n| access-date = 30 June 2019\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Tordner mot lyst\u00e5rn - H\u00e5kon Wium Lie er leder i stans.no og kjemper for \u00e5 fjerne reklamet\u00e5rn i Oslo.\n| trans-title = Thunders against advertising towers - H\u00e5kon wium Lie is the leader of stans.no and works to remove advertising towers from Oslo\n| url = https://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/navn-i-nyhetene/tordner-mot-lystarn-1.278254\n| last = Sandve\n| first = Gerd\n| date = 21 January 2014\n}}</ref> In 2009, Stans!no filed a suit against the city for allowing advertising towers to be built in public places, and the city subsequently bought the advertising towers and dismantled them.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Kostbare reklamet\u00e5rn\n| trans-title = Dear-bought advertising towers\n| newspaper = Aftenposten\n| location = Oslo\n| url = https://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/leder/i/dl3mA/Kostbare-reklametarn\n| date = 8 October 2009\n| quote = Mange naboer har protestert mot den politisk omstridte reklamen. Protestgruppen \u00abStans!no\u00bb varslet tidligere i \u00e5r s\u00f8ksm\u00e5l mot kommunen. N\u00e5 er leder av gruppen, H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, som fikk st\u00f8tte av flertallet i bystyret, lettet.\n}}</ref> After the advertising towers were removed, Stans.no has continued working against other types of advertising in the public space.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Her skal reklamen flomme\n| trans-title = Advertising will be flooding in these areas\n| newspaper = Aftenposten\n| location = Oslo\n| first = Bj\u00f8rn Egil\n| last = Halvorsen\n| url = http://www.aftenposten.no/osloby/i/y4X2r/Her-skal-reklamen-flomme\n| date = 9 March 2006\n| quote = Vi frykter dette vil f\u00f8re til st\u00f8rre og mer reklame, sier H\u00e5kon Wium Lie i stans!no. Aksjonsgruppen har markert seg som en kraftig opponent mot reklamet\u00e5rnene. Men selv om planforslaget frar\u00e5der flere slike t\u00e5rn og andre s\u00e5kalte reklamefinansierte gatem\u00f8bler, er ikke Wium Lie forn\u00f8yd. - Reklamen flytter n\u00e5 fra t\u00e5rn til vegg. Oslos innbyggere trenger en plan som er grunnleggende restriktiv til reklame.\n}}</ref>\n\nTo encourage sponsors to support the [[OLPC]] project, in 2008 he ordered 100 laptops and turned his Oslo home into a temporary OLPC village.<ref>{{ cite web\n|title=OLPC village in Oslo\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203023709/http://blog.abrenna.com/olpc-village-in-oslo/\n|archivedate=2009-02-03\n|url=http://blog.abrenna.com/olpc-village-in-oslo/\n|url-status=dead\n|first=Anders \n|last=Brenna\n}}</ref>\n<ref>{{ cite news\n|title=OLPC-landsby\n|url=https://www.digi.no/artikler/olpc-landsby/278752\n|first=Harald \n|last=Brombach\n|date=May 8, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 he co-founded the [[Pirate Party]] of Norway, and he ran as their candidate in the 2013 election and the 2019 election.<ref>{{ cite web\n|title=Valglistens navn: Piratpartiet\n|url=http://www.wiumlie.no/2019/pir/piratpartiet-oslo.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he proposed to use the two unused Norwegian [[Top-level domain|TLDs]] ([[.sj]] and [[.bv]]) to create privacy-enhanced zones.<ref>H\u00e5kon Wium Lie [https://www.opendemocracy.net/h%c3%a5kon-wium-lie/net-names-for-safe-shelter Net names for safe shelter], 31 July 2014, fetched Feb 25 2017</ref><ref>Stig \u00d8yvann [http://www.zdnet.com/article/how-two-remote-arctic-territories-became-the-front-line-in-the-battle-for-internet-privacy/ How two remote Arctic territories became the front line in the battle for internet privacy], 01 Oct 2014, fetched Feb 25 2017</ref>\n\nWium Lie is a self-declared [[Social democracy|social democrat]] and he has contributed economically to cultural and political causes. In 2007 he gave a significant contribution to the new [[Oslo Opera House]].<ref>{{ cite news\n| title=Ga kvart million til Operaen\n| quote=Vi er jo alle sosialdemokrater, og \u00f8nsker fortsette med det ... Jeg er ikke en superrik person. Noen bruker penger p\u00e5 dyre biler, men mitt store innkj\u00f8p i \u00e5r var en brukt elbil. Bare der sparte jeg nok en halv million\n| date=2007-11-23\n}}</ref> In 2017, he was an initial investor in the Norwegian online newspaper Resett stating it was meaningful to help provide a platform for Helge Lur\u00e5s, a critic of NATO campaigns in Afghanistan and Libya,  and [[Bj\u00f8rn Ihler]], a survivor of the [[Ut\u00f8ya massacre]].<ref>[http://www.digitalnewsreport.org/survey/2018/norway-2018/ Reuters Institute Digital News Report 2018]</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| last       = Lur\u00e5s\n| first      = Helge\n| last2      = Ulriksen\n| first2     = St\u00e5le\n| last3      = Valther\n| first3     = Vegard\n| date       = 2010\n| title      = The Strategic Significance of Afghanistan. A Note of Caution to the NATO Summit\n| url        = https://nupi.brage.unit.no/nupi-xmlui/handle/11250/194385\n| journal    = NUPI Policy Brief;\n| volume     = 9-2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Libya ble en rent sinnelagsetisk operasjon, som etterlot seg kaos \n| date = 29 September 2015\n| url = https://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/debatt/i/ay35/Libya-ble-en-rent-sinnelagsetisk-operasjon_-som-etterlot-seg-kaos--Helge-Luras\n| quote = Libya ble en rent sinnelagsetisk operasjon, som forutsigbart nok etterlot seg kaos. Noen av oss advarte mot dette da operasjonen tok til.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = A Norway massacre survivor explains how we need to pay more attention to the radicalization of white men\n| url = https://qz.com/1097212/bjorn-ihler-survivor-of-the-breivik-norway-massacre-on-how-we-need-to-tackle-the-radicalization-of-white-men/\n| date = 2017-10-07\n| quote = Should the world be concerned about the radicalization of white men? \u201cYes,\u201d says Bj\u00f8rn Ihler, \u201cI almost got killed by one.\u201d\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title=\u00d8nsker konfrontasjon med St\u00f8re og Solberg\n| date = 2017-08-24\n| url = https://www.dn.no/onsker-konfrontasjon-med-store-og-solberg/2-1-150952?_l\n| quote = Jeg synes det er meningfylt \u00e5 bidra til at nye stemmer som Helge Lur\u00e5s og Bj\u00f8rn Ihler f\u00e5r en plattform. Jeg har ingen rolle i redaksjonen, men jeg synes det Helge sier om trusselvurderingen av Russland virker fornuftig. Jeg synes ofte at norske medier demoniserer et naboland vi burde kunne ha gode relasjoner til, sier H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n}}</ref>\n\nWium Lie is against Norwegian membership in the EEA and when the party Alliansen was formed as an anti-[[European Economic Area|EEA]] party in 2017 he was on the election list for parliament for [[Akershus]].<ref>[https://www.abcnyheter.no/nyheter/politikk/2016/11/22/195258429/nytt-politisk-parti-vil-ha-norge-ut-av-eos Nytt politisk parti vil ha Norge ut av E\u00d8S]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/data/parti/stortingfylkestingsvalg/ |title=NSDs valglistearkiv |access-date=2019-04-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013070139/http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/data/parti/stortingfylkestingsvalg/ |archive-date=2018-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, Wium Lie denounced the party before the election due to its shifting platform.<ref>{{Kilde www|url=https://www.dn.no/magasinet/politikk/helge-luras/mikkel-dobloug/fremskrittspartiet/historien-om-milliardarenes-nye-nettavis/2-1-156204|tittel=Historien om milliard\u00e6renes nye nettavis|bes\u00f8ksdato=2019-04-23|dato=2017-09-01|spr\u00e5k=no-NB|sitat=Det m\u00e5 her skytes inn at H\u00e5kon Wium Lie ikke lenger vil la seg assosiere med partiet. I en epost skriver han: Jeg tror det hadde v\u00e6rt fint \u00e5 f\u00e5 en gr\u00fcnder p\u00e5 Stortinget, og det er slik jeg kjenner Hans J\u00f8rgen. At han til og med startet et firma som tilbyr sikker epost, er et ekstra pluss. Alliansens fanesak var kampen mot E\u00d8S-avtalen, som er et \u00e5k for Norge, og jeg sa derfor ja til \u00e5 bli listef\u00f8rt. S\u00e5 ser jeg ogs\u00e5 at valgkampen handler om andre temaer enn E\u00d8S, og jeg har m\u00e5ttet distansere meg fra uttalelser. Det er leit, og jeg regner meg ikke som kandidat, selv om jeg fortsatt st\u00e5r p\u00e5 listene.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Wium Lie was sued by [[Lovdata]] for publishing Norwegian court decisions on [[rettspraksis.no]], a volunteer web site. In less than 24 hours, the web site was closed by the Oslo court, and Wium Lie was sentenced to pay the legal bills of Lovdata. Under Norwegian law, court decisions are exempted from copyright but Wium Lie was not allowed to appear in court. In the wake of this decision, members of the Norwegian Parliament have asked for changes in how Lovdata is organized.<ref>[http://www.wiumlie.no/2018/rettspraksis/06-11-blog.html Being Sued]</ref> The case has been appealed and will be decided by the Supreme Court of Norway.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nWium Lie lives in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]. There, he has started web-based campaigns against high-rise buildings<ref>[http://www.stoppblokk.no StoppBlokk campaign]</ref> and advertising in the public space.<ref>[http://www.stans.no Stans!no campaign] against advertising in Oslo</ref> Wium Lie also maintains a [[woodworking]] studio and runs an [[organic farm]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://hakon.wium.lie.usesthis.com/ |title=H\u00e5kon Wium Le |work=The Setup |date=October 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n\nIn 1999, he was named to the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] [[Technology Review]] [[TR35|TR100]] as one of the top 100 innovators in the world under the age of 35.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.technologyreview.com/tr35/?year=1999 |title=1999 Young Innovators Under 35 |publisher=[[Technology Review]] | year=1999 | accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, he was a Technology Pioneer at the World Economic Forum in Davos.\n\nIn 2017, Wium Lie held a keynote at the WeAreDevelopers Conference 2017, talking about his contributions to the web today with the creation of CSS, and how it has evolved together with the web itself up to its current state.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LeC26IO1WV8</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arena (web browser)|Arena]] with the integrated [[Libwww]] by Lie.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nielsen|first=Henrik Frystyk|title=Libwww Hackers|url=http://www.w3.org/Library/Collaborators.html|publisher=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]|accessdate=2 June 2010|date=7 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nLie and [[Bert Bos]] wrote a book on CSS, now in its third edition.\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: Designing for the Web\n  |edition=1st\n  |isbn=0-201-41998-X\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/cascadingstylesh00lieh\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: Designing for the Web\n  |edition=2nd\n  |isbn=0-201-59625-3\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/cascadingstyles000lieh\n  |last1=Lie\n |first1=H\u00e5kon Wium\n |last2=Bos\n |first2=Bert\n |year=1999\n }}\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: Designing for the Web\n  |edition=3rd\n  |isbn=0-321-19312-1\n|last1=Lie\n |first1=H\u00e5kon Wium\n |last2=Bos\n |first2=Bert\n |year=2005\n }}\n\n* {{cite web\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: PhD thesis\n  |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/2006/phd/\n  |last=Lie\n  |first=H\u00e5kon Wium\n  |date=February 17, 2006\n  |issn=1501-7710\n  |publisher=University of Oslo\n  |location=Oslo, Norway\n  |access-date=May 1, 2006\n  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004215348/http://people.opera.com/howcome/2006/phd/\n  |archive-date=October 4, 2014\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.wiumlie.no/en Personal homepage of H\u00e5kon W. Lie]\n*[http://www.w3.org/People/howcome/ Old homepage at W3C]\n*[http://www.w3.org/People/howcome/p/cascade.html The initial CSS proposal]\n*[http://www.princexml.com Prince XML - (supports creation of PDF with CSS and webfonts)]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2395359,00.asp Interview with H\u00e5kon Wium Lie]\n\n{{OperaBrowser}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lie, H\u00e5kon Wium}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian engineers]]\n[[Category:People associated with CERN]]\n[[Category:Opera Software employees]]\n[[Category:Web developers]]\n[[Category:Computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian computer scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Halden]]\n[[Category:Chief technology officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Hakon Lie|the Norwegian politician|Haakon Lie}}\n{{short description|Norwegian software engineer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n| image       = H\u00e5kon-Wium-Lie-2009-03.jpg\n| caption     = H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, March 2009\n| birth_place = [[Halden]], Norway\n| employer  = [[Opera Software]]\n| known_for   = [[Cascading Style Sheets]]\n| spouse      =\n| children    = \n| website     = [http://www.wiumlie.no/en Personal homepage of H\u00e5kon W. Lie]\n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''H\u00e5kon Wium Lie''' (born July 16, 1965) is a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] web pioneer, a standards activist, and the [[Chief Technology Officer]] of [[Opera Software]] from 1998 until the browser was sold to new owners in 2016. He is best known for developing [[Cascading Style Sheets]] (CSS) while working with [[Tim Berners-Lee]] and [[Robert Cailliau]] at [[CERN]] in 1994.\n\n== Education and career ==\nH\u00e5kon Wium Lie attended [[\u00d8stfold University College]], [[University of West Georgia|West Georgia College]], and [[MIT Media Lab]], receiving an MS in Visual Studies in 1991.\n\nOn February 17, 2006, he successfully defended his [[PhD]] [[thesis]] at the [[University of Oslo]]. His [[PhD]] thesis is background to the origins of CSS and a rationale to some of the design decisions behind it &ndash; particularly as to why some features were ''not'' included and why CSS avoids trying to become [[DSSSL]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Disputas: Doktorand H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n |url=http://www.matnat.uio.no/tavle/disputas/2006/2006-0013.xml\n |archive-date=2006-02-23\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060223034541/https://www.matnat.uio.no/tavle/disputas/2006/2006-0013.xml\n |access-date=2019-05-20\n |url-status=live\n }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web \n |title=Phd. Thesis: Cascading Style Sheets\n |first=H\u00e5kon Wium\n |last=Lie\n |url=https://www.wiumlie.no/2006/phd/\n}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked for, among others, the [[W3C]], [[INRIA]], [[CERN]], [[MIT Media Lab]], and [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[Telecommunication|telecom]] research in [[Televerket (Norway)|Televerket]].\n\n=== Web Standards ===\n\nWhile working with [[Tim Berners-Lee]] and [[Robert Cailliau]] at [[CERN]] in 1994, he proposed the concept of [[Cascading Style Sheets]] (CSS).<ref>[https://www.w3.org/People/howcome/p/cascade.html Cascading HTML Style Sheets]</ref> As a showcase and [[testbed]], he integrated CSS into the [[Arena (web browser)|Arena]] [[web browser]], which became the first CSS implementation.<ref name=\"chapter20\">{{cite web\n|title=Chapter 20 - The CSS saga\n|url=http://www.w3.org/Style/LieBos2e/history/\n|publisher=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]\n|accessdate=23 June 2010\n|author=H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n|author2=Bert Bos \n|author2-link=Bert Bos\n}}</ref>\n \nAfter joining [[W3C]] in 1995, he worked on the CSS specifications, including CSS1,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-CSS1/\n|title=Cascading Style Sheets, level 1\n|work=World Wide Web Consortium\n|date=1996-12-17\n}}</ref> CSS2,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-CSS1/\n|title=Cascading Style Sheets, level 1\n|work=World Wide Web Consortium\n|date=1996-12-17\n}}</ref> and RFC 2318 (March 1998). Most of these specifications were developed with [[Bert Bos]], who is considered co-creator of CSS.<ref name=\"WWW3\">{{cite web|title=Simple style sheets for SGML & HTML on the web |url=http://www.w3.org/People/Bos/style.html|publisher=World Wide Web Consortium|accessdate=20 June 2010|authorlink=Bert Bos|first=Bert|last=Bos|date=14 April 1995}}</ref> Over the next decade, CSS established itself as one of the fundamental web standards, with profound impact on typography, aesthetics, and accessibility on the web.<ref>{{ cite news |work=Cnet.com \n|first=Stephen \n|last=Shankland \n|date=2010-11-08 \n|title=Browser underdog Opera fights for its survival\n|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/browser-underdog-opera-fights-for-survival/ \n|quote=And its chief technology officer, H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, worked with Web founder Tim Berners-Lee and founded the Web formatting technology called Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) that's now one of the hottest areas of Web design.\n}}</ref>\n\nAlong with his work on the CSS specifications, Wium Lie has been an activist for standards in general.\n\nIn 2005, he wrote an open letter to [[Bill Gates]] of [[Microsoft]], asking why Microsoft's [[Internet Explorer]] did not support common web standards.<ref>{{cite news \n |work=The Register\n |url=http://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/02/11/hakon_on_ms_interroperability/\n |date=2005-02-11\n |title=Opera to MS: Get real about interoperability, Mr Gates\n |quote=So, Mr. Gates, writes Hakon Lie, you say you believe in interoperability. Then why, pray tell, doesn't the web page of your interoperability communiqu\u00e9 conform to the HTML4 standard as it claims to?\n}}</ref> A few day later, when Bill Gates announced that [[Internet Explorer 7]] would be launched, Wium Lie responded by launching the [[Acid2]] challenge to Microsoft.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://news.cnet.com/The-Acid2-challenge-to-Microsoft/2010-1032_3-5618723.html \n |title=The Acid2 challenge to Microsoft \n |first=H\u00e5kon Wium \n |last=Lie \n |authorlink=H\u00e5kon Wium Lie \n |publisher=[[CNET]] \n |date=16 March 2005 \n |accessdate=12 January 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616125128/http://news.cnet.com/The-Acid2-challenge-to-Microsoft/2010-1032_3-5618723.html \n |archivedate=16 June 2011 \n |df=dmy \n |quote=To ensure that IE 7 does not become another failed promise, the Web community will issue a challenge to Microsoft. We will produce a test page, code-named Acid2, that will actively use features Web designers crave, such as fixed positioning of elements.\n}}</ref> Although primarily targeted at Microsoft, the Acid2 test was also difficult for other browsers. Since then, Acid2 and the subsequent [[Acid3]] have established themselves as benchmark tests which all browsers are measured against.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.webstandards.org/action/acid2/guide/\n|title=Acid2: The Guided Tour\n|publisher=The Web Standards Project\n|accessdate=24 December 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Wium Lie started campaigning for browsers to support downloadable web fonts using common font formats.<ref>[https://www.cnet.com/news/microsofts-forgotten-monopoly/ Microsoft's forgotten monopoly]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/2008/atypi/ |title=Web fonts: the view from the free world |access-date=2009-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723210909/http://people.opera.com/howcome/2008/atypi/ |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alistapart.com/articles/cssatten CSS @ Ten: The Next Big Thing]</ref> {{As of|2011}}, all major browser vendors have implemented web fonts this way.<ref>Samples at: [http://www.princexml.com/howcome/2008/webfonts/ ''Webfonts demo and test pages'']. for Prince, Safari, Opera 10 alpha, and a special build of Firefox. Retrieved 02-Aug-2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Wium Lie started campaigning for the video element to make it easier to publish video on the web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/2007/video/ |title=A call for video on the web |access-date=2009-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426030127/http://people.opera.com/howcome/2007/video/ |archive-date=2012-04-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At [[Google I/O]] in 2011, Wium Lie presented the video element in combination with the [[WebM]] format which [[Google]] had open-sourced.<ref>{{ cite news \n| work=The Register\n| first=Cade\n| last=Metz\n| title=Opera CTO still sour on Google native code plugin\n| url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/05/11/opera_cto_on_webp_webm_and_native_client/\n| quote=This morning, at Google I/O in downtown San Francisco, Wium Lie delivered a presentation on Opera's use of WebP, a new \"lossy\" image compression format open sourced by Google last fall. \n}}</ref><ref>[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=5545573096553082541 H\u00e5kon Wium Lie giving a Google Tech Talk on &lt;video&gt;]</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he was spokesperson for a group of technical committee members who resigned over the decision by [[Standards Norway]] to vote for the approval of [[OOXML]].<ref>{{ cite web \n|title=Norwegian standards body implodes over OOXML controversy\n|url=https://arstechnica.com/uncategorized/2008/10/norwegian-standards-body-implodes-over-ooxml-controversy/\n|quote=Opera CTO H\u00e5kon Wium Lie is among the technical committee members who are resigning over the OOXML decision. In the letter, he stresses the importance of open standards and the need for formats that are universally accessible to everyone.\n}}</ref>\n\nWium Lie has also promoted the concept of printing from the web.<ref>{{YouTube|vcXUrNSvjhU|H\u00e5kon Wium Lie and Michael Day giving a Google Tech Talk on printing from the web}}</ref> The third edition of his book on CSS, co-authored with [[Bert Bos]], was produced from HTML and CSS files.<ref>[http://www.alistapart.com/articles/boom Printing a Book with CSS: Boom!]</ref><ref>[http://www.princexml.com/samples/#book A description of how the CSS book was produced from HTML and CSS into PDF]</ref> These files were then converted to [[PDF]] by the [[Prince XML|Prince XML + CSS formatter]]. In 2005, he joined the board of YesLogic, the company that makes the Prince formatter.\n\nBuilding on his experience with web printing, in 2011 Wium Lie proposed to extend CSS to support pagination on screens.<ref>[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/10/12/opera_extends_css/ Opera brings fondleslab-style reading to bog-standard web]</ref>\n\nHe has argued against the use of [[XSL Formatting Objects|formatting objects]] and CSS Regions on the web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/1999/foch.html |title=Formatting Objects considered harmful |access-date=2009-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403232907/http://people.opera.com/howcome/1999/foch.html |archive-date=2011-04-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://alistapart.com/blog/post/css-regions-considered-harmful |title=CSS Regions Considered Harmful |access-date=2017-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525235404/https://alistapart.com/blog/post/css-regions-considered-harmful/ |archive-date=2019-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== CTO of Opera Software ===\n\nIn April 1999, Wium Lie joined [[Opera Software]] in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] as [[Chief technology officer|CTO]]. His move was motivated by seeing Opera programmers make more progress on implementing CSS in three months than what Netscape and Microsoft had achieved in three years.<ref>{{ cite news |\nwork=Computerworld |\ntitle=Why Opera isn't planning to go open source |\nfirst=Neil |\nlast=McAllister | url=http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/tech/982280C3DA7766DFCC257213007BC166 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061109113137/http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/tech/982280C3DA7766DFCC257213007BC166 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2006-11-09 |\ndate=2006-10-30 |\nquote=I joined Opera when I saw that Opera was able to implement as much of CSS in three months as Netscape and Microsoft could in three years\n}}</ref>\n\nAt Opera, he spearheaded the development of mobile browsers, in particular small-screen rendering of web pages. Small-screen rendering enabled Opera to show normal web pages on the small screens commonly found on [[feature phone]]s running the [[Opera Mini]] browser.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title=A quart into a pint pot\n| work=The Economist\n| date=2002-12-14\n| quote=Thank goodness, then, for Opera, a Norwegian software firm. It has devised a clever new way to squeeze grown-up web pages on to diminutive devices, such as smartphones, so that they both look good and are easy to navigate. The trick is to reformat the web page in an intelligent way\u2014by working out which parts are important and which not, says Hakon Lie, Opera's chief technology officer.\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen Opera Software filed a complaint against [[Microsoft]] in the [[EU]] over [[Internet Explorer]] in 2007, Wium Lie was a spokesperson, stressing the need for Microsoft to fully support web standards in their browser.<ref>{{ cite web\n|work=ZDNet\n|first=Larry\n|last=Dignan\n|title=Opera files complaint against Microsoft in the EU over IE, Windows bundle; CTO makes Web standards case\n|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/opera-files-complaint-against-microsoft-in-the-eu-over-ie-windows-bundle-cto-makes-web-standards-case/\n}}</ref> Opera's complaint led to a settlement where Microsoft started offering rival browsers from a [[BrowserChoice.eu|browser choice screen]] to Windows users in Europe, and Wium Lie declared this a victory for the web.<ref>{{ cite web \n|title=EC, Microsoft Settlement Broadly Welcomed\n|first=Paul\n|last=Meller\n|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/184851/article.html\n|quote=The legally binding commitments Microsoft made in the browser case mark \"a victory for the future of the Web and its users,\" Hakon Wium Lie, the chief technology officer at Opera said at a press conference.\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Opera started a gradual transition from its own [[Presto (browser engine)|Presto]] web engine, to the [[WebKit]] engine also used by [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]] and [[Google Chrome]]. Wium Lie said that it made most sense to work with the open-source communities than to continue developing its own engine.<ref>{{ cite web\n|title=Opera joins Google/Apple in-crowd with shift to WebKit and Chromium\n|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/02/13/webkit_sucks_on_webkit_chromium/\n|first=Gavin\n|last=Clarke\n|quote=Opera chief technology officer H\u00e5kon Wium Lie said in a statement: \"It makes more sense to have our experts working with the open source communities to further improve WebKit and Chromium, rather than developing our own rendering engine further.\u201d\n}}</ref>\n\n== Political and civic activities ==\n\nIn 2005, when politicians declared defeat against advertising towers on public pavements in [[Oslo]], Wium Lie started the [[Stans.no]] campaign.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Gir opp kampen mot gigareklame\n| trans-title = Gives up fight against giga-advertising\n| newspaper = KommunalRapport\n| first = Ole\n| last = Pedersen\n| location = Oslo\n| url = https://www.kommunal-rapport.no/artikkel/gir_opp_kampen_mot_gigareklame\n| date = 5 April 2005\n| quote = Leder av byutviklingskomiteen i Oslo, Ola Elvestuen (V), har gitt opp kampen mot reklamet\u00e5rene som firmaet JCDecaux skal sette opp i hovedstaden\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mobiliserer til reklamet\u00e5rn-protest\n| trans-title = Mobilizing protest agains advertising towers\n| newspaper = Kreativt Forum\n| last = Grenne\n| first = Harald\n| url = http://www.kreativtforum.no/sw11852.asp?newsID=2876\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051118181651/http://www.kreativtforum.no/sw11852.asp?newsID=2876\n| archive-date = 18 November 2005\n| date = 18 November 2005\n| quote = N\u00e5 maner grupperingen \u00abStans!\u00bb, best\u00e5ende av folk som beskriver seg selv som Oslo-entusiaster, til aksjon mot det reklamekj\u00f8ret mange Oslo-borgere n\u00e5 f\u00f8ler de f\u00e5r tredd nedover \u00f8rene. P\u00e5 nettsiden www.stans.no har de laget et opprop som folk kan skrive under, og i tillegg har de samlet all mulig relevant informasjon om den betente saken ... Gruppen er partipolitisk uavhengig og f\u00e5r ikke st\u00f8tte av kommersielle akt\u00f8rer. H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, som til daglig er Chief Technology Officer i landets mest offensive teknologibedrift, Opera Software, fungerer som kontaktperson.\n| access-date = 30 June 2019\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Tordner mot lyst\u00e5rn - H\u00e5kon Wium Lie er leder i stans.no og kjemper for \u00e5 fjerne reklamet\u00e5rn i Oslo.\n| trans-title = Thunders against advertising towers - H\u00e5kon wium Lie is the leader of stans.no and works to remove advertising towers from Oslo\n| url = https://www.dagsavisen.no/innenriks/navn-i-nyhetene/tordner-mot-lystarn-1.278254\n| last = Sandve\n| first = Gerd\n| date = 21 January 2014\n}}</ref> In 2009, Stans!no filed a suit against the city for allowing advertising towers to be built in public places, and the city subsequently bought the advertising towers and dismantled them.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Kostbare reklamet\u00e5rn\n| trans-title = Dear-bought advertising towers\n| newspaper = Aftenposten\n| location = Oslo\n| url = https://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/leder/i/dl3mA/Kostbare-reklametarn\n| date = 8 October 2009\n| quote = Mange naboer har protestert mot den politisk omstridte reklamen. Protestgruppen \u00abStans!no\u00bb varslet tidligere i \u00e5r s\u00f8ksm\u00e5l mot kommunen. N\u00e5 er leder av gruppen, H\u00e5kon Wium Lie, som fikk st\u00f8tte av flertallet i bystyret, lettet.\n}}</ref> After the advertising towers were removed, Stans.no has continued working against other types of advertising in the public space.<ref>{{ cite news\n| title = Her skal reklamen flomme\n| trans-title = Advertising will be flooding in these areas\n| newspaper = Aftenposten\n| location = Oslo\n| first = Bj\u00f8rn Egil\n| last = Halvorsen\n| url = http://www.aftenposten.no/osloby/i/y4X2r/Her-skal-reklamen-flomme\n| date = 9 March 2006\n| quote = Vi frykter dette vil f\u00f8re til st\u00f8rre og mer reklame, sier H\u00e5kon Wium Lie i stans!no. Aksjonsgruppen har markert seg som en kraftig opponent mot reklamet\u00e5rnene. Men selv om planforslaget frar\u00e5der flere slike t\u00e5rn og andre s\u00e5kalte reklamefinansierte gatem\u00f8bler, er ikke Wium Lie forn\u00f8yd. - Reklamen flytter n\u00e5 fra t\u00e5rn til vegg. Oslos innbyggere trenger en plan som er grunnleggende restriktiv til reklame.\n}}</ref>\n\nTo encourage sponsors to support the [[OLPC]] project, in 2008 he ordered 100 laptops and turned his Oslo home into a temporary OLPC village.<ref>{{ cite web\n|title=OLPC village in Oslo\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203023709/http://blog.abrenna.com/olpc-village-in-oslo/\n|archivedate=2009-02-03\n|url=http://blog.abrenna.com/olpc-village-in-oslo/\n|url-status=dead\n|first=Anders \n|last=Brenna\n}}</ref>\n<ref>{{ cite news\n|title=OLPC-landsby\n|url=https://www.digi.no/artikler/olpc-landsby/278752\n|first=Harald \n|last=Brombach\n|date=May 8, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 he co-founded the [[Pirate Party]] of Norway, and he ran as their candidate in the 2013 election and the 2019 election.<ref>{{ cite web\n|title=Valglistens navn: Piratpartiet\n|url=http://www.wiumlie.no/2019/pir/piratpartiet-oslo.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he proposed to use the two unused Norwegian [[Top-level domain|TLDs]] ([[.sj]] and [[.bv]]) to create privacy-enhanced zones.<ref>H\u00e5kon Wium Lie [https://www.opendemocracy.net/h%c3%a5kon-wium-lie/net-names-for-safe-shelter Net names for safe shelter], 31 July 2014, fetched Feb 25 2017</ref><ref>Stig \u00d8yvann [http://www.zdnet.com/article/how-two-remote-arctic-territories-became-the-front-line-in-the-battle-for-internet-privacy/ How two remote Arctic territories became the front line in the battle for internet privacy], 01 Oct 2014, fetched Feb 25 2017</ref>\n\nWium Lie is a self-declared [[Social democracy|social democrat]] and he has contributed economically to cultural and political causes. In 2007 he gave a significant contribution to the new [[Oslo Opera House]].<ref>{{ cite news\n| title=Ga kvart million til Operaen\n| quote=Vi er jo alle sosialdemokrater, og \u00f8nsker fortsette med det ... Jeg er ikke en superrik person. Noen bruker penger p\u00e5 dyre biler, men mitt store innkj\u00f8p i \u00e5r var en brukt elbil. Bare der sparte jeg nok en halv million\n| date=2007-11-23\n}}</ref> In 2017, he was an initial investor in the Norwegian online newspaper Resett stating it was meaningful to help provide a platform for Helge Lur\u00e5s, a critic of NATO campaigns in Afghanistan and Libya,  and [[Bj\u00f8rn Ihler]], a survivor of the [[Ut\u00f8ya massacre]].<ref>[http://www.digitalnewsreport.org/survey/2018/norway-2018/ Reuters Institute Digital News Report 2018]</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| last       = Lur\u00e5s\n| first      = Helge\n| last2      = Ulriksen\n| first2     = St\u00e5le\n| last3      = Valther\n| first3     = Vegard\n| date       = 2010\n| title      = The Strategic Significance of Afghanistan. A Note of Caution to the NATO Summit\n| url        = https://nupi.brage.unit.no/nupi-xmlui/handle/11250/194385\n| journal    = NUPI Policy Brief;\n| volume     = 9-2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Libya ble en rent sinnelagsetisk operasjon, som etterlot seg kaos \n| date = 29 September 2015\n| url = https://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/debatt/i/ay35/Libya-ble-en-rent-sinnelagsetisk-operasjon_-som-etterlot-seg-kaos--Helge-Luras\n| quote = Libya ble en rent sinnelagsetisk operasjon, som forutsigbart nok etterlot seg kaos. Noen av oss advarte mot dette da operasjonen tok til.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = A Norway massacre survivor explains how we need to pay more attention to the radicalization of white men\n| url = https://qz.com/1097212/bjorn-ihler-survivor-of-the-breivik-norway-massacre-on-how-we-need-to-tackle-the-radicalization-of-white-men/\n| date = 2017-10-07\n| quote = Should the world be concerned about the radicalization of white men? \u201cYes,\u201d says Bj\u00f8rn Ihler, \u201cI almost got killed by one.\u201d\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title=\u00d8nsker konfrontasjon med St\u00f8re og Solberg\n| date = 2017-08-24\n| url = https://www.dn.no/onsker-konfrontasjon-med-store-og-solberg/2-1-150952?_l\n| quote = Jeg synes det er meningfylt \u00e5 bidra til at nye stemmer som Helge Lur\u00e5s og Bj\u00f8rn Ihler f\u00e5r en plattform. Jeg har ingen rolle i redaksjonen, men jeg synes det Helge sier om trusselvurderingen av Russland virker fornuftig. Jeg synes ofte at norske medier demoniserer et naboland vi burde kunne ha gode relasjoner til, sier H\u00e5kon Wium Lie\n}}</ref>\n\nWium Lie is against Norwegian membership in the EEA and when the party Alliansen was formed as an anti-[[European Economic Area|EEA]] party in 2017 he was on the election list for parliament for [[Akershus]].<ref>[https://www.abcnyheter.no/nyheter/politikk/2016/11/22/195258429/nytt-politisk-parti-vil-ha-norge-ut-av-eos Nytt politisk parti vil ha Norge ut av E\u00d8S]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/data/parti/stortingfylkestingsvalg/ |title=NSDs valglistearkiv |access-date=2019-04-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013070139/http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/data/parti/stortingfylkestingsvalg/ |archive-date=2018-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, Wium Lie denounced the party before the election due to its shifting platform.<ref>{{Kilde www|url=https://www.dn.no/magasinet/politikk/helge-luras/mikkel-dobloug/fremskrittspartiet/historien-om-milliardarenes-nye-nettavis/2-1-156204|tittel=Historien om milliard\u00e6renes nye nettavis|bes\u00f8ksdato=2019-04-23|dato=2017-09-01|spr\u00e5k=no-NB|sitat=Det m\u00e5 her skytes inn at H\u00e5kon Wium Lie ikke lenger vil la seg assosiere med partiet. I en epost skriver han: Jeg tror det hadde v\u00e6rt fint \u00e5 f\u00e5 en gr\u00fcnder p\u00e5 Stortinget, og det er slik jeg kjenner Hans J\u00f8rgen. At han til og med startet et firma som tilbyr sikker epost, er et ekstra pluss. Alliansens fanesak var kampen mot E\u00d8S-avtalen, som er et \u00e5k for Norge, og jeg sa derfor ja til \u00e5 bli listef\u00f8rt. S\u00e5 ser jeg ogs\u00e5 at valgkampen handler om andre temaer enn E\u00d8S, og jeg har m\u00e5ttet distansere meg fra uttalelser. Det er leit, og jeg regner meg ikke som kandidat, selv om jeg fortsatt st\u00e5r p\u00e5 listene.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Wium Lie was sued by [[Lovdata]] for publishing Norwegian court decisions on [[rettspraksis.no]], a volunteer web site. In less than 24 hours, the web site was closed by the Oslo court, and Wium Lie was sentenced to pay the legal bills of Lovdata. Under Norwegian law, court decisions are exempted from copyright but Wium Lie was not allowed to appear in court. In the wake of this decision, members of the Norwegian Parliament have asked for changes in how Lovdata is organized.<ref>[http://www.wiumlie.no/2018/rettspraksis/06-11-blog.html Being Sued]</ref> The case has been appealed and will be decided by the Supreme Court of Norway.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nWium Lie lives in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]. There, he has started web-based campaigns against high-rise buildings<ref>[http://www.stoppblokk.no StoppBlokk campaign]</ref> and advertising in the public space.<ref>[http://www.stans.no Stans!no campaign] against advertising in Oslo</ref> Wium Lie also maintains a [[woodworking]] studio and runs an [[organic farm]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://hakon.wium.lie.usesthis.com/ |title=H\u00e5kon Wium Le |work=The Setup |date=October 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n\nIn 1999, he was named to the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] [[Technology Review]] [[TR35|TR100]] as one of the top 100 innovators in the world under the age of 35.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.technologyreview.com/tr35/?year=1999 |title=1999 Young Innovators Under 35 |publisher=[[Technology Review]] | year=1999 | accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, he was a Technology Pioneer at the World Economic Forum in Davos.\n\nIn 2017, Wium Lie held a keynote at the WeAreDevelopers Conference 2017, talking about his contributions to the web today with the creation of CSS, and how it has evolved together with the web itself up to its current state.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LeC26IO1WV8</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arena (web browser)|Arena]] with the integrated [[Libwww]] by Lie.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nielsen|first=Henrik Frystyk|title=Libwww Hackers|url=http://www.w3.org/Library/Collaborators.html|publisher=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]|accessdate=2 June 2010|date=7 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nLie and [[Bert Bos]] wrote a book on CSS, now in its third edition.\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: Designing for the Web\n  |edition=1st\n  |isbn=0-201-41998-X\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/cascadingstylesh00lieh\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: Designing for the Web\n  |edition=2nd\n  |isbn=0-201-59625-3\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/cascadingstyles000lieh\n  |last1=Lie\n |first1=H\u00e5kon Wium\n |last2=Bos\n |first2=Bert\n |year=1999\n }}\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: Designing for the Web\n  |edition=3rd\n  |isbn=0-321-19312-1\n|last1=Lie\n |first1=H\u00e5kon Wium\n |last2=Bos\n |first2=Bert\n |year=2005\n }}\n\n* {{cite web\n  |title=Cascading Style Sheets: PhD thesis\n  |url=http://people.opera.com/howcome/2006/phd/\n  |last=Lie\n  |first=H\u00e5kon Wium\n  |date=February 17, 2006\n  |issn=1501-7710\n  |publisher=University of Oslo\n  |location=Oslo, Norway\n  |access-date=May 1, 2006\n  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004215348/http://people.opera.com/howcome/2006/phd/\n  |archive-date=October 4, 2014\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.wiumlie.no/en Personal homepage of H\u00e5kon W. Lie]\n*[http://www.w3.org/People/howcome/ Old homepage at W3C]\n*[http://www.w3.org/People/howcome/p/cascade.html The initial CSS proposal]\n*[http:/